POD1000000005_S0000327	or how fast fashion is even supposed to work.
POD1000000005_S0000328	I figured Robin Gavon could help.
POD1000000005_S0000329	In addition to reporting on the runways of Paris and New York, Givhan often writes about what fashion says about how we live now.
POD1000000005_S0000330	And she thinks a lot about fast fashion and its impact on our culture, aesthetically, socially, and environmentally.
POD1000000005_S0000331	Surprisingly, she isn't totally down on fast fashion.
POD1000000005_S0000332	I do think that fast fashion has kind of allowed everyone to have access to aesthetically thoughtful clothing.
POD1000000005_S0000333	Doesn't mean we're all dressing better though.
POD1000000005_S0000334	Notice I said to have access to it.
POD1000000005_S0000336	In a way, Gavon says, fast fashion is kind of brilliant when it's done right.
POD1000000005_S0000337	For the vast majority of people, they're not going into the designer boutique.
POD1000000005_S0000338	they're going into a department store or a mass merchant.
POD1000000005_S0000339	And, you know, those stores look at trend reports and they look at what's on the runway and part of their great skill in both marketing and manufacturing is being able to take those ideas and turn them around at just a rapid-fire pace and get them into stores.
POD1000000005_S0000340	And there isn't just one delivery that happens at the beginning of a season. No, no.
POD1000000005_S0000341	It's a constant stream of newness.
POD1000000005_S0000342	And when I say constant, I mean like every two weeks for some of these places.
POD1000000005_S0000343	So, Gavon says that, at its best, fast fashion means that new stylish clothes aren't just for fancies with the cash to shop haute couture.
POD1000000005_S0000344	But I'm going to let you in on a little secret.
POD1000000005_S0000345	It is impossible for clothing designers to go from original idea to brand spanking new product on the rack in two weeks.
POD1000000005_S0000346	especially not at the volume that Forever 21 needed to fill all of their bazillion stores.
POD1000000005_S0000347	So the company had to find some shortcuts.
POD1000000005_S0000348	Copying other designers' ideas was part of Forever 21's business model from the beginning.
POD1000000005_S0000349	Susan Scafidi is the founder of the Fashion Law Institute at Fordham University, and she basically invented the field of fashion law.
POD1000000005_S0000350	And she'll be the first one to tell you that while Forever 21's practice of copying other designers' ideas isn't a cute look, it's generally totally legal.
POD1000000005_S0000351	Fashion is not recognized as an art form in the United States.
POD1000000005_S0000352	so it doesn't get copyright protection, in large part because a hundred years ago, the Copyright Office decided that fashion, no matter how fanciful, was utilitarian.
POD1000000005_S0000353	Only a couple areas of fashion are protected from copying.
POD1000000005_S0000354	We have a tiny bit of copyright protection, at least since the 1960s, for two-dimensional elements of fashion, things like fabric prints or lace designs.
POD1000000005_S0000355	Over on the patent side, we've had historically a little bit of protection for some functional elements of fashion. Things like zippers and Velcro and Kevlar and space suits or hazmat suits.
POD1000000005_S0000356	And then at the end of the day, what fashion really has to rely on is trademark protection.
POD1000000005_S0000357	that is, protection for the logo or label.
POD1000000005_S0000358	So basically the polo pony on your chest or the giant double G on your belt buckle, those are protected.
POD1000000005_S0000359	The design of the shirt and belt themselves are not. Original prints are generally also protected.
POD1000000005_S0000360	While there aren't a ton of copyright and trademark protections for fashion in the US,
POD1000000005_S0000361	Forever 21 has still found itself involved in many, many, many intellectual property lawsuits. Scafidi says they're one of the most egregious offenders in the game.
POD1000000005_S0000362	Gucci, Puma, Adidas, Anna Sui, Diane von Furstenberg, and Gwen Stefani have all pursued legal action against Forever 21, alleging various forms of copyright infringement.
POD1000000005_S0000363	Many smaller brands have also claimed their prints or designs were ripped off by the mega retailer.
POD1000000005_S0000364	But most didn't have the resources to go against a multi-billion dollar mammoth.
POD1000000005_S0000365	And Scafidi says fast fashion brands like Forever 21 bank on that.
POD1000000005_S0000366	A certain amount of copying is baked into the business model of every fashion company.
POD1000000005_S0000367	The only question is how literally they're copying and how much they're changing it up.
POD1000000005_S0000368	In Forever 21's case, they'd often barely bother to change anything about the original design they were ripping off.
POD1000000005_S0000369	And some of their fabric prints were just a straight cut and copy job.
POD1000000005_S0000370	And maybe on the back end, you get caught and have to pay out the occasional settlement or pay some legal fees.
POD1000000005_S0000371	but usually that's cheaper than actually hiring designers and engaging in innovative product research.
POD1000000005_S0000372	Copying clothing designs hasn't been Forever 21's only questionable move.
POD1000000005_S0000373	In 2001, a workers advocacy center filed a lawsuit on behalf of employees who said they were made to work insane hours for way less than minimum wage.
POD1000000005_S0000374	In 2012, the U.S. Department of Labor sued the retailer for failing to pay federal minimum wage to its manufacturers and contractors.
POD1000000005_S0000375	And in 2019, pop star Ariana Grande slapped Forever 21 with a $10 million lawsuit.
POD1000000005_S0000376	The company used a model in this ad campaign that looked an awful lot like Ariana Grande.
POD1000000005_S0000377	she claims they did this to confuse consumers that she had endorsed them.
POD1000000005_S0000378	And that Ariana Grande look-alike was me. Just kidding.
POD1000000005_S0000379	A behemoth like Forever 21 rarely fails because of one misstep.
POD1000000005_S0000380	How did it falter? Let us count the ways.
POD1000000005_S0000381	How about routine legal troubles? Leasing too much expensive retail space, screwy merchandising that gummed up their supply chain, and no traditional board of directors to pump the brakes.
POD1000000005_S0000382	And with retail moving more and more online, Forever 21's weak e-commerce game didn't help matters.
POD1000000005_S0000383	In recent years, there's been one other major issue tugging at Forever 21's fallacy hem. Sustainability. Because sustainable it ain't.
POD1000000005_S0000384	I wonder is fast fashion, if we're talking about sustainability, like is that just as bad as it can get?
POD1000000005_S0000385	Well, I'm hesitant to say the worst, but I would be hard-pressed to think of another realm of the fashion industry that is as bad.
POD1000000005_S0000386	Because fast fashion has as its fundamental purpose
POD1000000005_S0000387	quick disposability.
POD1000000005_S0000388	You know the $25 handbag that is a knockoff of some you know item that came down the runway.
POD1000000005_S0000389	that is really meant to be used for a few months and then chucked into the trash, well, that's going to end up in a landfill.
POD1000000005_S0000390	as opposed to, say, an Hermes handbag that is the price of a small car.
POD1000000005_S0000391	That's not getting tossed out.
POD1000000005_S0000392	That's going in a safe deposit box as insurance for the apocalypse.
POD1000000005_S0000393	Sustainability in fashion isn't just about buying more durable, classic handbags.
POD1000000005_S0000394	The rise of online consignment shopping, as well as clothing rental startups like Rent the Runway, means consumers are increasingly trying to buy used and own less stuff.
POD1000000005_S0000395	A clothing brand that banks on disposability is not long for this new world.
POD1000000005_S0000396	By September 2019, it had all become just too much for Forever 21.
POD1000000005_S0000397	The company, built by immigrants from a single storefront in LA into a $4 billion colossus, filed for bankruptcy.
