POD1000000013_S0000010	and it's great to be on this innovative program, Radio Ombudsman.
POD1000000013_S0000011	Where was I born? I was born in Belfast, Northern Ireland.
POD1000000013_S0000012	I was born into a large family. I was the youngest of a family of six.
POD1000000013_S0000013	West Belfast in the 1960s when I was born was a place of much turmoil.
POD1000000013_S0000014	and my early
POD1000000013_S0000016	Early childhood adult life and into my time at university was very much a time of conflict in Northern Ireland.
POD1000000013_S0000017	I came from a very religious background where values were very important.
POD1000000013_S0000018	So there was a willingness and a desire on the part of my mum and dad to bring us up regardless, to respect everybody and to respect everyone's views and religion.
POD1000000013_S0000020	That's interesting and that really anticipates the follow-up question which is what do you learn and take from those awful situations?
POD1000000013_S0000021	The need for fairness is very important, part of communities getting on together.
POD1000000013_S0000022	If one community feels they've been dealt with unfairly, or indeed one individual or group of individuals, that that is potentially destabilising for society and for that community.
POD1000000013_S0000023	So I realised very early on something that I think is probably part of my nature, which is this desire for fairness.
POD1000000013_S0000025	Does that explain why you took a law degree?
POD1000000013_S0000026	In part. One of the things that I've spoken about openly is the fact that I was in a convent school.
POD1000000013_S0000027	and I was, there was a particular day I was called out at assembly.
POD1000000013_S0000028	I was 12, 13 and I was hugely humiliated and embarrassed by the fact that I was being accused of stealing another girl's gym shoes when I hadn't.
POD1000000013_S0000029	It was a mistake and that mistake came out, but I remember that feeling.
