POD1000000013_S0000064	Dr. Frohley, yeah, he's been a huge support to me throughout my career and a mentor.
POD1000000013_S0000065	And yes, legendary.
POD1000000013_S0000066	We were talking earlier today about leadership and his famous phrase on leadership is, I am their leader, which way did they go?
POD1000000013_S0000068	So it's kind of, you know, to be a leader you need to have followers.
POD1000000013_S0000069	Absolutely.
POD1000000013_S0000070	Okay, so for our English listeners and for those in the United States, Northern Ireland is obviously unique politically and socially.
POD1000000013_S0000071	But I don't think that many of us have a great deal of understanding of how this must have impacted on your work as an ombudsman.
POD1000000013_S0000072	Could you say a little bit about that?
POD1000000013_S0000073	Well I think because the first Ombudsman's Office in Northern Ireland was created in 1969, so we are celebrating our 50th anniversary year this year.
POD1000000013_S0000074	It was created to deal with complaints of discrimination in housing, employment, particularly in local government.
POD1000000013_S0000075	I think that the genesis of the idea for an ombudsman was to bring fairness to the citizen.
POD1000000013_S0000076	And I think that's really been always a key element of the work of the office.
POD1000000013_S0000077	I mean we feel very, very strongly that we are in the justice business, that it is about being fair.
POD1000000013_S0000078	And not only being fair to complainants or people who feel that public services have failed them, but being fair to those who are wrongly criticised or wrongly blamed.
POD1000000013_S0000079	Because I think the role of an Ombudsman is also to provide vindication when things have gone right.
POD1000000013_S0000080	What about the impact of sectarianism on your work, both inside the office and externally as ombudsman?
POD1000000013_S0000081	Well, I have a workforce who believe totally, my staff totally believe in fairness and equality.
POD1000000013_S0000082	and it doesn't matter who complains to the office, it doesn't matter who complains or what the nature of the complaint is, that we're going to deal with it.
POD1000000013_S0000083	But I suppose where the area which is most challenging is in my role as Local Government Standards Commissioner, where I myself have been accused of sectarianism.
POD1000000013_S0000084	because I was adjudicating on a particular councillor from a particular part of the unionist community.
POD1000000013_S0000085	So there is that added layer of not only wanting to do things right, to make the right decision, but being aware that no matter what that decision is, it might please one side or the other.
POD1000000013_S0000086	So to be accused of sectarianism was a huge hurt for me because that's not part of my values or my staff values.
POD1000000013_S0000087	I mean that's a big issue because it affects you personally.
POD1000000013_S0000088	How do you deal with that? Because you're a very resilient, tough person, but even that must be hard to deal with.
POD1000000013_S0000089	Well first of all I've got huge support from my deputy in the senior management team who reassured me that of course this isn't true and you know it isn't true and we know it isn't true
POD1000000013_S0000090	But I think what was difficult was the impact on my family and how they felt
POD1000000013_S0000091	My husband was angry and my children were unhappy about it.
POD1000000013_S0000092	How did it affect me? I learned that you can deal with this sort of criticism.
POD1000000013_S0000093	and I learned that behind it all you've got to be sure that you're making the right decision.
POD1000000013_S0000094	I can remember a few weeks ago when I was savagely criticised on Twitter.
