POD1000000013_S0000098	I think you do need to consult.
POD1000000013_S0000099	What's been helpful has been part of the Ombudsman community's response to this is the personal support you've given me, Rob. I was able to talk to you about it.
POD1000000013_S0000100	I was able to talk to others like the current police ombudsman for Northern Ireland who said leave it alone.
POD1000000013_S0000101	just leave it because if you do anything, if you take any legal action, then it's merely going to provide more oxygen.
POD1000000013_S0000102	Yeah.
POD1000000013_S0000103	Doesn't stop it being difficult
POD1000000013_S0000104	No.
POD1000000013_S0000105	personally difficult and that's where the resilience comes in.
POD1000000013_S0000106	that's where you've got to get up the next morning, go into work and your staff have got to see that a low might affect you inside.
POD1000000013_S0000107	that you're going to continue to lead the office and do the job.
POD1000000013_S0000108	Thank you, that's important.
POD1000000013_S0000109	Let's just move that on a little bit and talk about human rights issues in relation to the actions of public services.
POD1000000013_S0000110	You launched a brilliant human rights manual which sets out an approach that many ombudsmen in Europe take.
POD1000000013_S0000111	but is not particularly prevalent in the United Kingdom, about actions that can be taken by an ombudsman.
POD1000000013_S0000112	Could you tell us a bit more about how you created this?
POD1000000013_S0000113	Well, it was created jointly with the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission and it started as ever, as All Good Ideas, with a conversation.
POD1000000013_S0000114	and it was a conversation between the Human Rights Commission and our office around the sort of casework that we were dealing with.
POD1000000013_S0000115	We were dealing with issues like the Roma community feeling discriminated because they didn't have access to health services.
POD1000000013_S0000116	We're dealing with issues of consent, patients not giving consent to interventions and the family and the patient feeling excluded from the decision making.
POD1000000013_S0000117	but also we realised that Ombudsman and Human Rights Commissions and or equality bodies are actually doing the same job.
POD1000000013_S0000118	So my style is to move on from the conversation and actually have a product.
POD1000000013_S0000119	and the product was How to do this manual for Ombudsman Staff.
POD1000000013_S0000120	how to introduce human rights principles into ombudsman investigations.
POD1000000013_S0000121	and it's quite simple and it's not about Strasbourg jurisprudence.
POD1000000013_S0000122	That's the beauty of it I think for non-lawyers, for non-legal staff, that they're very simple principles.
POD1000000013_S0000123	participation, a person affected by a decision by whatever public service provider, be it health, be it housing, be it local government, that they have to be able to participate.
POD1000000013_S0000124	They have to be given enough information to participate effectively in the decision making.
POD1000000013_S0000125	So there's the principle of empowerment, giving information.
POD1000000013_S0000126	There's the principle of non-discrimination and being treated equally and fairly and having equal access.
POD1000000013_S0000127	And ultimately the fourth principle of the human rights based approach is accountability and that's what we ombudsmen do.
POD1000000013_S0000128	We hold public services to account.
POD1000000013_S0000129	And would you say that you've been able to hold public services more to account as a result of having that human rights based approach?
POD1000000013_S0000130	Yes, I think maladministration is a tool.
POD1000000013_S0000131	but I think that having a human rights lens allows you to look more closely at a way so much from the process as to how the process actually affects the individuals and affects the individuals rights.
POD1000000013_S0000132	So to give you an example, we had a case where a young man died as a result of a routine ear operation.
POD1000000013_S0000133	And it was a one in a million reaction to a titanium implant, to the packing around a titanium implant.
POD1000000013_S0000134	The point being his mum and dad believed that he wasn't consented for that intervention.
POD1000000013_S0000135	and that that was unfair and affected his human rights.
POD1000000013_S0000136	The coroner had refused to undertake an inquest saying it didn't affect his human rights.
POD1000000013_S0000137	When it came to my office, we identified the human rights principle of participation.
POD1000000013_S0000138	If I know what is going to happen to me, if I'm told of the risks, instead of someone else making the decision for me, then my human rights have been respected.
POD1000000013_S0000139	When I drew that out in the investigation report, I was able to come to a conclusion that there was a conflict between the experts
POD1000000013_S0000140	Some said, well, another consultant might not have done the implant. Another said they would have gone ahead with the implant.
POD1000000013_S0000141	But actually, the human rights based approach meant that I thought about the individual and that they hadn't been properly consented.
POD1000000013_S0000142	The result, not only did the family get an investigation report identifying this issue, but they were able to go to the coroner.
POD1000000013_S0000143	He's commenced an inquest.
POD1000000013_S0000144	Now, you have two things in Northern Ireland that we don't have. You have...
POD1000000013_S0000145	partly because of your own excellence in bringing it about. You have an integrated public service ombudsman scheme and you have the power of own initiative.
POD1000000013_S0000146	Are these valuable additions to the way ombudsmen should be working?
POD1000000013_S0000147	I do believe in the one-stop shop model.
POD1000000013_S0000148	The Public Services Ombudsman in Northern Ireland looks at complaints about government departments, statutory agencies, local government, health and social care, education, schools, universities, colleges,
POD1000000013_S0000149	I think that can be challenging for staff but I believe that they enjoy the variety.
POD1000000013_S0000150	But I also believe that an ombudsman, ombudsman principles of good administration apply across sectors.
POD1000000013_S0000151	So yes, I think it is of value.
POD1000000013_S0000152	I think having one place to go to to seek redress for injustice is important.
POD1000000013_S0000153	If people don't want to go to court, there's an ombudsman there that can look at the full range.
POD1000000013_S0000154	Own Initiative is for me an essential tool of every Ombudsman's toolkit.
POD1000000013_S0000155	When you look internationally,
POD1000000013_S0000156	You look at ombudsman in Australia, you look at ombudsman in Europe, you look at ombudsman in North America, the Ontario ombudsman, the rest Western Australian ombudsman.
POD1000000013_S0000157	They all have own initiative. They've all had own initiative from the start.
POD1000000013_S0000158	The Irish Ombudsman Act that was created in 1980 had its own initiative there as well as dealing with individual complaints.
POD1000000013_S0000159	For me, an Ombudsman without own initiative can't fulfil the mandate of improving public services for many, not just for the individual.
POD1000000013_S0000160	So you would have no hesitation about introducing an initiative. It's essential.
POD1000000013_S0000161	Not at all. I was lucky to be part of the development of the Public Service Ombudsman Act.
POD1000000013_S0000162	and had an opportunity to persuade officials who were perhaps nervous about the Ombudsman having own initiative powers.
POD1000000013_S0000163	that really this was something that actually could benefit public services in the end.
POD1000000013_S0000164	See, it is about prevention.
POD1000000013_S0000165	You can deal with numerous complaints but never get to the core issue, whereas Own Initiative allows you to tackle the core issue of systemic failing.
POD1000000013_S0000166	Well, I agree with that.
POD1000000013_S0000167	And that's why I think it's necessary for us to have the reform that you've already been operating for nearly three years now.
POD1000000013_S0000168	Yes, and now the Welsh Ombudsman is about to get that also.
POD1000000013_S0000169	I believe Scottish Ombudsman would like to own initiative.
POD1000000013_S0000170	So if that happens, it means that the devolved administrations have it.
POD1000000013_S0000171	and the first ever Ombudsman in these islands, the Parliamentary Ombudsman, has not.
POD1000000013_S0000172	and I think that's missing an opportunity to improve public services for the citizen.
POD1000000013_S0000173	As you move on from the Public Service Ombudsman, what are you most proud of?
POD1000000013_S0000174	Is it bringing the whole thing together, the integration of the various systems?
POD1000000013_S0000175	Well I think the legislation that allowed the Public Services Ombudsman as a one-stop shop for complaints about public services
POD1000000013_S0000176	but also being able to bring in local government standards.
POD1000000013_S0000177	because Northern Ireland, which was the only part in Europe, didn't have a mandatory code of conduct for local representatives.
POD1000000013_S0000178	That was introduced in 2014.
POD1000000013_S0000179	and my office and I as Deputy Ombudsman, now Ombudsman, have been key to establishing an investigative and judicative function in Northern Ireland.
POD1000000013_S0000180	that is a unique model but I believe operates very well.
POD1000000013_S0000181	That is not work that is outwith ombudsmanry.
POD1000000013_S0000182	Because for me ethical standards, values, fairness, they're all part of good governance. And that's where we ombudsmen are.
POD1000000013_S0000183	I mean, we're not a court. We don't declare, don't make binding decisions.
POD1000000013_S0000184	but nevertheless we can influence with the recommendations that we make and with setting standards.
POD1000000013_S0000186	Now, we asked colleagues on Twitter to send in questions.
POD1000000013_S0000187	And we had a set of questions from one dissatisfied user of the service under your predecessor, who felt that she hadn't been treated fairly by the system.
POD1000000013_S0000188	What can you say to people in that position?
POD1000000013_S0000189	I think that many people misunderstand the role of the Ombudsman.
POD1000000013_S0000190	They believe that the Ombudsman is there particularly to advocate for them and their particular issue.
POD1000000013_S0000191	Ombudsmen are impartial so a finding of no failure can be disappointing to a complainant.
POD1000000013_S0000192	And I believe that was the case in relation to the particular individual that you refer to.
POD1000000013_S0000193	of the previous ombudsman did not find in her favour and that can be disappointing.
POD1000000013_S0000194	But then you've got to understand that there are the other side of that is that perhaps a clinician or a member of health staff who has been criticized receives a message that actually they did it right.
POD1000000013_S0000195	But there are many occasions in which complainants don't agree with my decisions.
POD1000000013_S0000197	But I still have to decide fairly, ensure there's a fair process, ensure everyone gets an opportunity to comment and report on the matter.
POD1000000013_S0000198	That's what an Ombudsman does.
POD1000000013_S0000199	Yes, it's difficult sometimes to explain that while the complaint belongs to the complainant, the decision belongs to the ombudsman, providing it's evidence-based and rigorous.
POD1000000013_S0000200	provided it's evidence-based and rigorous but also I believe fair.
POD1000000013_S0000201	I think you have to give everyone an opportunity, including those who are criticized.
POD1000000013_S0000202	but this issue about it's an ombudsman decision while you bring your complaint.
POD1000000013_S0000203	it is the Ombudsman's decision, has actually been written into the legislation that I refer to.
POD1000000013_S0000204	which is that under the Northern Irish Ombudsman legislation, the 2016 Act, that I mentioned, that even if a complainant withdrew their complaint, I can still investigate.
POD1000000013_S0000205	So it is the Ombudsman's investigation.
POD1000000013_S0000206	Now you've been with the office in Northern Ireland for 10 years.
POD1000000013_S0000207	It's a long time. Will you have any regrets about...
