POD1000000015_S0000001	Hello, this is Rob Barrons here, welcoming you to another episode of Radio Ombudsman.
POD1000000015_S0000002	I'm delighted to say that my guest today is Rosemary Agnew, Scottish Public Services Ombudsman.
POD1000000015_S0000003	Rosemary took up the post of Ombudsman around the same time as I did in 2017 and before this she was the Scottish Information Commissioner.
POD1000000015_S0000004	She has a wealth of experience in public service which we'll come on to.
POD1000000015_S0000005	She has developed the idea of a Complaint Standards Authority in Scotland, which is something that I want to ask her about.
POD1000000015_S0000006	Rosemary, you're very welcome. Thank you for coming.
POD1000000015_S0000007	Now, we like to start each episode by hearing a bit about our guests and where they come from.
POD1000000015_S0000008	So can you tell us a bit about your early life and the values you got from that?
POD1000000015_S0000009	I am hugely lucky. I come from a very loving family.
POD1000000015_S0000010	I have four younger brothers, so I think it fair to say that issues about equality were probably in there before I even knew the word.
POD1000000015_S0000011	But my family are military families, so I travelled around as a child.
POD1000000015_S0000012	And mostly I'd say what I got from them was a real strong moral compass.
POD1000000015_S0000013	not drilled into me, must do this, mustn't do that, but about treating people with respect, particularly when we were travelling to new places and meeting new people for the first time.
POD1000000015_S0000014	And I think that that moral and ethical background, not called that then,
POD1000000015_S0000015	It was just try and be a good person, tell the truth, do your homework on time, all these sorts of things probably instilled in me a strong work ethic.
POD1000000015_S0000016	but it also instilled in me a very deep level of caring for people.
POD1000000015_S0000017	Mm-hmm.
POD1000000015_S0000018	because I was able to see over the whole of my life still a whole range of people who have different starts in life, different opportunities.
POD1000000015_S0000019	And I think within that I've developed my own sense of justice.
POD1000000015_S0000020	and I'm hugely grateful to my parents, they're lovely people.
POD1000000015_S0000021	And I even get on with my brothers occasionally.
POD1000000015_S0000023	When you were travelling around as part of the military family, was that difficult? Did you feel like an outsider?
POD1000000015_S0000024	Yes and no to outsider.
POD1000000015_S0000025	I went to a lot of schools, so you had to learn to make friends quickly and you couldn't have a long lead in time, if you like.
POD1000000015_S0000026	Because I lived a lot of time in military accommodation, that was like a big family of itself, because you tended to be with people who were in a similar situation.
POD1000000015_S0000027	But mostly I suppose I just saw it as a big sense of adventure.
POD1000000015_S0000028	It doesn't suit all, but for me it was great because I just moved around, had a whole wealth of experience which I don't think I'd have got in any other way.
POD1000000015_S0000029	What did you study at university?
POD1000000015_S0000030	Well, my main claim to fame, I think, sitting here in Manchester, is the thing that I'm probably most pleased with, is my MBA from Manchester Business School.
