POD1000000015_S0000035	They're very famous alumni from that MBA. I think Vincent Campany is a graduate of that scheme. Did you know him?
POD1000000015_S0000036	No, I didn't. In fact, I don't think that any of my cohort are names that have come up to prominence
POD1000000015_S0000037	but have all gone on to do good things, some very interesting things.
POD1000000015_S0000038	I for myself, because I was public sector at the time and I've remained public sector for most of the time since then, perhaps have a slightly different view of it.
POD1000000015_S0000039	because I was very deliberate in not always going down public sector routes for study or public sector modules because I wanted to learn more about different sorts of thinking.
POD1000000015_S0000040	When did you decide what sort of career you wanted?
POD1000000015_S0000041	I'm yet to meet an ombudsman who decided they wanted to be an ombudsman.
POD1000000015_S0000042	Yep.
POD1000000015_S0000043	I think
POD1000000015_S0000044	I can own up to that.
POD1000000015_S0000045	It's fair to say that
POD1000000015_S0000046	I went to work, I was working in China, lecturing in business and economics, and I needed a job when I got back.
POD1000000015_S0000047	So I thought, oh, they're advertising for investigators at the local government ombudsman. That'll do for a while. It'll pay the mortgage until I get something else.
POD1000000015_S0000048	and I've pretty much never left ombudsmaning or information commissioning since.
POD1000000015_S0000049	And I think what it was, was I found a job that I enjoyed, it was challenging, but actually fitted in with my value system.
POD1000000015_S0000050	Right, and you've had a very distinguished and varied career. You were the Scottish Information Commissioner.
POD1000000015_S0000051	Now what was the highlight of that before you came to the Scottish Public Service Ombudsman?
POD1000000015_S0000052	I think it's hard to say what highlight is in terms of being the information commissioner
POD1000000015_S0000053	There are a number of things that I did that I was really proud of in a good way.
POD1000000015_S0000054	One of them was, it sounds very trivial, but we established a portal for the uploading of Freedom of Information statistics from public bodies in Scotland.
POD1000000015_S0000055	And what that means is now there is a three or four year database of the number of Freedom of Information requests and the outcome of them for the whole of Scotland.
POD1000000015_S0000056	that we can look at trends, we can look at developments.
POD1000000015_S0000057	And that actually, for me, was a highlight because I didn't necessarily have the enforcement power to do it.
POD1000000015_S0000058	It was done through cooperation and co-working with public bodies.
POD1000000015_S0000059	The other couple of things that really stick in my mind was very, very early on a particular decision I made
POD1000000015_S0000060	which was telling the Scottish government they had to disclose whether they had taken legal advice about Scotland's position with Europe.
POD1000000015_S0000061	should they gain independence, because it was the time of the independence referendum.
POD1000000015_S0000062	Yeah.
POD1000000015_S0000063	And why that's particularly interesting is it was a very big issue, I think, in the independence referendum and nobody, I think, could have foreseen where we are now.
POD1000000015_S0000064	The final one, which I think I'll talk about more when we talk maybe about some of the ombudsman powers,
POD1000000015_S0000065	was about a different way of intervening in relation to good and poor practice with Scottish public bodies.
POD1000000015_S0000066	You're English, I think. Is that correct?
POD1000000015_S0000067	Yes.
POD1000000015_S0000068	So has there ever been an issue about you holding prestigious and important jobs in Scotland?
POD1000000015_S0000069	about an English person having that responsibility.
POD1000000015_S0000070	No, I have a Scottish name, Agnew is a Scottish name and I am married to somebody from Scottish descent.
POD1000000015_S0000071	I was once asked by a journalist, was I happy that I had adopted Scotland as my home?
POD1000000015_S0000072	And I think it's fair to say the answer reflected how I felt, which was I'm eternally grateful that Scotland has adopted me as somebody who lives there and does these things within Scotland.
POD1000000015_S0000073	But no, it's a different experience to being in England, but I've never, not to my face anyway, ever had an issue with being English.
POD1000000015_S0000074	That's good to hear.
POD1000000015_S0000075	Now, can we just talk a bit about the Scottish Ombudsman, which you took up post nearly three years ago?
POD1000000015_S0000076	The devolved ombudsmen are different from the UK ombudsmen.
POD1000000015_S0000077	Because they're more modern, they've adopted legislation to make them more relevant to developing situations. And you have more powers than the UK Ombudsman has.
POD1000000015_S0000078	What's it like being the head of an integrated public service ombudsman? Is that a good thing?
POD1000000015_S0000079	Yes, I think it's a very good thing because you have a different sort of insight, you have a different sort of overview and sectors do vary.
POD1000000015_S0000080	There is variance because they're working to different regulations. It makes your job very varied also.
POD1000000015_S0000081	I think one of the challenges with it though is if you work in a specific sector
POD1000000015_S0000082	So if I reflect on local government ombudsman, you became much more immersed in the technicalities of local government.
POD1000000015_S0000083	When you work across sectors, what we find is, particularly a personal reflection is, I have to do a bit more digging round to find out about how the sectors operate in Scotland.
POD1000000015_S0000084	And I also rely quite a lot on professional advice, particularly for health and social work.
POD1000000015_S0000085	So we don't necessarily develop through experience of volume of cases the same experience that you do when you're perhaps looking at
POD1000000015_S0000086	one particular area of public service.
POD1000000015_S0000087	But the other thing that I think reflects with myself and the Welsh and the Northern Ireland Ombudsman is because the population of the country is smaller,
POD1000000015_S0000088	and the country itself has a different sort of structure to it.
POD1000000015_S0000089	you often get given things to do that are not necessarily what you would expect an ombudsman to be doing.
POD1000000015_S0000090	So as well as complaint handling and the complaint standards, we also have duties for, with the final stage of appeal, for a benefit Scottish Welfare Fund.
POD1000000015_S0000091	And then when you look at Northern Ireland and Wales, they also have other things that are different.
POD1000000015_S0000092	And I think that is as much a challenge as anything, because it's almost like running two completely different functions, but trying to have an integrated organisation.
POD1000000015_S0000093	Okay, so you rely on professional advice, but there must also be a challenge for your case handlers to deal with the width of functions that they come up with.
POD1000000015_S0000094	Are you divided according to the sectors or do people have
POD1000000015_S0000096	multitasking to do.
POD1000000015_S0000097	They have multitasking to do and they are an incredible set of people, my investigators.
POD1000000015_S0000098	But I think one of the things that drives us and that is probably the uniting thing is very much about values.
POD1000000015_S0000099	And I think like most ombudsman organisations I've ever come across, it's a fairly unique workforce I would say.
POD1000000015_S0000100	because you ask anybody why we're there and very rarely will you deviate far from because we want to make a difference, because we want to see improvement, because we want to make things better.
POD1000000015_S0000101	So yes, it's a challenge having the scope and we have some individuals who may have a background in a particular area, but we don't have specialists.
POD1000000015_S0000102	OK, now what you have, which we don't have, is the status of being a Complaint Standards Authority.
POD1000000015_S0000103	Could you explain to our listeners briefly what that means?
POD1000000015_S0000104	Briefly, what it means is the Ombudsman is responsible for setting a model complaints handling process that all Scottish bodies must follow.
POD1000000015_S0000105	And we then, with that, have a duty to monitor performance in relation to complaint handling and combined with some of our other powers, duty to enforce good practice to report on it.
POD1000000015_S0000106	Now that sounds, you know, oh that's nice, model complaints handling.
POD1000000015_S0000107	But what it means in practice is with some slight variations by sector, because different sectors have slightly different needs,
POD1000000015_S0000108	It means that anybody making a complaint to a public body in Scotland and about a public body in Scotland is basically making a complaint under the same set of standards.
POD1000000015_S0000109	So the model complaints handling process says that the first stage of a complaint you must try and respond within five working days to resolve it.
POD1000000015_S0000110	very big focus on resolution.
POD1000000015_S0000111	If you can't or the person is not satisfied, you can then take another 20 working days to look at it in more detail.
POD1000000015_S0000112	If it's something that you think you need more than 20 days for, then talk to the complainer about that.
POD1000000015_S0000113	But it essentially means that if somebody does not receive a response or doesn't receive a response in time, they get to the ombudsman a lot quicker than they might otherwise do.
POD1000000015_S0000114	The other benefit of the model complaints handling process is that there is a very strong focus on learning from complaints.
POD1000000015_S0000115	So the standards that go with this, which incidentally I have to lay before the Scottish Parliament the standards,
POD1000000015_S0000116	They also have a very strong bent on learning from complaints.
POD1000000015_S0000117	And I think that's an area where we can perhaps develop more in how we hold public bodies to account to demonstrate that learning.
POD1000000015_S0000118	because like our complaints, the model complaints handling, we have to show that there is an impact and that there is value to individuals and to public services as a whole.
POD1000000015_S0000119	I think for me the most valuable thing about it though is it gives you an opportunity to work with public bodies, not always in opposition to them.
POD1000000015_S0000120	which with the best will in the world, however much you try a resolution or a sort of discursive way of looking at complaints,
POD1000000015_S0000121	Once a complaint has reached the ombudsman, it is in many ways adversarial, whether you want it to be or not.
POD1000000015_S0000122	But when you're talking about complaint handling as a whole, you have an opportunity actually to help public bodies.
POD1000000015_S0000123	and encourage them to get better at complaint handling, which you hope means they get better at learning from complaints.
POD1000000015_S0000124	which means people get the right service the first time.
POD1000000015_S0000125	I don't think we'll ever eliminate complaints but certainly it hopefully will make it a more productive experience.
POD1000000015_S0000126	Now I'm a full supporter of what you're doing
POD1000000015_S0000127	I'm a burglar of your practice when I was the higher education ombudsman I stole it hook line and sinker to use in English universities
POD1000000015_S0000128	The idea that they could resolve complaints within five days was anathema to them. They wouldn't have that. We ended up with 90.
POD1000000015_S0000129	but nevertheless they did it.
POD1000000015_S0000130	But the difference and the radical nature of what you do is effectively you are a regulator now.
POD1000000015_S0000131	Whereas ombudsmen have traditionally always said we rely on our moral authority, not on a coercive power.
POD1000000015_S0000132	Has that made a difference or is it just words?
POD1000000015_S0000133	No, I don't think it makes, it's made a difference yet.
POD1000000015_S0000134	I also think I should add that I wasn't ombudsman when the Complaint Standard Authority came in.
POD1000000015_S0000135	Yeah.
POD1000000015_S0000136	And credit has to go to Jim Martin, my predecessor, for driving this.
POD1000000015_S0000137	Yep.
POD1000000015_S0000138	What he's left me as a legacy is something really good to develop and work with, which is what we're doing now.
POD1000000015_S0000139	Having been an information commissioner, which really is a regulatory function, your decision is binding or you go to court.
POD1000000015_S0000140	I think the concept of regulation probably hasn't crept into our thinking with complaint standards in quite the same way.
POD1000000015_S0000141	but it is something that we're currently developing but maybe not calling it regulation in the same way.
POD1000000015_S0000142	because one of the things that I would say learning from hindsight is that we took a very structured approach of rolling it out sector by sector, this model complaints handling.
POD1000000015_S0000143	And what that meant was it was a number of years before every public body in Scotland was following this.
POD1000000015_S0000144	So the NHS was the last, and that's been the last, I think, just coming up to the end of their second year.
POD1000000015_S0000145	If you compare that to the first, which was local government,
POD1000000015_S0000146	Local government now, a really high percentage of complaints get responded to in the first instance in the five working days.
POD1000000015_S0000147	I think from memory it's over 80% and that's really significant for complainers.
POD1000000015_S0000148	Now what we've been looking at in the last few months and we went live with in April is what we've called our support and intervention policy.
POD1000000015_S0000149	And this is a concept that I brought with me from being information commissioner.
POD1000000015_S0000150	And basically was looking at all the powers that you have as an ombudsman because the real value comes in the combination of them, not just the individual bits.
POD1000000015_S0000151	So when you look at the powers to set complaint handling processes to take action if complaint handling falls short, you then look at other things like your information gathering powers,
POD1000000015_S0000152	We've created a framework which sets out what our powers are and within that what we are going to do to either support or if necessary intervene.
POD1000000015_S0000153	because when we, for example, a simple example, we might see a number of complaints from a public body where the final response that they give to the complainer does not signpost the ombudsman.
POD1000000015_S0000154	They have a duty to do that under the complaints handling process.
POD1000000015_S0000155	So we are getting better at our own intelligence, we're logging feedback, recommendations, observations from what we see in complaints.
POD1000000015_S0000156	So if we spot something like that, we might just, well, my investigators, my complaints reviewers will let the public body know.
POD1000000015_S0000157	we give feedback in decisions.
POD1000000015_S0000158	If we keep seeing that, we might give it more formal and say we spotted this a number of times.
POD1000000015_S0000159	But is there any help? We might offer to, say, share a template letter.
POD1000000015_S0000160	or if it's something different, perhaps go and give them some training if we've got the resource to do that.
POD1000000015_S0000161	But we set it out step by step at which point it becomes a management issue and senior managers might actually contact senior managers or chief executives.
POD1000000015_S0000162	The ultimate being we use the powers that the Ombudsman has to enforce and report.
POD1000000015_S0000164	very incremental and civilized. But do you come across intransigence?
POD1000000015_S0000165	Well, it went live in April and so far we've not found intransigence.
POD1000000015_S0000166	And I think some of this is drawing on experience of
POD1000000015_S0000167	information commissioner that I'll give you a very simple example
POD1000000015_S0000168	similar powers to compel production of information for an investigation
POD1000000015_S0000169	and telling public bodies very formally, if you do not provide this, this and this by this date, I will report on this. I will take further action.
POD1000000015_S0000170	it can actually be treated as contempt of court in Scotland.
POD1000000015_S0000171	So you only need to make that clear that you're going to do it and to do it once and then report on it in your annual report.
POD1000000015_S0000172	and actually public bodies realise, I think, that you're being serious.
POD1000000015_S0000173	But we try to get to the point before that where you point out this is the value, particularly for the complainer of doing this.
POD1000000015_S0000174	So we're in early days, we haven't come across the real intransigence yet.
POD1000000015_S0000175	but I've no doubt that there'll be some there at some point.
POD1000000015_S0000176	but the word civilized is a good one and we will endeavor to be as civilized as we can but firm with it.
POD1000000015_S0000177	What is your report to the Scottish Parliament?
POD1000000015_S0000178	Yes.
POD1000000015_S0000179	What is your relationship like with that body?
POD1000000015_S0000180	I'd say it's pretty good in the sense of it's open, challenging and when I say friendly, I don't mean we're all friends. It's very professional in many ways.
POD1000000015_S0000181	So my main dealings are with the Scottish Parliamentary Corporate Body.
POD1000000015_S0000182	I get my funding through them, so we have contact with them on a fairly regular basis.
POD1000000015_S0000183	Each year I appear before the local government and communities committee to be held accountable for my annual reports.
POD1000000015_S0000184	so they'll ask me questions about our performance, about what we're doing.
POD1000000015_S0000185	I do appear before other committees as well, either in relation to other policies or in relation to other consultations that we've responded to.
POD1000000015_S0000186	I would say in Scotland that generally the Ombudsman is held in high regard and seen as being independent and impartial.
POD1000000015_S0000187	And probably the most telling evidence of this is we're taking on new powers next year.
POD1000000015_S0000188	This is about whistle blowing.
POD1000000015_S0000189	Yes, I'm taking on the wonderful title of Independent National Whistleblowing Officer for the NHS in Scotland.
POD1000000015_S0000190	Wow.
POD1000000015_S0000191	And the reason that we are taking on this function is because the government's public consultation, it was suggested it should be the ombudsman.
POD1000000015_S0000192	It's another good example of how in a smaller jurisdiction you get a number of different things.
POD1000000015_S0000193	but going back to Parliament, they have held me to account on things, but also where I have brought something to them in my committee appearances, they've also been quite supportive.
POD1000000015_S0000194	So one of my beefs about my legislation is complaints must be in writing unless there are special circumstances.
POD1000000015_S0000195	Now the problem with that is the onus is on the complainer to show special circumstances.
POD1000000015_S0000196	and it means you can't be as flexible in how you take complaints.
POD1000000015_S0000197	Yeah.
POD1000000015_S0000198	And I've been trying since I became ombudsman to have the legislation, it's secondary legislation, to say I can take complaints in any format.
