POD1000000021_S0000284	No other state does elections like Louisiana.
POD1000000021_S0000285	The credit for that, or the blame, belongs to Edwin Edwards.
POD1000000021_S0000286	The first time he ran for governor, Edwards had to compete in three separate races.
POD1000000021_S0000287	a closed Democratic primary, a Democratic runoff, and then the general election.
POD1000000021_S0000288	In the days when Democrats dominated Louisiana, that last race, against a Republican also-ran, was a pointless nuisance.
POD1000000021_S0000289	It was like winning the 100-meter dash at the Olympics, then having to out-sprint a kid pulled from the stands to get your gold medal.
POD1000000021_S0000290	And I didn't like that idea. I said, well, look, let's change it.
POD1000000021_S0000291	Everybody qualifies at the same time regardless of affiliation.
POD1000000021_S0000292	and everybody votes for anybody he or she wishes regardless of registration.
POD1000000021_S0000293	Louisiana's open primary system went into effect in 1975.
POD1000000021_S0000294	Edwards cruised to re-election that year, as the Republican Party didn't even field a candidate.
POD1000000021_S0000295	But in the Reagan years, the GOP surged throughout the South.
POD1000000021_S0000296	By 1991, the open primary was open in a way Edwards maybe hadn't anticipated.
POD1000000021_S0000297	It was a true two-party free-for-all.
POD1000000021_S0000298	Political writer John McGinnis had a name for the showdown between David Duke, Edwin Edwards, and Buddy Roemer.
POD1000000021_S0000299	I call this the race from hell.
POD1000000021_S0000300	You have three very angry men, candidates for governor, and the people aren't too happy either.
POD1000000021_S0000301	In the beginning, the race from hell wasn't exactly rollicking.
POD1000000021_S0000302	One reason for that was a package of campaign finance reforms, part of Buddy Roemer's good government agenda.
POD1000000021_S0000303	The new law limited individual contributions to $5,000 in major statewide races.
POD1000000021_S0000304	banned cash contributions of more than $100, and required that small cash donations be reported.
POD1000000021_S0000305	Duke could pass the bucket with impunity during his 1990 Senate campaign because that was a federal race.
POD1000000021_S0000306	But thanks to Romer the Revolutionary, Louisiana's guidelines on cash-giving were now stricter than the nation's.
POD1000000021_S0000307	Hamstrung by these new rules, Duke held fewer rallies as a candidate for governor than when he ran for the Senate. And Edwards' fundraising slowed to a trickle.
POD1000000021_S0000308	He'd raised $16 million during the 1983 governor's race.
POD1000000021_S0000309	In the 1991 primary, he brought in a little more than $1 million.
POD1000000021_S0000310	And Buddy Romer, he preferred staying in to going out to meet his public.
POD1000000021_S0000311	Romer had always been like this.
POD1000000021_S0000312	Raymond Strother saw it up close during the 1987 race.
POD1000000021_S0000313	He was sitting in the back of the campaign headquarters and reading novels, usually mystery novels, and he wouldn't go out and campaign.
POD1000000021_S0000314	We'd go to a restaurant to eat lunch and he would sit in the back of the restaurant in a corner with his back to the room.
POD1000000021_S0000315	so nobody would see him and recognize him and come over and start talking.
