POD1000000028_S0000041	But as complicated as their story would become, it all started with something simple.
POD1000000028_S0000043	It started with perfection.
POD1000000028_S0000045	At the 1976 Olympic Games in Montreal, 14-year-old Nadia Comaneci earned the first perfect 10 in Olympic gymnastics history.
POD1000000028_S0000046	And when the judges announced her score, the crowd erupted, but no one more so than Nadia's coach, Bella Caroli.
POD1000000028_S0000047	At 33 years old, Bella and Marta Caroli were just beginning their career as coaches. Outside of Romania, they were unknowns. But Bella was impossible to miss.
POD1000000028_S0000048	especially as the 6-foot-plus coach towered over his 4-foot-11, 86-pound protege.
POD1000000028_S0000050	Over the course of a single thrilling week, Nadia became the crowd favorite and an international star as she scored perfect 10 after perfect 10.
POD1000000028_S0000052	an unbelievable 7 perfect 10s all together. And in the individual all-around, Nadia won the gold medal, a first for Romania.
POD1000000028_S0000053	Finally Nadia comes up and does her incredible routine. That's where the crowd exploded. I mean that was explosion, explosion of support, explosion of love and excitement and I'm looking through the corner of my eyes.
POD1000000028_S0000054	And I see the Soviet team getting their stuff and they walk in out of the arena. I said, yes, yes, we got it.
POD1000000028_S0000055	Finally, after decades of dominance, a Romanian had beaten the Soviets.
POD1000000028_S0000056	In a way for some people this is the end of a love affair, the dethroning of the USSR gymnastic competition. Nadia Komanecha now takes over, 14 year old sprite of a girl.
POD1000000028_S0000057	But for Bela Karolyi and his wife and coaching partner Marta, there was something even greater at stake. The favor of the Romanian government.
POD1000000028_S0000060	It was late night, Romanian time, so I was watching before Tim Doctor and his wife, Marta's friend, and my wife. We watched on black and white TV.
POD1000000028_S0000062	My name is Geza Pozsar. That's the Hungarian pronunciation. In English it's like, Geza Pozsar. So, Geza Pozsar.
POD1000000028_S0000063	Geza Pozar was the choreographer for the Romanian national team.
POD1000000028_S0000064	He'd been working with Bela and Marta for years. He designed Nadia's floor routine and helped her train for this moment. But instead of watching from the sidelines with Bela and Marta, he was watching from home. Because the Romanian government wouldn't let him travel to Montreal.
POD1000000028_S0000065	because I didn't get the visa to go.
POD1000000028_S0000066	Gza had recently married a French woman and so the government didn't trust him to go to Canada and actually return to Romania.
POD1000000028_S0000068	From his living room in the small town of Onest, Gheza, like the rest of Romania, watch Nadia make history.
POD1000000028_S0000070	The whole town came out to the streets. It was like midnight. All of them, they come out and it was like carnival in Rio, you know? It was unbelievable. First of all, they get drunk, you know, that's the first thing. But everyone is so happy.
POD1000000028_S0000071	And that's a huge celebration, huge.
POD1000000028_S0000072	But this moment was bigger than just the party in those small town streets.
POD1000000028_S0000073	The whole world is in ecstasy, you know?
POD1000000028_S0000074	The whole world was in ecstasy. That's why Nadia's perfect tens and her gold medal were so important. They made Romania visible. A country that suddenly stood out from the rest of the communist bloc.
POD1000000028_S0000075	Nadia was a lovable figure, from a place the Western world saw as very grim.
POD1000000028_S0000076	Nadia was the diamond. She was the treasure of Romania. It was the best product Romania ever had. Nadia put Romania on the map. After Nadia, everybody knows that there is Romania.
POD1000000028_S0000078	During the Cold War, sports were a way for nations to assert their power without going to war. Olympic success equaled national pride. For athletes and coaches in Romania, it meant security and stature. It meant not waiting in line for a loaf of bread.
POD1000000028_S0000079	People suffer shortages.
POD1000000028_S0000080	brought about despotism and corruption of the imperial government.
POD1000000028_S0000081	Romania at that time was under a very, very strict, ugly dictatorship. And it was a cult of personality.
POD1000000028_S0000082	A public display of giant portraits of communist leaders.
POD1000000028_S0000083	We had to idolize the leader of the country.
POD1000000028_S0000084	Nadia's win was the ultimate political validation for the country's leader, Nikolai Ceausescu.
POD1000000028_S0000085	Paganci was befitting the crowning of a princess.
POD1000000028_S0000086	It was a national celebration and the president got very excited.
POD1000000028_S0000087	This presentation was made personally by the President of Romania, Nicolae Ceauescu.
POD1000000028_S0000089	Nadia and the Corolis were welcomed home to Romania as heroes.
POD1000000028_S0000090	They gave us awards, you know, we got some bonuses. We paid only half of the taxes like everybody paid. We got 50% deduction on our taxes.
POD1000000028_S0000091	Propaganda is power in a regime like Ceausescu's, and there was no better propaganda than celebrating and rewarding the success of its Olympic champion and the coaches who had brought Romania such high honor.
POD1000000028_S0000092	Nadia was made hero of the socialist country and she was a hero, well decorated.
POD1000000028_S0000093	A country honored Nadia with its highest award, the Hero of the Socialist Labor.
POD1000000028_S0000094	She got the call. Bella got two calls.
POD1000000028_S0000095	Nadia and the Corolis were gifted cars. Their taxes were cut in half. As the rest of the country dealt with crushing rations, the Romanian coaches and their choreographer had meals delivered to them for free.
POD1000000028_S0000096	The days of waiting in food lines were over for them.
POD1000000028_S0000097	The only thing what they expected us to do is to win medals.
POD1000000028_S0000098	as long as they could keep making Romania proud.
POD1000000028_S0000100	Bella Caroli had always been an athlete, but never a gymnast.
POD1000000028_S0000101	He was a boxer in the beginning, then he became a hammer thrower, then he became a handball coach. So everything about gymnastics.
POD1000000028_S0000102	Bella's first experience with gymnastics didn't come until college.
POD1000000028_S0000103	I had to pass some gymnastic test, which was all difficult to me. I was a tall and pretty heavy guy.
POD1000000028_S0000104	It was something, something to see me swinging on the bars and doing a tumbling, which is an unknown sport for me, totally unknown before.
POD1000000028_S0000105	He was introduced to gymnastics and to one of his classmates, Marta Eros, the woman he would marry.
POD1000000028_S0000106	I got married and my wife, a former gymnast, she was a good gymnast though, we got married and we went out to teach gymnastics.
POD1000000028_S0000107	Marta and Bella both majored in physical education with the goal of coaching young kids. They wanted to work together and decided to focus on her specialty, gymnastics.
POD1000000028_S0000108	It was a new experience, a totally new experience for me. I never had the experience to teach young children. I didn't know how to start with them.
POD1000000028_S0000109	Bella came to the sport not knowing much about gymnastics, but that didn't really matter because he was essentially teaching himself the basics of the sport by teaching little kids who didn't know much about gymnastics themselves.
POD1000000028_S0000110	That's something Geza noticed the first time he saw Bella in action.
POD1000000028_S0000111	I saw this big guy, big guy, all dressed in a blue warm-up, and some very small little kids who were up almost just up to his hips, you know.
POD1000000028_S0000112	flipping like the little fishes in the water, like little silver fishes, tumbling on the floor. So it was very impressive. And I saw this guy with huge hands, sometimes spouting them and throwing them up in there and catching them.
POD1000000028_S0000113	Oh my god, I think this is something different.
POD1000000028_S0000114	It was kind of an ideal match. Giant Bella could easily spot these small kids and help them safely learn new skills. His wife, Marta, had the gymnastics know-how and credibility.
POD1000000028_S0000115	They started to teach very young kids very hard tricks. Easy to spot them, you know.
POD1000000028_S0000116	The Karolis refined their system in local gymnasiums for 10 years before breaking on to the national stage.
POD1000000028_S0000117	After that he got in connection with the Gymnastic Federation. We got lots of help from them.
POD1000000028_S0000118	Bella and Marta's approach got results. Nearly all of the athletes on the Romanian Olympic team that won the silver medal in 1976 had trained with the Corollis.
POD1000000028_S0000119	As a group, they were noticeably younger and tinier than the gymnasts who had come before them.
POD1000000028_S0000120	14 year old Nadia Comaneci of Romania, 4 feet 11, 86 pounds.
POD1000000028_S0000121	By comparison, the 1972 Olympic gold medalist was a 19-year-old. The 1968 gold medalist was 26. They'd been through puberty. They were taller. They had women's bodies.
POD1000000028_S0000122	When Nadia won gold at 14 years old, it sealed the trend toward child athlete.
POD1000000028_S0000123	the youngest ever to win a gold medal in the all-around competition.
POD1000000028_S0000124	Nadia, congratulations again. And one thing I wanted to ask her, she's the youngest girl to win a gold medal at the Olympic Games. Where does she go from here? What about 1980?
POD1000000028_S0000127	I'm going to participate at the Olympics in Moscow and I'm going to try to do better than I did here and learn a lot new things.
POD1000000028_S0000128	How many more tens does she expect?
POD1000000028_S0000130	As many as possible.
POD1000000028_S0000131	Congratulations and to your coach, Bella Caroli.
POD1000000028_S0000132	Before the 1976 games were even over, the Romanians were focused on repeating and adding to that success. And because Bela was seen as responsible for Nadia,
POD1000000028_S0000133	The Romanian government put the Karolyi's in charge of a new national training center in the small industrial town of Deva.
POD1000000028_S0000134	Bela always liked to work in this type of small places when he had a lot of control.
POD1000000028_S0000135	It was isolated. That was the point. Bella liked to keep tabs on the girls.
POD1000000028_S0000136	So he knew if the girls went to buy some ice cream or... He knew because he knew everybody. So the girls were under control at the time. He cannot go there and buy food or something without him knowing.
POD1000000028_S0000137	Geza had moved to Deva with Bella and Marta to continue as the team's choreographer and dance coach. They were working at the pinnacle of Romania's centralized system.
POD1000000028_S0000138	and there was tremendous pressure to find more Nadia's.
POD1000000028_S0000139	My real full name is Gertrude Amelia Eberle.
POD1000000028_S0000140	Trudy Kolar was a gymnast for Romania's national team from 1976 to 1983. She competed under her middle and maiden names, Emilia Eberli.
POD1000000028_S0000141	because it sounded more like Romanian.
POD1000000028_S0000142	By age 12, Trudy was the reigning junior national champion.
POD1000000028_S0000143	I just got a call at home.
POD1000000028_S0000144	It was Bella Corolli.
POD1000000028_S0000145	I saw Nadia on TV and I loved gymnastics and I always told my mom, oh my gosh, I wish I could train with her, but that's never gonna happen. And then we get a phone call and I was like, I said, okay, mom, let's go.
POD1000000028_S0000146	Trudy traveled with her mother by train to Deva.
POD1000000028_S0000147	I was so happy when we got there and I saw Bella. He looked to me like a mountain. I was a little tiny girl and he was like big and all smiling and everything.
POD1000000028_S0000148	Her mother kissed her and placed a half a loaf of bread in a dresser drawer before leaving. She told her daughter to please remember to eat.
POD1000000028_S0000149	She said, okay, honey, I need to leave now. I need to catch the train. I said, bye, mom. I gave her a kiss and then Bella showed her to the, through the hallway to the door.
POD1000000028_S0000150	And I was just like, oh, okay, by myself in a room. I said, okay, so where should I put my stuff? And the door just suddenly opens in a scary way, you know, just really fast.
POD1000000028_S0000151	And Bella comes and he smacked me over the face so hard that it flew on my bed. And he opened the drawer where my bread was in and he said, if I ever see you again eating anything like this, I will kill you.
POD1000000028_S0000152	That was my welcome.
POD1000000028_S0000154	Don't misunderstand, the National Training Center at a drab town called Dava is not a concentration camp. There are pillow fights and fun and going to school, but there's mostly training.
POD1000000028_S0000155	Tough training it is. This was Nadia in her training days with coach Karolyi standing by, but not catching her. Is this training or torture? And what do the youngsters think about it?
POD1000000028_S0000156	We fail to watch all the time.
POD1000000028_S0000157	Gabby Jaikulescu was 13 years old when she was recruited to train with Trudy and the other Olympians in the making.
POD1000000028_S0000158	Life in Deva was one of deprivation, beatings, and living in constant fear.
POD1000000028_S0000159	I tell you what I saw when I got there. You know, two little crackers in the morning. It was a little food, but it was not enough.
POD1000000028_S0000160	I mean, I ate toothpaste because I was not able to sleep. I was so hungry. And I just felt that I need something in my stomach.
POD1000000028_S0000161	We were eating leftovers on the street. If you find a little apple that was like half eaten, then you would pick it up.
POD1000000028_S0000162	You fall asleep dreaming about chocolates floating in front of your eyes. You fall asleep seeing like fried chicken.
POD1000000028_S0000163	Especially when you go and the coaches eat to a table next to you and they get like fried chicken and french fries and they eat right next to us and we sit there we have
POD1000000028_S0000164	plain yogurt and a boiled egg. Or you have a dry piece of meat that gets stuck in your throat, it's so dry.
POD1000000028_S0000165	I mean, you go to sleep hungry and with all that training, you know, training, training, training, and we were given a fist of vitamins or who knows what was that.
POD1000000028_S0000166	And we never knew what's going to happen next. And there were times where 11 o'clock at night came and Billa came to the dorm and said, put your shoes on and let's go start running outside, you fat ass pigs.
POD1000000028_S0000168	go run. Rain, shine, snowing.
POD1000000028_S0000169	There was no patience or compassion for injuries at Bella's training center.
POD1000000028_S0000170	He wanted everything fast, quick, you know, put them back together fast, you know. If the doctor didn't follow Bela's orders, you know, they are out.
POD1000000028_S0000171	Bella fired doctors who didn't follow his orders, and the gymnasts knew that complaining about injuries could lead to a beating.
POD1000000028_S0000172	One day, doing a vault at practice, Gabby landed awkwardly and broke two fingers. She walked back to her teammates and showed them her throbbing right hand.
POD1000000028_S0000173	And they told me, shut up, don't say anything because he's gonna get so mad. And I had to finish that practice with two broken fingers.
POD1000000028_S0000174	I remember trying to grab the bar with one of the hands. I could have put two fingers down. And somehow he just got kind of sick of looking at me not doing a good job.
POD1000000028_S0000175	He said a few words, you know, and just dismissed me. Nobody's going to take me to take an X-ray, not have a doctor to look at this.
POD1000000028_S0000176	And all what I hear from colleagues is just keep going.
POD1000000028_S0000177	Everything about the gymnast's lives in Dava was monitored. The national team coaches listened to their phone calls and intercepted their mail.
POD1000000028_S0000178	When homesick girls ran away from the training center, police took them back to Deva.
POD1000000028_S0000179	I was so scared, I swear I thought he has eyes on the trees, on the bushes, on the walls.
POD1000000028_S0000180	We couldn't quit. It was not a choice. And you had to keep going against your will, against everything.
POD1000000028_S0000181	Bella maintained complete control, while Marta came into the gym mostly to coach balance beam.
POD1000000028_S0000182	To me, it always seemed like he was always on top of everything and she was doing whatever he wanted her to do and obeying everything.
POD1000000028_S0000183	when Marta was in the gym, she could also be physically abusive.
POD1000000028_S0000184	And we could actually defend ourselves from her because she was not strong enough to catch us and hit us.
POD1000000028_S0000185	So, you know, sometimes she would scratch us and she would grab us from the neck like this and then she would pour her fingernails into your meat and it kind of hurt. But she was not good at beating.
POD1000000028_S0000186	Bella was the bad one. Oh gosh, that was bad.
POD1000000028_S0000187	And when they faltered at Meats, they faced his wrath.
POD1000000028_S0000188	Let's say you fell on beam, that was a disaster. You got off the beam, saluted the judges, and we went straight to the bathroom and he came after us and we got beaten up.
POD1000000028_S0000190	And then he said, well, you better put yourself together because you have two more events.
POD1000000028_S0000191	The girls' only respite from Bella and Marta was their dance classes with Geza.
POD1000000028_S0000192	You know, it was relaxing for us. It was fun. He could make us, you know, smile and have a good time.
POD1000000028_S0000193	They also knew he would look out for them.
POD1000000028_S0000194	Geza was always the one that was always behind Bella's back. He was protecting us.
POD1000000028_S0000195	When he was together with Bella and Marta, he was a tough guy because he had to look like a tough guy because he would have probably lost his job if he didn't.
POD1000000028_S0000196	So every time we went to practice at the gym in the afternoon and Geza was there before and he was always at the door looking through the keyhole and when Bella marked, he said, six, six, six and five. Five was marked and six was Bella.
POD1000000028_S0000197	Geza used dance counts as code names for Marta and Bella.
POD1000000028_S0000198	That's how we knew when he said six, we already were like, oh my gosh, Bella's coming.
POD1000000028_S0000199	Some days, Bella disappeared from the gym to go hunting.
POD1000000028_S0000200	Those are the best days of our lives in the gym. So basically Dracula wasn't there.
POD1000000028_S0000201	Who was Dracula?
POD1000000028_S0000202	Oh, Bella.
POD1000000028_S0000204	Bella and Marta faced enormous pressure going into the 1980 Olympics. Their standing with the government was only as good as their next result.
POD1000000028_S0000205	They'd have to match or beat the success of the 76 games to keep their country's favor.
POD1000000028_S0000206	The entire Romanian team felt the weight of their country's oppressive regime when they met with officials before they left for Moscow.
POD1000000028_S0000207	Some kind of lieutenant, I don't know, he was all dressed in green and stuff, big guy and really serious. And he said, you better think what you're doing twice. Don't you ever bring shame on your country. You're weighing our country on your shoulders.
POD1000000028_S0000208	Trying to defend her gold medal in the all-around, Nadia became the center of a judging dispute.
POD1000000028_S0000210	Nadia went on a beam and her beam score didn't come up.
POD1000000028_S0000212	Bella protested Nadia's low beam score in full view of the television cameras.
POD1000000028_S0000214	Nadia had to settle for silver in the all-around, but went on to win gold on floor and beam. Trudy won a silver medal on the uneven bars.
POD1000000028_S0000215	The Romanians repeated with a silver in the team competition. But this time finishing second to the Russians was a disappointment. Bela and Marta weren't returning to Romania as heroes again.
POD1000000028_S0000216	So when we made a big brouhaha about Nadia's calling on me, the government didn't like it.
POD1000000028_S0000217	In a society hyper-sensitive about how it was perceived on the world stage, and particularly by its communist allies, Bela's protest in response to the Russian judge embarrassed the Romanian officials.
POD1000000028_S0000218	Plus, his most important ally in the Ceausescu regime,
POD1000000028_S0000219	had just been demoted.
POD1000000028_S0000220	So Bela knew that the end is close. He told me at that moment, we are in big trouble. And from there everything started to go sour for us.
POD1000000028_S0000222	The first time I ever saw Bela Karolyi in action with his gymnasts was pretty memorable.
POD1000000028_S0000224	It was the Nadia 81 tour when Bella and the Romanian women's national team toured with the American team in March 1981.
POD1000000028_S0000225	My reporting partner, Bonnie Ford, covered the Detroit stop of the Nadia 81 tour, a seven-city promotional tour of the U.S. featuring the Romanian national team and its superstar.
POD1000000028_S0000226	So I personally, as both an Olympic fan and a reporter at that time, I didn't think of it as a political event where the Romanians were showing off their system, so to speak.
POD1000000028_S0000227	Certainly, they did. They saw it as a propaganda tool and a chance to highlight their excellence.
POD1000000028_S0000229	But to me, it was just a chance to see the best athlete in her sport.
POD1000000028_S0000231	I was focused on Nadia, the audience was focused on Nadia, a lot of very excited young girls. This was like Beatlemania. Nadia-mania was definitely a real thing.
POD1000000028_S0000233	Bella Corolli was very visible and he was unmistakable on the floor. Huge guy. He was, in our eyes, the guru, the genius behind Nadia's precision and perfection.
POD1000000028_S0000234	Being on tour with Bella as the Romanians coach, it was interesting to watch him and the gymnast really, just how they interacted with each other.
POD1000000028_S0000235	The U.S. national team had been invited to perform with the Romanians on their tour. Tracy Talavera was a member of that team.
POD1000000028_S0000236	The gymnasts were always very stern, very robotic. They worked extremely hard. They did numbers of routines and skills way beyond what we had ever seen.
