POD1000000030_S0000001	If it saves energy and gives your performance a boost, well, when is a shoe just a shoe? From American Public Media, this is Marketplace Tech demystifying the digital economy. I'm Jack Stewart, in for Molly Wood.
POD1000000030_S0000003	World Athletics, the governing body for track and field, is set to announce whether it'll ban certain types of shoes.
POD1000000030_S0000004	In particular, Nike's Vaporfly shoes have been prominently on the feet of athletes responsible for tumbling race records recently.
POD1000000030_S0000005	Nike claims the $250 sneakers shave up to 4% off a runner's time. So is that technology doping?
POD1000000030_S0000006	We got a hold of Ian Hunter, professor of exercise science at Brigham Young University, as he was with some athletes training at BYU's indoor track. He told us the shoes work by combining foam in the sole with a carbon fiber plate.
POD1000000030_S0000007	I think the plate mostly allows for some structure of the shoes.
POD1000000030_S0000008	So if that plate wasn't there and you have a 44 millimeter height off the ground that's just foam and you try running around a corner, it's just going to collapse on you.
POD1000000030_S0000009	So the plane...
POD1000000030_S0000011	mainly give structure to the shoe, but it does give a small benefit in terms of energy cost.
POD1000000030_S0000012	Combine that with now you can do higher foam because you can hold everything together with the plate.
POD1000000030_S0000013	and you've got a really good pushing into the ground, big displacement of the foot while it interacts with the ground and then pushes off really effectively.
POD1000000030_S0000014	So it quite literally puts a spring in your step.
POD1000000030_S0000015	Yeah, it's not a coiled spring like we're used to, but any foam is really a spring. This one's just really effective at it.
POD1000000030_S0000016	But where's the line? That's what the question is now. And I think these are either at the line where I'd feel comfortable or a little bit beyond.
POD1000000030_S0000017	So you're saying that there could still be some innovation allowed in shoes? We're not going to say everybody must wear the same type of shoe, but there must be a limit to it.
POD1000000030_S0000018	Yeah, I think it's wonderful to have the innovation and what Nike's done is propelled other companies to catch up and they will catch up.
POD1000000030_S0000019	So we could have the standard for marathoning or road racing is a shoe like the Vaporfly, but then Nike or someone will go a little further with it.
