POD1000000031_S0000001	The holidays are over, it's back to reality for most of us, and back to some distant warehouse for a lot of our unwanted gifts.
POD1000000031_S0000002	From American Public Media, this is Marketplace Tech demystifying the digital economy.
POD1000000031_S0000003	I'm Jack Stewart, in for Molly Wood.
POD1000000031_S0000005	This season's online holiday sales were worth some $138 billion to e-retailers.
POD1000000031_S0000006	But nearly a third of that stuff is expected to be returned, according to new research from CBRE, a real estate research group.
POD1000000031_S0000007	And that's pretty typical. 30% of online shopping is returned, versus 8% of stuff bought in shops.
POD1000000031_S0000008	And all of those returns come with a cost, even if they're free to us, the shoppers.
POD1000000031_S0000009	There's the emissions from the trucks and planes, the waste from packaging and discarded products, the cost of finding space for it all, or even just chucking it out.
POD1000000031_S0000010	David Egan with CBRE says right about now warehouse workers are getting buried.
POD1000000031_S0000011	Well, it's just the flood of packages. When you think about the way the supply chain is built and designed, it really is meant to be as efficient as possible in moving product from the point of production, so wherever something is made, to the end point, the point of consumption.
POD1000000031_S0000012	And all of the networks, the buildings, the flow through the buildings, the transportation networks, even the way the employees are trained to handle the packages are really meant to get that stuff moving out as quickly as possible.
POD1000000031_S0000013	Are there ways that we could use technology to try to mitigate this problem?
POD1000000031_S0000014	In my opinion, the real solution is going to be a technological solution at the point of sale. So how do you provide the customer better assurance that what they're buying is what they actually want?
POD1000000031_S0000015	So the classic example is someone buys three or four shirts with the intention of only keeping one or two of them because they don't know if the size is right, they don't know if the color is quite going to be right, they don't know what it's going to feel like.
POD1000000031_S0000016	And I do think there are technologies between augmented reality and virtual reality where we'll be able to shop online and have a more, you know, a sense of an in-person type of experience, which I believe will really substantially reduce the number of returns that occur.
POD1000000031_S0000017	The other side of it though is that offering that type of free frictionless seamless return policy is really important to keeping customers.
POD1000000031_S0000018	Do you think we as consumers have a role to play here? I mean returns are so easy, most of the time they're free, they're maybe something we don't even think about as much as we should.
POD1000000031_S0000019	I think we need to incur some of the costs, frankly. I do think that the free and painless return system that we've all been accustomed to dealing with is long term not sustainable.
POD1000000031_S0000020	So I do think in some place we need to understand how damaging it is, not only to the retailers that we're doing business with, but also to the environment.
POD1000000031_S0000021	You know, one fact that I find shocking, frankly, is that in the United States alone, five billion pounds of return merchandise gets put in the landfill every single year, just in the US.
POD1000000031_S0000022	So merchandise that's been handled and enough time has passed between the point of sale to the return point that has been deemed worthless and it gets thrown away. Five billion pounds a year.
POD1000000031_S0000023	So, I mean, it's just, it's a destructive type of system that we're all taking part in. I think we all need to do our part to make it go away.
POD1000000031_S0000024	And one of the ways to do that is to pay for it. And when people are asked to pay for something, they'll be a lot more careful about the way they behave.
POD1000000031_S0000025	Now the flip side of that is that the consumers have voted overwhelmingly in favor of free and frictionless returns and have said that they will find someone if you won't give it to me someone else will.
POD1000000031_S0000026	So, fixing this is not going to be easy. It's really hard to imagine the first retailer that's going to be brave enough to turn around and say, sure, we'll take your returns, but it's actually going to cost you.
POD1000000031_S0000027	That was David Egan with CBRE.
POD1000000031_S0000029	And now for some related links.
POD1000000031_S0000030	It's impossible to talk about online shopping without mentioning the behemoth that is Amazon. As Adweek says, where it goes, other retailers follow.
POD1000000031_S0000031	And in the last decade it has set new standards and expectations for delivery, pushing its competitors to do the same.
POD1000000031_S0000032	Adweek has the five ways which Amazon changed shopping in the 2010s.
POD1000000031_S0000033	With returns often being free, it's really not surprising that consumers aren't aware of the real costs.
POD1000000031_S0000034	Or maybe we just like to assume or hope that those unwanted items that we so carefully return with all their original packaging intact are then restocked and resold.
POD1000000031_S0000035	The idea that a good chunk of them end up in landfill is, as the LA Times calls it, a hidden environmental crisis.
POD1000000031_S0000036	David Egan explained that the logistics operation is set up to run smoothly in one direction, getting things to us.
POD1000000031_S0000037	There are a lot of efforts to streamline the opposite direction too though. There are companies making it their business to help retailers and consumers.
POD1000000031_S0000038	So if you do ever step out from behind your computer and actually go to malls a little more frequently than me, you've probably noticed some return bars where you can drop off purchases and have someone else just deal with all that sending it back stuff for you.
POD1000000031_S0000039	And for the sellers, these companies promise to analyze returns and the reasons for them, and reduce the packaging they need. Vogue Business breaks it down.
POD1000000031_S0000040	But I think really the New Year's resolution that I'm taking away from all of this is just to buy less stuff. I'm Jack Stewart, and that's Marketplace Tech.
