POD1000000032_S0000001	The US needs a lot more hospital beds fast.
POD1000000032_S0000002	Kentec, help us build them.
POD1000000032_S0000003	From American Public Media, this is Marketplace Tech demystifying the digital economy.
POD1000000032_S0000004	I'm Molly Wood.
POD1000000032_S0000006	States and cities are rushing to find hospital beds to prepare for an increase in patients suffering from COVID-19.
POD1000000032_S0000007	In New York, makeshift hospitals are going up in Central Park. A Navy hospital ship is in the city's harbor.
POD1000000032_S0000008	Its Javits Convention Center has been converted into a temporary medical facility. And the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is looking to convert empty hotels and other buildings into hospitals across the country.
POD1000000032_S0000009	Now, as part of its response to the coronavirus, the Chinese government built two giant hospitals in 10 days.
POD1000000032_S0000010	And we wondered, could we build hospitals that fast here in the US? And what tech exists to innovate on the construction process?
POD1000000032_S0000011	Chris Jettina is working on it. He's the CEO of the manufacturing and design firm Blocks, which specializes in modular medical facility construction.
POD1000000032_S0000012	We deliver acute care facilities. Think about hospitals. We design them digitally and we manufacture them in our plant.
POD1000000032_S0000013	And imagine a big complex Lego that we can ship out. And then when we get there, we assemble it as a completed building.
POD1000000032_S0000014	And all of this relies on a bunch of technology that we use, the digital design and the supply chain and the machines that make these parts real together.
POD1000000032_S0000015	but at the end, we take raw material and we turn it into hospitals.
POD1000000032_S0000016	And about how long does that take?
POD1000000032_S0000017	A typical building may take 12 to 16 months to make.
POD1000000032_S0000018	And we do it in four months now. And every day we have a team that's working to make it faster and faster.
POD1000000032_S0000019	Yeah, you know, I asked that because no pressure, but it seems as though we are going to need some health care facilities quickly.
POD1000000032_S0000020	how do you see your company being a part of that?
POD1000000032_S0000021	So a few weeks ago, when the size of this pandemic became clear,
POD1000000032_S0000022	Our team had to refocus. I mean, we were making permanent hospitals and we were doing them really fast, but we had to think about how to take this problem and put it through our machine blocks.
POD1000000032_S0000023	and figure out how to do that so that we could get hospital beds quicker.
POD1000000032_S0000024	We set out immediately to design a 24-bed MICU.
POD1000000032_S0000025	You know?
POD1000000032_S0000026	A MICU is a mobile isolation care unit. This MICU, it's got three jobs.
POD1000000032_S0000027	And the first one is it's got to protect the frontline health care worker.
POD1000000032_S0000028	And then there's this second thing that they've got to do, which is they're designed to protect the hospital's existing capacity.
POD1000000032_S0000029	And then the final one is we're trying to make these MICUs become a permanent and flexible asset that helps serve the health system going forward.
POD1000000032_S0000030	So I mean, they're institutional grade, they're reusable.
POD1000000032_S0000031	It's a fleet of ICU rooms that gets to be moved in the future to wherever the hot spot is.
POD1000000032_S0000032	How much do they cost?
POD1000000032_S0000033	These things will be around $200,000 to $300,000 a bed in the beginning, and then those prices will drop down.
POD1000000032_S0000034	So these are significantly less expensive, but they're still high-tech devices that are chock full of equipment and pressurization and electronics, and they're still pretty expensive boxes.
POD1000000032_S0000035	Can you tell us at all where these projects might be happening? Like where you're putting up these mickeys?
POD1000000032_S0000036	Well, we're not putting them up yet, so it's still going to production in two weeks.
POD1000000032_S0000037	The first ones could be in any of the spots that are needed.
POD1000000032_S0000038	So obviously we've been in pretty heavy discussions in New York. We've been in discussions in Georgia. And there's a big there's a big delta between those two places. But it really doesn't matter to us where they're needed.
POD1000000032_S0000039	they can go just as easily to one or the other.
POD1000000032_S0000040	And then just out of curiosity, is it sort of like a modular house where it's basically sort of pre-built and then it just comes on a big truck?
POD1000000032_S0000041	You know, parts of it are. So a Lego analogy is really a pretty good one.
POD1000000032_S0000042	If you think about a Lego kit or advanced one, it has different types of parts.
POD1000000032_S0000043	Some of them are volumetric and some of them are custom parts and some of them are little pieces that can be used in a thousand different ways.
POD1000000032_S0000044	And we're agnostic about it. We think that there's just a value stream that goes from raw material and it's converted into a usable building.
POD1000000032_S0000045	And the process that it goes through is a whole lot of different stages.
POD1000000032_S0000046	We're just trying to find an optimal one.
POD1000000032_S0000047	there's not always a right path because of, in fact, we're using many of the things that we do for a regular hospital right now
POD1000000032_S0000048	but we've made different changes. The foundation, for example, is significantly different on a MICU.
POD1000000032_S0000049	It doesn't need all of the permanence that an acute care hospital may have, you know, that has a 50-year lifespan.
POD1000000032_S0000050	So the idea is we think of it as completed parts, but every part's completed.
POD1000000032_S0000051	And it goes together in a form of chunking.
POD1000000032_S0000052	It's kind of the way they build the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner. It's not made on an assembly line the way you think of an assembly line.
POD1000000032_S0000053	It's made in chunks that are made all over the world, and they've all brought together in Charleston and put together as an OEM in a matter of days.
POD1000000032_S0000054	So that's more like what we're doing with blocks.
POD1000000032_S0000055	Got it. What makes these specific to medical facilities?
POD1000000032_S0000056	what kind of certification and technology goes into that.
POD1000000032_S0000057	Hospitals are really heavily regulated.
POD1000000032_S0000058	And if you try and understand which ones there are, it's a long list.
POD1000000032_S0000059	And so what I would just simply say is these things are dealing with life safety at an institutional level. They're dealing with emergency power, critical care operations.
POD1000000032_S0000060	They're dealing with temperature control that's based on air exchanges, which allow you to evacuate disease and infection.
POD1000000032_S0000061	They are designed to be visible and operational high performances, if you will.
POD1000000032_S0000062	So these nurses and doctors are under an enormous amount of pressure.
POD1000000032_S0000063	And what you're trying to do is create a place which is safe for them to work, but visually controlled so they can see everything at once.
POD1000000032_S0000064	And that's what we focused on. How do we make this really a beautiful, elegantly simple, operationally visually controlled device that is technologically empowered?
POD1000000032_S0000065	and can be deployed really fast and still be done with the stuff that's available today, not the stuff that we wish was available today.
POD1000000032_S0000066	You said that you're trying to take a typical construction time for a building from 12 to 18 months down to four months.
