POD1000000035_S0000005	New Jersey's governor recently went on TV asking for volunteers who know COBOL, a more than 60-year-old computer programming language.
POD1000000035_S0000006	That's because the state's unemployment benefit system runs on a decades-old mainframe that can't keep up with the volume of requests for financial help.
POD1000000035_S0000007	And New Jersey isn't alone. Several states, not to mention lots of financial institutions, are all at the mercy of these very old systems running on a programming language that isn't even taught in schools anymore.
POD1000000035_S0000008	Joseph Steinberg is a cybersecurity consultant and author of the book Cybersecurities for Dummies.
POD1000000035_S0000009	Well, first of all, there are many financial institutions that use mainframes with COBOL for back-end processing of transactions and batch processing.
POD1000000035_S0000010	I think they probably have things in a lot better shape because they have the resources in-house.
POD1000000035_S0000011	In some cases they've replaced the systems at great expense over recent years, in some cases they're doing it now.
POD1000000035_S0000012	and in some cases they've made the decisions to actually train people to be able to support these systems going forward.
POD1000000035_S0000013	But when it comes to government, and I would say probably even worse in the state governments than in the federal,
POD1000000035_S0000014	You have many systems that seem to hang around for a very long time.
POD1000000035_S0000015	One of the questions that I posed in the last week is simply if, God forbid, this pandemic continued for several more months and all Americans had to vote in the presidential election remotely,
POD1000000035_S0000016	Mm-hmm.
POD1000000035_S0000017	Do all 50 states actually have computer systems that could accommodate that volume of ballots going out and in to be counted, processed in a secure fashion, in any reasonable time frame?
POD1000000035_S0000018	And I'm afraid of what the answer to that question might be. We simply have a lot of legacy systems involved in various state processes and they are not meant, they were never designed to accommodate mass loads that could suddenly happen now.
POD1000000035_S0000019	Mm-hmm.
POD1000000035_S0000020	and it's a lot harder to scale these legacy systems.
POD1000000035_S0000021	newer technologies scale much better and I'm afraid of what's out there you know at the state level.
POD1000000035_S0000022	And I'm sure there's some in the federal government, but you know, after this pandemic is over, it's really going to be time to take a serious look at a lot of these older systems and evaluate whether they really are reliable only because we haven't had to make changes or they're really reliable.
POD1000000035_S0000023	And I think in many cases we'll find it's the former.
POD1000000035_S0000024	Right. I mean, it seems like this is sort of an invisible infrastructure problem in America that in some ways is as expensive and difficult to fix as roads and bridges.
POD1000000035_S0000025	It's as expensive and perhaps in some ways more dangerous because you don't notice it until the problem happens.
POD1000000035_S0000026	You have people who desperately need money because their work suddenly ended, they place an unemployment claim and they can't get it processed.
POD1000000035_S0000027	that can be dangerous. People could be low on food and other supplies and it's not like they can easily obtain them now either.
POD1000000035_S0000028	And I think that's precisely the issue with these older systems.
POD1000000035_S0000029	Often we assume that they're reliable until it's too late and the problem has hit. And at that point, you've got a tactical problem. How do we process these unemployment claims?
POD1000000035_S0000030	and a strategic problem, how do we make sure this never happens again in the future?
POD1000000035_S0000031	You're saying that even if we were able to bring a lot of programmers out of retirement, that these systems simply may not ever be able to handle the load that is being put on them now.
POD1000000035_S0000032	It may be possible to scale them up with improved hardware, but that's going to be very expensive, number one.
POD1000000035_S0000033	And they don't scale as simply as more modern systems do. So, you know, the fact that you're hiring programmers out of retirement and people don't live forever.
POD1000000035_S0000034	You're not going to have an endless supply of programmers who programmed in the 70s in the workforce.
