POD1000000045_S0000345	Okay, Katie 2020, it's been a rough year, but you had a big life moment happen when you published your first book. It's called My Storied Year.
POD1000000045_S0000346	So let's see, where should we even start? I would love to hear kind of where did the story come to you. First of all, give us a little snapshot of what My Story Dear is about.
POD1000000045_S0000347	And then maybe tell us the story of how did this story come into your life, into your mind? Walk us through a little bit of how the process was from taking it from like, oh, I have this idea to now you can hold it in your hands. You wrote a book, you're an author. Tell us everything.
POD1000000045_S0000348	Okay, so my story here starts with Dragon Stewart. He's a seventh grader and he is dyslexic and he has a really hard life at home and he's got some bullying situations going on at school.
POD1000000045_S0000349	But this year he has a new set of teachers and some new kids in his class and his English teacher, who is my favorite, really kind of pulls out the writer in him. He's like a secret poet. He has this journal that he carries around and writes poetry.
POD1000000045_S0000350	but otherwise doesn't really like to read or write because it's hard for him. And he has kind of this secret story that he doesn't really know if he should tell it or how he should tell it. And so
POD1000000045_S0000351	through the year he kind of opens up to his friends more and then he's able to kind of reveal his story and so that's the basic premise of it.
POD1000000045_S0000352	Oh my goodness, you have sent a copy. It's on the way to me. I cannot wait again. I love, love, love a middle grade novel. And this just feels so heartwarming already, just hearing you set up the story.
POD1000000045_S0000353	You've mentioned that you taught elementary. Was that kind of a jumping off point for you in terms of how this character came into your mind?
POD1000000045_S0000355	So when I taught, writing was my absolute favorite thing to teach. I did a lot of extensive training on writing and a lot of the things that she does in the book, there's kind of like little writing lessons along the way that you could do with your kids if you were homeschooling them or even teachers in the classroom.
POD1000000045_S0000356	But a lot of those things I learned through my trainings. And so I wanted to pull in like the whole writing is therapy almost for people, you know, how we put things into words and how our creativity kind of find out who we are. And so
POD1000000045_S0000357	I wanted to pull in that aspect of it and Dragon is really kind of a mixture of a lot of kids that I taught you know I had some hard kids, you're going to teach for any amount of time you're going to have some kids with some hard lives and so.
POD1000000045_S0000358	He's a mixture of a bunch of different ones and I just had the beginning of my teaching I didn't understand these kids because that wasn't my life experience. I grew up in a two-parent household and
POD1000000045_S0000359	you know, we were always financially stable and so I didn't struggle like that. And so when I met these kids, it was almost like I can't believe people like this exist, you know, I didn't have that context. And so
POD1000000045_S0000360	I learned over the course of my years how to help these kids get through their daily lives and how to do things to help them. And I wish I had done more. Looking back, you always wish you had done more.
POD1000000045_S0000362	Yeah.
POD1000000045_S0000363	But Dragon is just a mixture of all those kids. So I wanted kids to be able to see that kids like this are real and that they do have real problems and how, you know,
POD1000000045_S0000364	They need support at school from their friends, from their teachers. I wanted to write it for teachers to see how, you know, they can be so important in these kids' lives, especially if their home life is not stable.
POD1000000045_S0000365	you know, their teacher might be their one adult that loves them. And so I wanted to put that in the book too.
POD1000000045_S0000366	Yes, yeah, that is so true. I mean, teachers can have a huge impact on our lives, sometimes not even in a good way, but definitely in positive ways.
POD1000000045_S0000367	And I think that can happen at any point along our journey, but I think those middle grade years are so tender and so formative and
POD1000000045_S0000368	When you have a teacher in your life that really sees you and is really able to help you to discover who you are, that is absolutely an actual life changer.
POD1000000045_S0000369	Yeah, what a great context to set the story in. As you have this idea, and so it's obviously going to be fiction, in the fiction writing process, and maybe this even differs depending on if you're writing children's or middle grade or YA or adult,
POD1000000045_S0000370	Do you fully write the book and then start to go to agents or publishers and say, okay, I have this thing, or do you talk on the publishing end first and then go and write? Like, what was that process like for you?
POD1000000045_S0000371	So it's different for fiction and nonfiction, which I didn't even know until I had kind of gone through it. But what happened was I wrote, and it wasn't even this book that I wrote, I wrote another manuscript.
POD1000000045_S0000372	There's a huge writing conference in Dallas, Fort Worth called DFW Con and it's a big writing conference.
POD1000000045_S0000373	With your conference ticket, you get 10 minutes with a literary agent to pitch your work. At that point, I had a finished manuscript. And when I was kind of researching the conference for fiction, they want you to have a complete manuscript.
POD1000000045_S0000374	before you ever contact anybody. For nonfiction, it's a little bit different because they want to make sure that they can sell the book before you go like write all of it. They see if you have a platform and you write a proposal and all that stuff, but the book doesn't necessarily have to be done.
POD1000000045_S0000375	for fiction, generally they want you to have a complete manuscript before you start pitching it to anybody. So I sat down with this agent, I kind of gave her my elevator pitch about the book,
POD1000000045_S0000376	And then she asked me to send her the full manuscript, which is kind of the best thing that you can hear at a conference because some people will say I'll pass on this or send me five pages or whatever. She asked for the full thing.
POD1000000045_S0000377	So I sent it to her and then, you know, six, eight, ten months later, she got, I mean, it's a long waiting process.
POD1000000045_S0000378	because they have so many manuscripts that are coming into them and they have to read them. And this woman actually ended up being my agent. And I'm so grateful for her because she didn't just send back like, I don't want this.
POD1000000045_S0000379	She sent back a list of really helpful notes for revisions and she said, if you want to like revise and then resubmit, I'll be happy to look at it again. She was like, I don't think we can sell it as it is right now, but I'll be happy to look at it again.
POD1000000045_S0000380	So I took her notes, did a lot of things, worked with a professional editor, and then sent it back to her, and then she agreed to represent me. So that's kind of how that situation went. But that was like a year-long process, probably, from start to finish.
POD1000000045_S0000381	And then once she has it, I still went back and rewrote it probably two or three times. Not a major rehaul, but just like these parts need to be fixed.
POD1000000045_S0000382	And then she started to shop it to publishers. So she did the same thing I did to find an agent. She had to send out letters and samples and all that stuff to different publishers until we found one.
POD1000000045_S0000383	My publishing journey is kind of like wacky because my publisher bought the first book that I wrote, but then they said, what else does she have? So we sent her my story year.
POD1000000045_S0000384	and then they were like we want to publish this one first they felt like it was really timely and they wanted to get it out there
POD1000000045_S0000386	first and then the first book that I sold will actually come out in June. So that's like a totally different book, but they wanted to get this one out.
POD1000000045_S0000387	Is it a middle grade novel too?
POD1000000045_S0000388	It's also middle grade and it's historical fiction so it's totally like on a different level than this one but yes.
POD1000000045_S0000389	That is fascinating. I mean, you say that the timeline was a little wacky, but if I've learned anything from my friends who are authors, it's that like the timeline's always crazy. Like everything takes so long.
POD1000000045_S0000390	And then sometimes you write the, like I've had friends who are nonfiction authors who write the whole thing, submit it, and then the publisher is like, yeah, no, we don't want to do this after all. I mean, there's always like so many twists and turns on the publishing journey.
POD1000000045_S0000391	So I can only imagine, yeah, that every single one I'm sure has surprises along the way. Some maybe are not so happy surprises, but what has surprised you in a way that you really, like this was a happy surprise about the publishing process?
POD1000000045_S0000392	The thing that surprised me the most that wasn't really happy was how long it took because you know, like I'm like I wrote this book and let's get it out. I didn't realize how long of a process it is from like getting it from a raw draft to an actual book.
POD1000000045_S0000393	But I think the thing that surprised me in the best way is that I have just met so many good people that like my editor is one of my favorite people she is gracious but she's tough and she's, you know, cut this, you know,
POD1000000045_S0000394	let's fix this part because it's not quite working. And I just learned a lot about myself as a writer and about good writing. And so that's been really, really good.
POD1000000045_S0000395	I also want to encourage anybody who's writing to find yourself a writing group and it doesn't have to be someone you meet with. Like my writing group I found from Sorta Awesome. We're in the Sorta Awesome writers
POD1000000045_S0000396	And so we're all over the place. Like I'm in Texas and there's one in New York and one in Lebanon and one in Connecticut.
POD1000000045_S0000397	And we just all, we send each other our work every week and we have a Voxer that we can process through all of our writing questions. And, you know, the days that we're like, this is horrible. Why am I doing this? We have a place for that. So that's been really, really helpful.
POD1000000045_S0000398	Oh my gosh, that gives me chills. I love that part of the story, obviously.
