YOU1000000003_S0000001	This is a 3. It's sloppily written and rendered at an extremely low resolution of 28x28 pixels
YOU1000000003_S0000002	but your brain has no trouble recognizing it as a 3.
YOU1000000003_S0000003	And I want you to take a moment to appreciate how crazy it is that brains can do this so effortlessly.
YOU1000000003_S0000004	I mean this, this, and this are also recognizable as 3s.
YOU1000000003_S0000005	even though the specific values of each pixel is very different from one image to the next.
YOU1000000003_S0000006	The particular light-sensitive cells in your eye that are firing when you see these three are very different from the ones firing when you see these three.
YOU1000000003_S0000007	But something in that crazy smart visual cortex of yours resolves these as representing the same idea.
YOU1000000003_S0000008	while at the same time recognizing other images as their own distinct ideas.
YOU1000000003_S0000009	But if I told you, hey, sit down and write for me a program that takes in a grid of 28x28 pixels like this,
YOU1000000003_S0000010	and outputs a single number between 0 and 10, telling you what it thinks the digit is,
YOU1000000003_S0000011	While the test goes from comically trivial to dauntingly difficult.
YOU1000000003_S0000012	Unless you've been living under a rock, I think I hardly need to motivate the relevance and importance of machine learning and neural networks.
YOU1000000003_S0000013	to the present and to the future. But what I want to do here is show you what a neural network actually is.
YOU1000000003_S0000014	assuming no background, and to help visualize what it's doing. Not as a buzzword, but as a piece of math.
YOU1000000003_S0000015	My hope is just that you come away feeling like the structure itself is motivated.
YOU1000000003_S0000016	and to feel like you know what it means when you read or you hear about a neural network quote-unquote learning.
YOU1000000003_S0000017	This video is just going to be devoted to the structure component of that, and the following one is going to tackle learning.
YOU1000000003_S0000018	What we're going to do is put together a neural network that can learn to recognize handwritten digits.
YOU1000000003_S0000020	This is a somewhat classic example for introducing the topic.
YOU1000000003_S0000021	And I'm happy to stick with the status quo here, because at the end of the two videos, I want to point you to a couple good resources where you can learn more.
YOU1000000003_S0000022	and where you can download the code that does this and play with it on your own computer.
YOU1000000003_S0000024	There are many, many variants of neural networks and in recent years there's been sort of a boom in research towards these variants.
YOU1000000003_S0000025	But in these two introductory videos, you and I are just going to look at the simplest plain vanilla form with no added frills.
YOU1000000003_S0000026	This is kind of a necessary prerequisite for understanding any of the more powerful modern variants.
YOU1000000003_S0000027	And trust me, it still has plenty of complexity for us to wrap our minds around.
YOU1000000003_S0000028	But even in this simplest form, it can learn to recognize handwritten digits.
YOU1000000003_S0000029	which is a pretty cool thing for a computer to be able to do.
YOU1000000003_S0000031	And at the same time, you'll see how it does fall short of a couple hopes that we might have for it.
YOU1000000003_S0000033	As the name suggests, neural networks are inspired by the brain. But let's break that down. What are the neurons, and in what sense are they linked together?
YOU1000000003_S0000034	Right now, when I say neuron, all I want you to think about is a thing that holds a number, specifically a number between 0 and 1. It's really not more than that.
YOU1000000003_S0000036	For example, the network starts with a bunch of neurons corresponding to each of the 28 times 28 pixels of the input image
YOU1000000003_S0000037	which is 784 neurons in total. Each one of these holds a number that represents the grayscale value of the corresponding pixel.
YOU1000000003_S0000038	ranging from 0 for black pixels up to 1 for white pixels. This number inside the neuron is called its activation.
YOU1000000003_S0000039	And the image you might have in mind here is that each neuron is lit up when its activation is a high number.
YOU1000000003_S0000041	So all of these 784 neurons make up the first layer of our network.
YOU1000000003_S0000043	Now jumping over to the last layer, this has 10 neurons, each representing one of the digits.
YOU1000000003_S0000044	The activation in these neurons, again some number that's between 0 and 1,
YOU1000000003_S0000045	represents how much the system thinks that a given image corresponds with a given digit.
YOU1000000003_S0000046	There's also a couple layers in between called the hidden layers, which for the time being should just be a giant question mark.
YOU1000000003_S0000047	for how on earth this process of recognizing digits is going to be handled. In this network I chose two hidden layers, each one with 16 neurons.
YOU1000000003_S0000048	And admittedly, that's kind of an arbitrary choice. To be honest, I chose two layers based on how I want to motivate the structure in just a moment.
YOU1000000003_S0000049	And 16? Well that was just a nice number to fit on the screen. In practice there is a lot of room for experiment with a specific structure here.
YOU1000000003_S0000050	The way the network operates, activations in one layer determine the activations of the next layer.
YOU1000000003_S0000051	And of course the heart of the network as an information processing mechanism comes down to exactly how those activations from one layer bring about activations in the next layer.
YOU1000000003_S0000052	It's meant to be loosely analogous to how in biological networks of neurons, some groups of neurons firing cause certain others to fire.
YOU1000000003_S0000053	The network I'm showing here has already been trained to recognize digits, and let me show you what I mean by that.
YOU1000000003_S0000054	It means if you feed in an image, lighting up all 784 neurons of the input layer according to the brightness of each pixel in the image,
YOU1000000003_S0000055	That pattern of activations causes some very specific pattern in the next layer, which causes some pattern in the one after it,
YOU1000000003_S0000056	which finally gives some pattern in the output layer. And the brightest neuron of that output layer is the network's choice, so to speak, for what digit this image represents.
YOU1000000003_S0000058	And before jumping into the math for how one layer influences the next, or how training works,
YOU1000000003_S0000059	Let's just talk about why it's even reasonable to expect a layered structure like this to behave intelligently.
YOU1000000003_S0000060	What are we expecting here? What is the best hope for what those middle layers might be doing?
YOU1000000003_S0000061	Well, when you or I recognize digits, we piece together various components. A 9 has a loop up top and a line on the right.
YOU1000000003_S0000062	An 8 also has a loop up top, but it's paired with another loop down low.
YOU1000000003_S0000063	A 4 basically breaks down into 3 specific lines and things like that.
YOU1000000003_S0000064	In a perfect world, we might hope that each neuron in the second to last layer corresponds with one of these subcomponents.
YOU1000000003_S0000065	that anytime you feed in an image with, say, a loop up top, like a 9 or an 8, there's some specific neuron whose activation is going to be close to 1.
YOU1000000003_S0000066	And I don't mean this specific loop of pixels, the hope would be that any generally loopy pattern towards the top sets off this neuron.
YOU1000000003_S0000067	That way, going from the third layer to the last one just requires learning which combination of subcomponents corresponds to which digits.
YOU1000000003_S0000068	Of course that just kicks the problem down the road because how would you recognize these subcomponents or even learn what the right subcomponents should be?
YOU1000000003_S0000069	and I still haven't even talked about how one layer influences the next, but run with me on this one for a moment. Recognizing a loop can also break down into subproblems.
YOU1000000003_S0000070	One reasonable way to do this would be to first recognize the various little edges that make it up.
YOU1000000003_S0000071	Similarly, a long line, like the kind you might see in the digits 1, 4, or 7, is really just a long edge, or maybe you think of it as a certain pattern of several smaller edges.
YOU1000000003_S0000072	So, maybe, our hope is that each neuron in the second layer of the network corresponds with the various relevant little edges.
YOU1000000003_S0000073	Maybe, when an image like this one comes in, it lights up all the neurons associated with around 8-10 specific little edges,
YOU1000000003_S0000074	which in turn lights up the neurons associated with the upper loop and a long vertical line, and those light up the neuron associated with the 9.
YOU1000000003_S0000075	Whether or not this is what our final network actually does is another question, one that I'll come back to once we see how to train the network.
YOU1000000003_S0000076	But this is a hope that we might have, a sort of goal with the layered structure like this.
YOU1000000003_S0000077	Moreover, you can imagine how being able to detect edges and patterns like this would be really useful for other image recognition tasks.
YOU1000000003_S0000078	And even beyond image recognition, there are all sorts of intelligent things you might want to do that break down into layers of abstraction.
YOU1000000003_S0000079	Parsing speech, for example, involves taking raw audio and picking out distinct sounds, which combine to make certain syllables,
YOU1000000003_S0000080	which combine to form words, which combine to make up phrases and more abstract thoughts, etc.
YOU1000000003_S0000081	But getting back to how any of this actually works, picture yourself right now designing how exactly the activations in one layer might determine the activations in the next.
YOU1000000003_S0000082	The goal is to have some mechanism that could conceivably combine pixels into edges, or edges into patterns, or patterns into digits.
YOU1000000003_S0000083	And to zoom in on one very specific example, let's say the hope is for one particular neuron in the second layer,
YOU1000000003_S0000084	to pick up on whether or not the image has an edge in this region here.
YOU1000000003_S0000085	The question at hand is what parameters should the network have? What dials and knobs should you be able to tweak?
YOU1000000003_S0000086	so that it's expressive enough to potentially capture this pattern, or any other pixel pattern, or the pattern that several edges can make a loop, and other such things.
YOU1000000003_S0000087	What we'll do is assign a weight to each one of the connections between our neuron and the neurons from the first layer.
YOU1000000003_S0000088	These weights are just numbers. Then, take all of those activations from the first layer and compute their weighted sum according to these weights.
YOU1000000003_S0000090	I find it helpful to think of these weights as being organized into a little grid of their own. And I'm going to use green pixels to indicate positive weights and red pixels to indicate negative weights.
YOU1000000003_S0000091	where the brightness of that pixel is some loose depiction of the weight's value.
YOU1000000003_S0000092	If we made the weights associated with almost all of the pixels 0, except for some positive weights in this region we care about,
YOU1000000003_S0000093	Then taking the weighted sum of all the pixel values really just amounts to adding up the values of the pixel just in the region that we care about.
YOU1000000003_S0000095	And if you really wanted to pick up on whether there's an edge here, what you might do is have some negative weights associated with the surrounding pixels.
YOU1000000003_S0000096	Then, the sum is largest when the middle pixels are bright, but the surrounding pixels are darker.
YOU1000000003_S0000098	When you compute a weighted sum like this, you might come out with any number, but for this network, what we want is for activations to be some value between 0 and 1.
YOU1000000003_S0000099	So a common thing to do is to pump this weighted sum into some function that squishes the real number line into the range between 0 and 1.
YOU1000000003_S0000100	A common function that does this is called the sigmoid function, also known as a logistic curve.
YOU1000000003_S0000101	Basically, very negative inputs end up close to 0, very positive inputs end up close to 1, and it just steadily increases around the input 0.
YOU1000000003_S0000103	So the activation of the neuron here is basically a measure of how positive the relevant weighted sum is.
YOU1000000003_S0000105	But maybe it's not that you want the neuron to light up when the weighted sum is bigger than 0. Maybe you only want it to be active when the sum is bigger than, say, 10.
YOU1000000003_S0000106	That is, you want some bias for it to be inactive.
YOU1000000003_S0000107	We'll then add in some other number, like negative 10, to this weighted sum before plugging it through the sigmoid squishification function.
YOU1000000003_S0000108	That additional number is called the bias.
YOU1000000003_S0000109	The weights tell you what pixel pattern this neuron in the second layer is picking up on, and the bias tells you how high the weighted sum needs to be
YOU1000000003_S0000110	before the neuron starts getting meaningfully active.
YOU1000000003_S0000111	That's just one neuron, every other neuron in this layer is connected to all 784 pixel neurons from the first layer.
YOU1000000003_S0000112	And each one of those 784 connections has its own weight associated with it.
YOU1000000003_S0000113	Also, each one has some bias, some other number you add on to the weighted sum before squishing it with the sigmoid.
YOU1000000003_S0000114	And that's a lot to think about.
YOU1000000003_S0000115	With this hidden layer of 16 neurons, that's a total of 784 times 16 weights along with 16 biases.
YOU1000000003_S0000116	And all of that is just the connections from the first layer to the second. The connections between the other layers also have a bunch of weights and biases associated with them.
YOU1000000003_S0000117	All said and done, this network has almost exactly 13,000 total weights and biases.
YOU1000000003_S0000118	13,000 knobs and dials that can be tweaked and turned to make this network behave in different ways.
YOU1000000003_S0000120	So when we talk about learning, what that's referring to is getting the computer to find a valid setting for all of these many, many numbers so that it'll actually solve the problem at hand.
YOU1000000003_S0000122	One thought experiment that is at once fun and kind of horrifying is to imagine sitting down and setting all of these weights and biases by hand.
YOU1000000003_S0000123	purposefully tweaking the numbers so that the second layer picks up on edges, the third layer picks up on patterns, etc.
YOU1000000003_S0000124	I personally find this satisfying, rather than just treating the network as a total black box.
YOU1000000003_S0000125	because when the network doesn't perform the way you anticipate,
YOU1000000003_S0000126	If you've built up a little bit of a relationship with what those weights and biases actually mean, you have a starting place for experimenting with how to change the structure to improve.
YOU1000000003_S0000127	Or, when the network does work, but not for the reasons you might expect, digging into what the weights and biases are doing is a good way to challenge your assumptions.
YOU1000000003_S0000128	and really expose the full space of possible solutions.
YOU1000000003_S0000129	By the way, the actual function here is a little cumbersome to write down, don't you think?
YOU1000000003_S0000131	So let me show you a more notationally compact way that these connections are represented. This is how you'd see it if you choose to read up more about neural networks.
YOU1000000003_S0000132	Organize all of the activations from one layer into a column as a vector.
YOU1000000003_S0000134	then organize all of the weights as a matrix, where each row of that matrix corresponds to the connections between one layer and a particular neuron in the next layer.
YOU1000000003_S0000135	What that means is that taking the weighted sum of the activations in the first layer according to these weights
YOU1000000003_S0000136	corresponds to one of the terms in the matrix-vector product of everything we have on the left here.
YOU1000000003_S0000138	By the way, so much of machine learning just comes down to having a good grasp of linear algebra
YOU1000000003_S0000139	So for any of you who want a nice visual understanding for matrices and what matrix-vector multiplication means, take a look at the series I did on linear algebra, especially chapter 3.
YOU1000000003_S0000140	Back to our expression, instead of talking about adding the bias to each one of these values independently,
YOU1000000003_S0000141	We represent it by organizing all those biases into a vector, and adding the entire vector to the previous matrix-vector product.
YOU1000000003_S0000142	Then as a final step, I'll wrap a sigmoid around the outside here.
YOU1000000003_S0000143	And what that's supposed to represent is that you're going to apply the sigmoid function to each specific component of the resulting vector inside.
YOU1000000003_S0000144	So, once you write down this weight matrix and these vectors as their own symbols, you can communicate the full transition of activations from one layer to the next
YOU1000000003_S0000145	in an extremely tight and neat little expression.
YOU1000000003_S0000146	And this makes the relevant code both a lot simpler and a lot faster since many libraries optimize the heck out of matrix multiplication
YOU1000000003_S0000148	Remember how earlier I said these neurons are simply things that hold numbers? Well, of course, the specific numbers that they hold depends on the image you feed in.
YOU1000000003_S0000150	So it's actually more accurate to think of each neuron as a function, one that takes in the outputs of all the neurons in the previous layer and spits out a number between 0 and 1.
YOU1000000003_S0000151	Really, the entire network is just a function, one that takes in 784 numbers as an input and spits out 10 numbers as an output.
YOU1000000003_S0000152	It's an absurdly complicated function, one that involves 13,000 parameters in the forms of these weights and biases that pick up on certain patterns.
YOU1000000003_S0000153	and which involves iterating many matrix vector products and the sigmoid squishification function.
YOU1000000003_S0000154	but it's just a function nonetheless. And in a way, it's kind of reassuring that it looks complicated.
YOU1000000003_S0000155	I mean, if it were any simpler, what hope would we have that it could take on the challenge of recognizing digits? And how does it take on that challenge?
YOU1000000003_S0000156	How does this network learn the appropriate weights and biases just by looking at data? Well, that's what I'll show in the next video.
YOU1000000003_S0000157	I'll also dig a little more into what this particular network we're seeing is really doing.
YOU1000000003_S0000159	Now is the point I suppose I should say subscribe to stay notified about when that video or any new videos come out.
YOU1000000003_S0000160	But realistically, most of you don't actually receive notifications from YouTube, do you?
YOU1000000003_S0000161	Maybe more honestly, I should say subscribe so that the neural networks that underlie YouTube's recommendation algorithm
YOU1000000003_S0000162	are primed to believe that you want to see content from this channel get recommended to you. Anyway, stay posted for more.
