YOU1000000118_S0000001	We start the specialization with this course.
YOU1000000118_S0000002	How Google Does ML, where I introduce machine learning, and what Google means when we say we are AI first.
YOU1000000118_S0000003	My colleague Josh then comes in to talk about the strategy of machine learning.
YOU1000000118_S0000004	We end with a discussion of tooling of how to do machine learning at scale using Python notebooks and serverless data processing components.
YOU1000000118_S0000006	Now, if you're an engineer or a scientist, you're probably thinking that this is all too high level.
YOU1000000118_S0000007	and you're ready to jump to the next course, which starts to delve into technical details of TensorFlow. But before you make that decision, let me tell you something.
YOU1000000118_S0000008	When we taught this set of courses to our customers,
YOU1000000118_S0000009	One remark that often came back was that the module by Josh was the one they revisited the most often.
YOU1000000118_S0000011	After they went back to work, six months later, the module that they went to look at the most was on the strategy of machine learning.
YOU1000000118_S0000012	So you want to get the big picture before you delve into the technical details.
YOU1000000118_S0000013	because the big picture is very important for you to be able to get buy-in from the rest of the organization to carry out.
YOU1000000118_S0000014	We then move on to doing machine learning with TensorFlow. That involves two aspects.
YOU1000000118_S0000015	One, creating a good machine learning dataset, and two, building your first machine learning model with TensorFlow.
YOU1000000118_S0000016	Creating a machine learning data set is another of those practical modules that you don't want to ignore.
YOU1000000118_S0000017	When you create a machine learning model and it works well in your experiments, but then fails miserably in production,
YOU1000000118_S0000018	The reason will often come back to how you created the machine learning dataset. So give yourself time to absorb the lessons.
YOU1000000118_S0000019	And then we have two courses that are about improving machine learning accuracy.
YOU1000000118_S0000020	As you build your first machine learning model, you will learn that there are lots of things you can do to improve that model.
YOU1000000118_S0000021	So think of this section as filling your tool chest with a set of ideas.
YOU1000000118_S0000022	You'll use different ideas in different situations. So you'll find that knowing them will be helpful in your career as you solve different machine learning problems.
YOU1000000118_S0000023	And as before, it's not enough to just name check these concepts. You need to give yourself time to understand them.
YOU1000000118_S0000024	and know how to implement them in code. We then move on to a set of courses that are about operationalizing the machine learning model.
YOU1000000118_S0000025	As I mentioned earlier, operationalizing a machine learning model.
YOU1000000118_S0000026	And by that I mean training it at scale in a distributed way, serving out the predictions.
YOU1000000118_S0000027	Building a machine learning model end-to-end, operationalizing a machine learning model can be super hard.
YOU1000000118_S0000028	It is a stage where most enterprise machine learning projects fail.
YOU1000000118_S0000029	I cannot tell you how many companies I've talked to who have said their innovation teams had devised these cool ML projects, but they were struggling getting the ML models into production.
YOU1000000118_S0000030	In this set of courses, we will talk about how to train, deploy, and predict with ML models in a way that they're production ready.
YOU1000000118_S0000031	And finally, we delve back into machine learning theory, but theory in big air quotes.
YOU1000000118_S0000032	Machine learning theory is mostly heuristics. Machine learning is an intensely heuristic discipline.
YOU1000000118_S0000033	and you're only as good as your bag of tools and tricks.
YOU1000000118_S0000034	So we'll introduce a number of tools and tricks that work when the inputs to your machine learning models are images.
YOU1000000118_S0000036	tools and tricks that help in your processing or outputting sequences.
YOU1000000118_S0000037	and sequences in machine learning can be either time series data or text data.
YOU1000000118_S0000038	And finally, we will look at several ways to build powerful recommendation systems.
YOU1000000118_S0000039	Recommendation systems are how you build personalized algorithms.
YOU1000000118_S0000040	And so it's something that most ML engineers build at some point in their careers.
YOU1000000118_S0000041	In fact, it might be the only ML system that many people will build.
YOU1000000118_S0000042	But in order to build powerful recommendation engines, it turns out that you need to understand tools and tricks.
YOU1000000118_S0000043	that are borrowed from images and from sequences.
YOU1000000118_S0000044	So that's why we're looking at them in this order. And that's why we look at recommendation engines pretty much at the end of the specialization.
