YOU1000000119_S0000001	Welcome to the first course in the blockchain specialization titled Blockchain Basics.
YOU1000000119_S0000002	Let's start by asking ourselves, what is a blockchain? Why should you care about it?
YOU1000000119_S0000003	Unlike traditional methods, blockchain enables peer-to-peer transfer of digital assets without any intermediaries.
YOU1000000119_S0000004	It was a technology originally created to support the famous cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
YOU1000000119_S0000005	The blockchain by itself has taken a life of its own and permeated a broad range of applications across many industries including finance, healthcare, government, manufacturing and distribution.
YOU1000000119_S0000006	The blockchain is poised to innovate and transform a wide range of applications, including goods transfer, for example, supply chain, digital media transfer, for example, sale of art.
YOU1000000119_S0000007	Remote services delivery, example, travel and tourism, platform for decentralized business logic, for example, moving computing to data sources.
YOU1000000119_S0000008	and distributed intelligence example, education and credentialing.
YOU1000000119_S0000009	Additional applications of blockchain include distributed resources, for example, power generation and distribution.
YOU1000000119_S0000010	crowdfunding for example startup fundraising, crowd operation for example electronic voting, identity management for example, one ID for all your life's functions.
YOU1000000119_S0000011	and government public records and open governing.
YOU1000000119_S0000013	Moreover, blockchain can enable an inclusive economy. It can enable a person in a remote corner of the world to partake in a democratic process.
YOU1000000119_S0000014	Opportunities for innovative applications are endless.
YOU1000000119_S0000015	There is a dire need for critical thinkers, designers, and developers who can envision and create newer application models on blockchain to benefit the world.
YOU1000000119_S0000016	This course is a first step in addressing this need.
YOU1000000119_S0000017	At the end of this course, you will be able to explain the three fundamental characteristics that define the blockchain using Bitcoin blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000018	Bitcoin is not the only player in town. By the end of the first module, we'll move beyond Bitcoin into introducing the next generation blockchains with Ethereum.
YOU1000000119_S0000020	You will also be able to discuss the important features of Ethereum blockchain that is used as a reference implementation in many newer blockchains.
YOU1000000119_S0000021	and explain the algorithms and techniques that enable the blockchain, including a public key cryptography and hashing.
YOU1000000119_S0000022	Finally, you will be able to outline methods for realizing trust in a blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000024	Let's begin with an introduction of Bitcoin.
YOU1000000119_S0000025	Two major contributions of cryptocurrency Bitcoin are a continuously working digital currency system and a model for autonomous decentralized application technology called the blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000027	Though our focus is on a general blockchain, we have to understand the working of the technology behind Bitcoin to fully appreciate the innovation of blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000029	We can all agree that the advent of the internet and the World Wide Web has transformed every aspect of our lives from stock markets to street corner food trucks.
YOU1000000119_S0000030	It has enabled the technology explosion with Web 2.0 and the world of e-commerce applications.
YOU1000000119_S0000031	Around 2008, 2009, when the institutions and markets we trusted were crumbling down and everybody was running away from the Wall Street.
YOU1000000119_S0000032	a mysterious person or persons called Satoshi Nakamoto introduced a new digital currency, a cryptocurrency called Bitcoin.
YOU1000000119_S0000034	Bitcoin enabled an innovative platform for peer-to-peer transfer of value without any central authority.
YOU1000000119_S0000036	With no central authority, how did Bitcoin realize trust and security?
YOU1000000119_S0000037	by implementing software programs for validation, verification, consensus in a novel infrastructure called the blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000039	Later on, in about 2012-2013, computational elements were added to the blockchain infrastructure
YOU1000000119_S0000040	that has opened up a whole world of possibilities beyond simple currency transfer.
YOU1000000119_S0000041	These innovations are significantly shaping the direction of Web 3.0 as you will learn in the next four courses.
YOU1000000119_S0000043	What is a blockchain? Blockchain is about enabling peer-to-peer transaction in a decentralized network.
YOU1000000119_S0000044	establishing trust among unknown peers.
YOU1000000119_S0000045	recording the transaction in an immutable distributed ledger.
YOU1000000119_S0000047	Let's understand centralized versus decentralized network using a common scenario.
YOU1000000119_S0000048	Consider a scenario where a customer wants to buy an item using her credit card.
YOU1000000119_S0000050	Let's enumerate the intermediaries involved in accomplishing this task.
YOU1000000119_S0000051	We have a credit card agency, we have a customer bank, we have a credit cards bank, we have an exchange, we have the merchants bank and finally the merchant.
YOU1000000119_S0000053	This is an example of a centralized system that we are so used to.
YOU1000000119_S0000054	Now, compare this with a system where peers can transact directly with each other irrespective of where they are located.
YOU1000000119_S0000056	functions of the intermediaries are shifted to the periphery, to the peer participant in the blockchain infrastructure.
YOU1000000119_S0000057	peers are not necessarily known to each other. This is a decentralized system.
YOU1000000119_S0000058	How do we establish trust among the peers in such a decentralized system?
YOU1000000119_S0000059	by having a process in place to validate, verify, and confirm transactions.
YOU1000000119_S0000060	record the transaction in a distributed ledger of blocks.
YOU1000000119_S0000061	Create a tamper-proof record of blocks, chain of blocks.
YOU1000000119_S0000063	and implement a consensus protocol for agreement on the block to be added to the chain.
YOU1000000119_S0000064	So, validation, verification, consensus and immutable recording lead to the trust and security of the blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000066	Now I'll explain these concepts using another scenario.
YOU1000000119_S0000068	I'm lending Amy $10,000. This is one single peer-to-peer transaction.
YOU1000000119_S0000069	We both make a note of it on a ledger.
YOU1000000119_S0000070	What if I change my entry from 10,000 to 11,000?
YOU1000000119_S0000071	Alternatively, Amy changes hers from 10,000 to 1,000.
YOU1000000119_S0000072	To prevent this trust violation, we need to seek the help of people around us, Lisa, Allison and Francis.
YOU1000000119_S0000073	provide all of them a valid copy of this lecture.
YOU1000000119_S0000074	This is the basic concept of an immutable distributed ledger defined in a blockchain process.
YOU1000000119_S0000076	In this scenario, we were all physically present in one location, Amherst.
YOU1000000119_S0000077	Now, imagine this to be an online transaction.
YOU1000000119_S0000078	to an unknown peer, also scale up the one transaction to 10,000 transactions. How about a million transactions?
YOU1000000119_S0000079	I should be able to transact with equal ease to any unknown peer in Amherst, Albany, or Albania.
YOU1000000119_S0000080	maybe to send some flowers to a friend in Albania. This is the tenet of a decentralized system supported by blockchain.
YOU1000000119_S0000082	In the case just described, how do we trust our unknown peers?
YOU1000000119_S0000083	through verification and validation. In our example, Amy requests Kevin to verify the amount I transacted with her.
YOU1000000119_S0000085	Kevin checks it, oops, Kevin finds the amount of transaction is not 10,000 but 300, not valid.
YOU1000000119_S0000086	Kevin rejects and nullifies the transaction. Similar to this, validation and verification methods defined by the blockchain
YOU1000000119_S0000087	and implemented by the peers provide the collective trust needed in a decentralized system.
YOU1000000119_S0000088	Summarizing, blockchain technology supports methods for a decentralized peer-to-peer system, a collective trust model,
YOU1000000119_S0000089	and the distributed immutable ledger of records of transactions.
