YOU1000000122_S0000001	Take a look at these two photos of outer space. What do you see? They're basically identical, but not quite. Now look a different way, in sequence.
YOU1000000122_S0000002	Here, you see something different, something moving. That dot is a newly discovered world. It's closer than we ever thought possible.
YOU1000000122_S0000003	And the trick we used to find it could rewrite the story of our cosmic neighborhood.
YOU1000000122_S0000005	Today, scientists have our solar system pretty well mapped out. We know about the eight planets, Pluto, moons, asteroids, comets.
YOU1000000122_S0000006	And until recently, we thought we had a handle on our solar neighborhood, too.
YOU1000000122_S0000008	There's the Alpha Centauri system about four light years away, and Barnard's star, a red dwarf a little farther out.
YOU1000000122_S0000009	Astronomers made these discoveries more than 100 years ago.
YOU1000000122_S0000010	But today, some new work is totally upending our view of the neighborhood. It involves a space telescope, an army of volunteers, and a scientist on a very specific mission.
YOU1000000122_S0000011	My name is Jackie Farrity and I'm an astrophysicist at the American Museum of Natural History.
YOU1000000122_S0000012	Jackie has spent 15 years searching our solar neighborhood for new neighbors.
YOU1000000122_S0000013	She's focused on mysterious worlds known as brown dwarfs, balls of gas that are too big to be planets, but too small to be stars.
YOU1000000122_S0000014	Now, they're often called failed stars, but I really dislike the word failure in the title.
YOU1000000122_S0000015	because I just feel like it's kind of demeaning to the brown dwarf.
YOU1000000122_S0000016	like it needs to be a star, it doesn't care. And so oftentimes I call them over-excited planets.
YOU1000000122_S0000017	Brown dwarfs would be stars if they were more massive, but without enough hydrogen, they don't achieve nuclear fusion.
YOU1000000122_S0000018	They emit lots of infrared energy, but very little visible light.
YOU1000000122_S0000019	So for a long time, they were hidden to astronomers. But that all changed in the 90s.
YOU1000000122_S0000020	Infrared technology and infrared telescopes started to come online in earnest. And when that happens, you start to see these sky surveys.
YOU1000000122_S0000021	that are able to produce the wavelengths where you can actually see the brown dwarfs.
YOU1000000122_S0000022	The first brown dwarfs were ID'd around 1995, and since then, the field has exploded.
YOU1000000122_S0000023	Today, the astronomy community is awash in imagery that could harbor nearby brown dwarfs.
YOU1000000122_S0000024	Actually, finding them is another story. But there's an old technique called the blink method that works wonders.
YOU1000000122_S0000025	The basic idea is that all stars are in motion relative to us. Most are so far away that they move imperceptibly.
YOU1000000122_S0000026	But objects in our solar neighborhood, those are close enough that we can actually catch their movement, if we're patient enough.
YOU1000000122_S0000027	Here are four images taken with various telescopes over a span of 32 years.
YOU1000000122_S0000028	If you flip or blink through them, you see that not everything is staying put.
YOU1000000122_S0000029	Objects of interest that are in the nearby vicinity, they will move, they will jump against the background of stars.
YOU1000000122_S0000030	That is Lumen 16, a pair of brown dwarfs that's only 6.5 light-years from Earth. It was discovered using the blink method in 2013.
YOU1000000122_S0000031	and it's now the third closest known system to ours.
YOU1000000122_S0000032	We had not changed that list of objects in the top five in a century. It shouldn't happen.
YOU1000000122_S0000033	We should not be finding objects all of a sudden that are spitting distance away from us that we've been missing all this time.
YOU1000000122_S0000034	The Blink method isn't new. Clyde Tombaugh used it to discover Pluto back in 1930, and it's been used to discover moons, asteroids, and dwarf planets.
YOU1000000122_S0000035	But paired with new infrared imagery, it's slowly bringing our neighborhood into focus. A little too slowly, really.
YOU1000000122_S0000036	A few years back, Jackie found herself staring down millions of images that could contain new discoveries. It was daunting.
YOU1000000122_S0000037	I am spending hours of my time every week blinking images in my spare time.
YOU1000000122_S0000038	and I can't, it's just, it's frustrating. It's taking too much time and I'll never get through all of it.
YOU1000000122_S0000039	The images are noisy and blurry and each one needed real attention. It was far too much for any team to handle.
YOU1000000122_S0000041	Unless that team were hundreds of thousands of people.
YOU1000000122_S0000042	And so thus sprung our Citizen Science Project.
YOU1000000122_S0000043	At the beginning, my girlfriends didn't understand why I was looking for just a bunch of moving pixels for hours.
YOU1000000122_S0000044	Starting in 2017, Jackie and her team invited the entire internet to go hunting for brown dwarfs.
YOU1000000122_S0000045	Their system is dead simple. Users log into a website and meet their first astronomy flipbook.
YOU1000000122_S0000046	The images come in a sequence of four and it will flip, those images flip through time. So it shows you what this point in space looked like.
YOU1000000122_S0000047	in this year and then a little bit after and then a little after and then a little after.
YOU1000000122_S0000048	You'll kind of see blue and orange dots typically that are everywhere.
YOU1000000122_S0000049	It looks like you're staring at colorful television static.
YOU1000000122_S0000050	It can be kind of annoying at first if you don't quite know what you're looking for.
YOU1000000122_S0000051	But if you're lucky, you'll catch a mover.
YOU1000000122_S0000052	When you finally find something moving, it's a bit of an adrenaline rush.
YOU1000000122_S0000053	Faster-moving objects actually do blink across the screen. Slower ones might just twinkle.
YOU1000000122_S0000054	They're basically these little tiny white dots that will flash when you play our flip books.
YOU1000000122_S0000055	Either way, you can mark your anomaly and alert the community.
YOU1000000122_S0000057	I think I found something and everyone else kind of is like, yeah, yeah, that's one. It's like, ah, yes, I'm good. I found something.
YOU1000000122_S0000058	The most promising leads end up on Jackie's radar. Her team can then book telescope time to look more closely. For you, citizen scientist, it's back to blinking.
YOU1000000122_S0000059	It's like in a world, it's like a treasure hunt in your couch. It's really something that keeps you hooked.
YOU1000000122_S0000060	Since Backyard Worlds launched, volunteers have been on a tear.
YOU1000000122_S0000061	They've discovered hundreds, hundreds of nearby objects.
YOU1000000122_S0000062	Some were a novel kind of compact frozen world.
YOU1000000122_S0000063	Prior to Backyard Worlds, there was only 24 of them known. They added five new ones.
YOU1000000122_S0000064	Others had surprising new atmospheres.
YOU1000000122_S0000065	really strange looking objects.
YOU1000000122_S0000066	And still others were hidden siblings of known objects.
YOU1000000122_S0000067	I had certainly studied the brown dwarf in the system a lot in previous work and never did I guess that it had a little cold companion with it.
YOU1000000122_S0000068	All in, hundreds of thousands of users have found more than 1,500 new objects.
YOU1000000122_S0000069	Volunteers like Dan and Guillaume have gotten credits and academic papers for their discoveries.
YOU1000000122_S0000070	There's still more to find. Jackie thinks the effort could reveal a brown dwarf even closer than Alpha Centauri.
YOU1000000122_S0000071	A new next-door neighbor. There's even a chance we could find the Bigfoot of our solar system. Planet 9.
YOU1000000122_S0000072	There is an object that's theorized to exist beyond Pluto that is massive, that it could be causing some objects in the outer solar system to be bumped around a bit.
YOU1000000122_S0000073	And it's an exciting prospect. Now, does it exist? I don't know. I'm happy that we have citizens that are very interested in trying to find it.
YOU1000000122_S0000074	If it's real, if it's there, and maybe it is.
YOU1000000122_S0000076	As successful as the blink method is, it has competition. Artificial intelligence has been huge for astronomers who need to sift through tons of imagery, including Jackie.
YOU1000000122_S0000077	The human eye is beautiful at picking out things.
YOU1000000122_S0000078	It's just slow because we have to go image by image. And so, human eye wins in some ways, but AI wins in speed. So, I use both.
YOU1000000122_S0000079	One limitation of AI is that it needs to train using examples of things that it's looking for. So if that thing is brand new, human brains have the edge.
YOU1000000122_S0000080	You are the trained algorithm at that point.
YOU1000000122_S0000081	That said, astronomy is facing a total wave of data.
YOU1000000122_S0000082	In a couple years, astronomers will begin imaging the entire night sky of the Southern Hemisphere, twice a week.
YOU1000000122_S0000083	There is no way we are looking through all of the data in the classic ways in the coming future. Like, it's over.
YOU1000000122_S0000084	For now, Jackie will take all the help she can get, from human volunteers to algorithms. The humans are more enthusiastic about it.
YOU1000000122_S0000085	You spend countless hours pouring through images and designing custom algorithms and services and you get something great.
YOU1000000122_S0000086	It's super exciting to see that all of this work that we put in has an impact.
YOU1000000122_S0000087	You can say to yourself, yeah, it's something I saw.
