YOU1000000124_S0000073	So, I'm going to explain, many of you know this already, but I'm going to explain what large-measuring neuron is. It's a little computational device.
YOU1000000124_S0000074	It's a little bit like a real neuron, but not very. It takes some inputs, coming typically from other neurons. It has weights on the connections.
YOU1000000124_S0000075	He takes the inputs times the weights, adds it up, that's his total input, and then he puts it through a nonlinear function.
YOU1000000124_S0000076	That nonlinear function on the right there is what we mostly use now, and that's its output.
YOU1000000124_S0000077	So basically that nonlinear function simply says, if you've got a lot of input, give a lot of output, and if your input's below the threshold, don't give any output.
YOU1000000124_S0000078	So it's called a rectified leading edge.
YOU1000000124_S0000080	And the question is, if you hook together a bunch of those guys, and you figure out a way to make those weights on the connections adapt, what can you do with it?
YOU1000000124_S0000082	So we typically hook them together by making multiple layers. This again is sort of neurally inspired. And if you look at a multi-layer neural network like that,
YOU1000000124_S0000084	The layers in the middle, it's hard to figure out what the weights should be. When you adapt those weights, in effect you're deciding what features
YOU1000000124_S0000085	the neurons in the middle edge should detect. So the problem of adapting those weights is the problem of deciding what intermediate features do you want. They're the same problem.
YOU1000000124_S0000087	Now I'm going to show you a way of learning those features that's really stupid.
YOU1000000124_S0000088	But we'll definitely work. We're going to give it inputs, and we're going to tell it what the right answer is.
YOU1000000124_S0000089	And then we're going to adapt the weights one at a time.
YOU1000000124_S0000091	So suppose we want something that will tell the difference between pictures of cats and pictures of dogs. We give it two out, that's one for cat and one for dog.
YOU1000000124_S0000092	And if you show a cat, and the apple for dog is higher than the apple for cat, that's bad. So we can show a bunch of pictures and measure how well it's doing.
YOU1000000124_S0000094	And then we can pick one of the weights in the network, and we can change the value of that weight.
YOU1000000124_S0000096	And we can see if the network is doing better or worse than it was before. To see that, you need to show a bunch of examples.
YOU1000000124_S0000097	If the change worked, we keep it. And then we do it again, but another way.
YOU1000000124_S0000099	Now, I think you can see that that algorithm is going to have to show a bunch of examples for each weight. And if you've got a million weights, it's going to be extremely slow.
YOU1000000124_S0000101	But that's what we want to do. We want to change weights in the direction that makes them help. That's all we're trying to do. We're just trying to do that efficiently.
YOU1000000124_S0000102	And back propagation, which many of you know, but I'm not going to explain that.
YOU1000000124_S0000103	It's just an efficient way of computing how to change the weights in the direction that will help reduce the discrepancy between what the network outputs and what you'd like it to output.
YOU1000000124_S0000105	And the big difference is that if you perturb the weights, you measure the effects of a change of weight on the output.
YOU1000000124_S0000106	And with backpropagation you compute the effects. So if you know all the weights in the network, you don't have to measure, you compute.
YOU1000000124_S0000107	And when you compute, you can compute for all the weights at the same time, what direction you should change them to have.
YOU1000000124_S0000108	You can't do that when you're measuring. You have to change the one at a time.
YOU1000000124_S0000110	So computing is much more efficient than measuring. Evolution can't do the same measuring, can't do the same computing. In evolution you change a gene.
YOU1000000124_S0000111	And then there's a whole developmental process in the environment, and you don't know all that, so you can't back up again.
YOU1000000124_S0000113	So what evolution did was it came up with a brain so that it could use that cognition. That's my theory.
YOU1000000124_S0000114	So in backpropagation, you go forwards through these layers, you compare with the correct answer, you backpropagate signals, that allows you to compute for each weight what direction to change it in, to make it work better.
YOU1000000124_S0000116	And we thought in the 80s that was problem-solved. We had come out and done lots of those. And it didn't work very well.
YOU1000000124_S0000118	And we didn't know why it didn't work. Most people thought it didn't work because this is a stupid idea. That is, the idea that you would take a network with random weights,
YOU1000000124_S0000119	And you just show the world data. As a result of seeing this data, it will be able to design all its own feature detectors.
YOU1000000124_S0000120	and do very good performance of things like machine translation or recognizing objects in images or recognizing speech.
YOU1000000124_S0000122	Almost everybody in AI thought that idea was completely crazy. A few of us didn't. A few of us just thought, we don't know why it's not working.
YOU1000000124_S0000123	It's obviously the right thing to do. And we discovered later, the reason it wasn't working was because computers were too slow and data sets weren't big enough.
YOU1000000124_S0000124	If you'd said that in the 80s, people would have said, oh yeah, sure, if you had a bigger computer and more data it would work. But look, it doesn't work. It turned out I was right.
YOU1000000124_S0000125	And when we got a bigger computer and more data, it worked. Now there were some technical things too, but it was mainly the increasing computer speed and data size that mattered.
