YOU1000000124_S0000174	So people in symbolic AR, I mean, we all agree that symbols come in and symbols come out. Okay?
YOU1000000124_S0000175	The question is, what's in between? Is it just more symbols?
YOU1000000124_S0000176	So the classic AI view is symbols come in, what's inside is sort of like symbols, it's sort of cleaned up symbols.
YOU1000000124_S0000177	It's symbolic expressions. And you do manipulations on symbolic expressions, and then another symbol string comes out. So it's called symbols.
YOU1000000124_S0000179	The biological view would be symbols come in. They're the way we code things to go over a communication channel.
YOU1000000124_S0000180	They resist noise nicely. Once the symbols have come in, they get converted into things that are nothing like those symbols.
YOU1000000124_S0000182	So the point about a symbol is it only has basically one property. A symbol either is or is not identical to another symbol.
YOU1000000124_S0000184	If you take two different symbols, the only problem that matters is, are they the same symbol?
YOU1000000124_S0000186	OK? All the other properties are just...
YOU1000000124_S0000188	Well, it's a property of the symbol that are not relevant to the process.
YOU1000000124_S0000190	In neural nets, what happens is a symbol comes in, and it gets converted into a great big vector that has all sorts of features.
YOU1000000124_S0000191	that capture lots of knowledge about the meaning of that word.
YOU1000000124_S0000193	And words that mean similar things but don't look similar, like Friday and Wednesday.
YOU1000000124_S0000195	They mean pretty similar things. They're distinct symbols.
YOU1000000124_S0000197	There's nothing, well, there's the morpheming structure of Dane, so that's a bad example, but basically,
YOU1000000124_S0000199	They're distinct symbols, and that's all a symbol processing system learns. In a neural net, it learns that Wednesday and Friday are very, very similar things. And we'll see that later.
YOU1000000124_S0000201	So the symbolic AI-critical machine translation is to say, OK, a simple string comes in in English.
YOU1000000124_S0000202	We're going to do some manipulations using rules, and we're clearly going to use rules of grammar. We're also going to use semantic rules that somehow do compositional semantics.
YOU1000000124_S0000203	That is, given what the individual pieces mean, they figure out what a group of pieces must mean. And then we're going to produce symbols coming in.
YOU1000000124_S0000205	and we're going to use all the knowledge that linguists have about how language works.
YOU1000000124_S0000207	The neural network approach. Now, even I thought this was a bit crazy, a bit ambitious.
YOU1000000124_S0000208	is to say, let's just take a whole bunch of translations, pairs of an English sentence and a French sentence.
YOU1000000124_S0000210	And we'll stick in the English sentence one word at a time. And then we'll go into a recurrent neural network, which I'll explain in a minute, where things cycle around inside.
YOU1000000124_S0000212	And after we finish sticking the English sentence, that recurrent neural network will have some particular state of activity. And we'll call that a thought vector.
YOU1000000124_S0000214	That's what a thought is. It's the state of activity of the neural net after it's read the English sentence.
