YOU1000000130_S0000000	Henry Ford, one of the most influential American industrialists. Through his company, Henry transformed American life and in this video we're gonna learn how he did it, starting from the very beginning.
YOU1000000130_S0000002	This video is brought to you by Audible, and a big part of it is based on Henry Ford's biography, which you can listen to for free on Audible if you register for a free trial with the link in the description.
YOU1000000130_S0000003	You should also check out Real Engineering's video on the manufacturing innovations of the assembly line, which he explains masterfully on his channel.
YOU1000000130_S0000005	By all accounts, Henry Ford should have been a farmer. Born in Michigan barely twenty years after it had become a state,
YOU1000000130_S0000006	Henry grew up at a time when farming was slow, exhausting, and manual, which is why unsurprisingly he came to hate it with a passion. But whereas most people at the time didn't have the fortune to escape what they were born into,
YOU1000000130_S0000007	Henry was lucky enough to get such an opportunity. You see, the village he was born into was just 8 miles west of Detroit, which was rapidly becoming an industrial center thanks to the steam engine.
YOU1000000130_S0000008	Early on in his childhood Henry encountered technology which few children his age could play around with.
YOU1000000130_S0000009	He'd tinker with the watches of his better-off neighbors and by the time he was 12 he could not just take them apart, but also put them back together and repair them.
YOU1000000130_S0000010	His interest grew into an obsession when he got to observe a working steam engine first-hand while on a school trip to one of the rail companies in Detroit.
YOU1000000130_S0000011	By the time Henry had become a teenager, the steam engine was already making its way into the farming community. Coal-powered threshing machines and sawmills were becoming common sight and Henry was learning how they worked and how to fix them.
YOU1000000130_S0000012	At the age of 16 he made a big leap forward when against his father's wishes he left his village to go work in Detroit, where any young mechanic could easily find very lucrative employment.
YOU1000000130_S0000013	Industry in Detroit was booming and it had been doing so for close to five decades. In 1825 a canal had been dug, connecting the Hudson River to the Great Lakes, which at the time were effectively their western frontier.
YOU1000000130_S0000014	All the untapped resources that had no way of getting out could suddenly be moved by steamboat to New York and in the span of just 50 years Detroit's population increased by a factor of 10.
YOU1000000130_S0000015	with vast mines in the north producing copper and iron and lumber mills opening up virtually everywhere.
YOU1000000130_S0000016	All this metal and wood sustained close to a thousand companies in Detroit alone, including the ones in which Henry would work at over the course of the 1880s.
YOU1000000130_S0000017	It is during this time that Henry by chance learned about the gas engine from a British magazine. It was being produced in small numbers by a German engineer, Nicholas Otto.
YOU1000000130_S0000018	and it was gaining some traction in Europe, but it was practically unheard of in America. Henry would get the chance to work on such an engine himself in 1889 and he instantly recognized the advantages it had.
YOU1000000130_S0000019	Because it did not use steam, the engine was much lighter and got rid of the heavy boiler and all the water in it because it did all the combustion internally, a much more efficient process.
YOU1000000130_S0000020	This also allowed the gas engine to start quickly, whereas steam engines of the time needed as much as 30 minutes to heat up the water and generate enough steam to start working. The gas engine was an innovation Henry fell in love with.
YOU1000000130_S0000021	but it was also one he didn't fully understand. After all, he had extensive experience with steam and metal, but almost none with electricity, and the gas engine was fired by an electric spark.
YOU1000000130_S0000022	To obtain this missing knowledge, Henry went to work for the local branch of the Edison Illuminating Company.
YOU1000000130_S0000023	It was generating electricity for over a thousand homes in Detroit and it was doing so by using steam engines, so Henry was a natural hire for them. Whenever the engines broke, Henry had to fix them, but whenever they were working,
YOU1000000130_S0000024	he was free to do as he wished. It was the perfect job that allowed him to spend his days experimenting with gas engines. In 1893, when Henry had already been promoted to chief engineer at Edison,
YOU1000000130_S0000025	he created his first working gas engine. The idea of using the gas engine to create a horseless carriage had been around in Henry's mind since he first laid eyes on one, but actually making that idea a reality would take years of work.
YOU1000000130_S0000026	Building a car in a world with no car parts wasn't easy, and Henry had to figure out every detail through trial and error. It took him three years of constant effort to produce this, the quadricycle.
YOU1000000130_S0000027	A simple frame with an engine powered by ethanol and four bicycle wheels mounted onto it. It had only two gears, and neither one was for going in reverse, but what's worse is that it had no cooling system to speak of.
YOU1000000130_S0000028	thus making overheating a constant issue. In its first year, Henry made numerous improvements to the quadricycle, most notably adding a cooling system and by the time he sold it in 1897 for $200,
YOU1000000130_S0000029	he had driven a thousand miles in it. Henry built a second quadricycle and then a third one, always improving the design, before finally feeling confident enough in 1899 to start his own company.
YOU1000000130_S0000031	capitalized at $150,000, the Detroit Automobile Company was a very ambitious venture. Many of the Detroit elite invested in it, including Henry's friends from the Edison Company,
YOU1000000130_S0000032	and everyone was eager to see what Henry could create with proper capital. Henry's plan was very clever, since he personally knew many of the industrialists in Detroit by that point, he'd try to build an automobile they could use in their businesses.
YOU1000000130_S0000033	He leased a factory and planned to hire a hundred workers to make his new delivery wagon, as he called it. But it turned out that building such complex machines in high numbers was much more difficult than Henry imagined.
YOU1000000130_S0000034	The vast majority of the parts used in the making of the delivery wagon were produced by other companies and every time a single delivery was late, the entire factory would have no choice but to stop working.
YOU1000000130_S0000035	The first delivery wagon took six months to produce, and no more than 20 were made in the first two years of the company's existence. By the end of 1902, the other shareholders were sick of Henry's lack of progress,
YOU1000000130_S0000036	and actually voted to get rid of him. Now, because Henry held only 15% of the company, he had no choice but to comply.
YOU1000000130_S0000037	And, interestingly enough, the man who took over the Detroit Automobile Company would eventually transform it into Cadillac. But that's a story for a different time. What matters is that Henry was pushed out of his own company.
YOU1000000130_S0000038	and had only a thousand dollars to his name. It was back to the drawing board and this time Henry would take a very different approach. Instead of targeting businesses with expensive machines, Henry would design a vehicle to be used by the average man.
YOU1000000130_S0000039	You see, at the time virtually all cars were high-ticket items. They were mostly made by skilled craftsmen, one at a time, and more often than not were designed for racing, which was rapidly becoming a favorite American activity.
YOU1000000130_S0000040	Henry envisioned turning the car from a status symbol into a commodity, but doing that would not be easy and in fact it took Henry 20 different design iterations before he finally got one that worked.
YOU1000000130_S0000041	Henry labeled his first design as the Model A and worked his way through the alphabet over the next five years, sustained by capital from his friends and family.
YOU1000000130_S0000042	But what changed the most during this time is not the car itself, but the production process. Henry learned the importance of having a reliable supply chain when his first company failed, which is why this time around
YOU1000000130_S0000043	he tried getting as many parts as possible from the same manufacturer. The one he chose will probably sound familiar, the Dodge Brothers company, a machine shop in Detroit that would eventually evolve into the eponymous American brand.
YOU1000000130_S0000044	The biggest game-changer of all, however, was Henry's chance visit to a slaughterhouse in Chicago. He saw there something interesting, a disassembly line, so to speak, where multiple workers would process carcasses moving down a line.
YOU1000000130_S0000045	Henry figured he could use the same process but in reverse, an assembly line. Using the money he had saved from some of his earlier models, which were also assembled by the Dodge Brothers,
YOU1000000130_S0000046	Henry was able to build a factory of his own in 1904 where he could experiment with the assembly line process. By 1905, the Ford factory employed over 300 people that built 25 cars a day
YOU1000000130_S0000047	but Henry still hadn't figured everything out. He was producing multiple different models at the same time, which prevented him from properly using an assembly line.
YOU1000000130_S0000048	Nevertheless, there was a sign of things to come. The affordable Model N, created in 1906, became the best-selling car in the US and Ford became the biggest car producer in America.
YOU1000000130_S0000049	It is actually during the production of this model that Henry would first use the assembly line process to at least partially assemble some of his cars.
YOU1000000130_S0000050	It wasn't a full moving assembly line, but nevertheless, this experiment increased production by a factor of 5 in the same factory. Logistics, of course, was another big part of Henry's success.
YOU1000000130_S0000051	In 1905 he created the Ford Manufacturing Company, complete with its own factory, to start making the engines and transmissions of Henry's cars to further eliminate any possibility of delays.
YOU1000000130_S0000052	But the biggest factor in Henry's success came from perhaps the most unexpected place. Peru. Now this is a story you're not gonna hear anywhere else, so listen carefully.
YOU1000000130_S0000053	In 1907 Henry began construction of a heat treatment plant to produce Vanadium steel.
YOU1000000130_S0000054	This alloy was new to America. In fact, few furnaces in the US could even reach the temperature needed to manufacture it. The difficulty in producing it, however, was worth it.
YOU1000000130_S0000055	because vanadium steel was more than twice as strong as regular steel while actually being lighter. Now, at the time, vanadium metallurgy was cutting-edge research.
YOU1000000130_S0000056	but Henry had an extremely lucky connection. He was friends with the two brothers who owned the 1 Vanadium mine in Peru, producing 92% of the world's supply.
YOU1000000130_S0000057	Joseph and James Flannery had commercialized vanadium steel in Europe and in the US by selling it to rail companies, but their Peruvian mine was producing so much vanadium that they had to do something else with it.
YOU1000000130_S0000059	They sold vanadium steel to the US government for the construction of the Panama Canal, but even that wasn't enough, so when they met Henry in 1906, they immediately made him an offer.
YOU1000000130_S0000060	They would help him transition his entire manufacturing process to use vanadium steel. It was their chief engineer that built the heat treatment plant for Henry in 1907,
YOU1000000130_S0000061	and it was their company that supplied Ford with all the vanadium it needed for its cars. The first Ford car designed with vanadium steel was the Model T in 1908 and it was this alloy that actually made it successful.
YOU1000000130_S0000062	It wasn't the cheapest car Henry had made, the Model N and its upscale versions were actually cheaper, but it didn't need to be, because it was by far the best car built at the time, much stronger than any competitor.
YOU1000000130_S0000063	The sheer difference in quality was the only marketing Henry needed and within weeks of the Model T's release, Ford received 25,000 orders for it.
YOU1000000130_S0000064	even though it managed to produce only 17,000 units for the entirety of 1909. Henry realized just how big of a deal the Model T was, which is why he built a second factory in 1910.
YOU1000000130_S0000065	and it is there that he would perfect the moving assembly line in 1913. During this period production would double every year. In 1910 he built 20,000 Model Ts
YOU1000000130_S0000066	and just six years later he was building over half a million. At the same time, Henry adopted another brilliant strategy, he was constantly reducing the price of his cars to further increase his market share.
YOU1000000130_S0000067	In fact, during these six years, he cut the Model Ts price by more than half. By 1918, half of all cars in America were Model Ts and this trend would continue well into the 1920s.
YOU1000000130_S0000068	Henry had begun a new age in American history, the age of the automobile, and it was his company that would totally dominate it in its first two decades.
YOU1000000130_S0000069	It wasn't until the end of the 1920s that the rest of the auto industry caught up to Henry, but at that point he was already one of the richest men alive.
YOU1000000130_S0000070	In 1922 he actually took the time to write an autobiography, where parts of this video came from and which you can listen to for free as part of your 30-day free trial of Audible.
YOU1000000130_S0000071	In his book, Henry not only recounts his experiences in a very eloquent fashion, he also shares plenty of business advice that is actually still relevant today.
YOU1000000130_S0000072	You should visit audible.com slash businesscasual or you can text businesscasual to 500-500 to get started with Audible, who have the biggest collection of audiobooks in the world.
YOU1000000130_S0000073	And if you're more into the manufacturing side of things, you should check out the video my friend Brian from Real Engineering made on exactly this topic. He will walk you through the beauty of the assembly line that made the automobile miracle possible.
YOU1000000130_S0000074	So you should definitely head on over to his channel, which I'm certain you're gonna enjoy. In case you also enjoyed this video, I'd like to thank you for watching it, and I'd also like to encourage you to share it around with your friends.
YOU1000000130_S0000075	You can expect my next video in two weeks, and until then stay smart.
YOU1000000131_S0000000	When you look at the wealthiest men alive today, topping the charts are tech billionaires like Jeff Bezos and Bill Gates. But actually, the wealthiest businessman to have ever lived died almost a century ago.
YOU1000000131_S0000001	In today's video, we'll be looking at a business empire so vast that even after a hundred years of technological progress, no man has managed to overtake its founder. This is the history of Standard Oil.
YOU1000000131_S0000003	This video is brought to you by Dollar Shave Club. Visit the link in the description to learn about the awesome deal they're offering.
YOU1000000131_S0000005	The origins of history's greatest oil monopoly are actually pretty humble. It all starts in 1839 with the birth of John Rockefeller in upstate New York. He was the eldest son of a traveling merchant.
YOU1000000131_S0000006	who identified himself as a botanic physician but in reality was selling the 19th century equivalent of homeopathic medicine.
YOU1000000131_S0000007	He would spend weeks away from home and in fact would have several children with another woman, who he decided to bring back home to his wife
YOU1000000131_S0000008	so they could all live together. In this very confusing household, John would grow up learning how to hustle people for the best deal possible and how to get the most out of every penny he got. His family would rarely stay in one place for long,
YOU1000000131_S0000009	and John would live this nomadic lifestyle ever since he was three years old. To help his mother, John would earn any money he could by raising turkeys or doing work for neighbors. His intelligence was put to good use
YOU1000000131_S0000010	when the family moved to Cleveland, Ohio in 1854, where he got the chance to attend a proper school. But less than a year later, John dropped out in order to work as a bookkeeper at a local produce broker. He would earn 50 cents per day.
YOU1000000131_S0000011	which obviously wasn't much at the time, so he would help other companies on the side. But after two years of working there his bosses refused to give him a meaningful raise, so he decided to one-up them by starting his own produce brokerage.
YOU1000000131_S0000012	Thanks to his good reputation, he got a loan of $4,000, which at the time was a huge sum. John started trading hay, grain and various meats and in his first year he recorded sales of half a million dollars.
YOU1000000131_S0000013	of which he only got a small fraction as commissions, but still it was a huge success. Every bank in Cleveland was begging John to borrow money, and he was barely 18 years old. But then in 1859
YOU1000000131_S0000014	something happened that would change his life forever. Just a hundred miles east of Cleveland, the first American oil well had been discovered. This marked the beginning of the Pennsylvania oil rush and within a year,
YOU1000000131_S0000015	4,500 barrels of oil would be produced. Now, back then oil wasn't quite as valuable as it is today. Gasoline cars hadn't been invented yet, but oil could still be processed into kerosene, which people would then use in lamps.
YOU1000000131_S0000016	John realized, however, that the biggest profits to be had weren't in drilling for oil, but in refining it. He witnessed many people going bust before striking oil, so he knew that the business was too risky for him.
YOU1000000131_S0000017	Instead, he'd let others go through the hassle of finding the oil and he would just buy it off of them. John had to wait until 1863 for the government to build a rail line connecting the Pennsylvania oil fields to Cleveland.
YOU1000000131_S0000018	But when that line was built, John was ready for it, with a long line of partners and banks ready to back him up. He also assembled a team of seasoned chemists and engineers, who not only optimized the refining process, but also discovered various uses
YOU1000000131_S0000019	for the byproducts of refining petroleum. You see, the early refineries in Cleveland could only operate at about a 60% efficiency, but John not only increased that percentage, he also started selling all the byproducts like paraffin wax
YOU1000000131_S0000020	tar, and naphtha. Within two years, the Rockefeller refinery was worth over $70,000 and was among the largest in Cleveland. But John wasn't done.
YOU1000000131_S0000021	In 1865 there were 26 competing refineries, but within five years John had acquired all but four of them.
YOU1000000131_S0000023	By this point his business was getting too big to handle as a partnership, so in 1870 he incorporated as Standard Oil of Ohio. To convince the few remaining competitors in Cleveland, John would simply invite them over and show them his books.
YOU1000000131_S0000024	revealing that he could operate at a loss far longer than they could stay solvent. In exchange for a good buyout price, John would offer his competitors positions in his own company, thus placing the brightest minds in the industry under his control.
YOU1000000131_S0000025	Of course, not everyone would give up immediately, and over time, John eroded the price of oil and kerosene, sometimes by as much as 80% in order to strangle competitors. Unsurprisingly, his strategy worked.
YOU1000000131_S0000026	By 1880 he had acquired refineries across the northeastern US and was refining over 90% of the entire country's oil production. At this point John was so powerful that he could invite the owners of the big rail companies
YOU1000000131_S0000027	and personally negotiate rebates for using their trains. But this practice of negotiating backroom deals really got the business world riled up. At the time, and still kind of today, most industrial goods were transported by rail.
YOU1000000131_S0000028	and many big industrialists got worried
YOU1000000131_S0000030	that John's abuse of transportation rebates could result in similar monopolization in their industries.
YOU1000000131_S0000031	Over the next decade, businessmen, politicians, and the media would attack Standard Oil with increasing ferocity. Legislators in Ohio began drafting antitrust regulations to bring down Rockefeller, but he was one step ahead.
YOU1000000131_S0000032	In 1882 he reincorporated in New Jersey, this time creating the Standard Oil Trust, which in turn held stakes in over 40 local companies.
YOU1000000131_S0000033	Then, to showcase his success, John built an impressive headquarters for his company on Broadway. This moment was the high point of Rockefeller Standard Oil.
YOU1000000131_S0000034	He owned 20,000 oil wells, 4,000 miles of pipeline and employed over 100,000 people. But his grip on the oil industry was loosening, both domestically and abroad.
YOU1000000131_S0000035	Massive oil deposits had been discovered in Russia and in Asia and were being developed by the Rothschild family, which spared no effort in getting that oil to America.
YOU1000000131_S0000036	Worse yet, in 1890 the federal government passed the Sherman Antitrust Act, which officially gave politicians the teeth to go after the Standard Oil Trust itself.
YOU1000000131_S0000037	Of course, the complex legal structure behind all the companies was very difficult to investigate, which is why the government couldn't actually break up Standard Oil until 1911.
YOU1000000131_S0000038	By that point, however, John Rockefeller had already cashed in and was no longer actively managing the company. In the final 20 years of his company's existence, it had paid out over half a billion dollars in dividends.
YOU1000000131_S0000039	By some estimates, the true worth of Standard Oil at its peak was $1 trillion, so the breakup didn't really come as a surprise to most people. In 1911, the Supreme Court found Standard Oil guilty of anti-competitive practices.
YOU1000000131_S0000040	and broke the company up into 34 separate entities. Of course, John Rockefeller kept his stake in those companies until his death and in fact it turns out that the breakup was the most profitable event in his life.
YOU1000000131_S0000041	You'll see over time many of those companies merged back with one another. Today, most of the standard remnants are part of either ExxonMobil, Chevron or BP, which have since become incredibly large companies in their own right.
YOU1000000131_S0000042	John Rockefeller's ownership of these successor companies made him the richest businessman to have ever lived with an estimated net worth of $400 billion. Even today no one has beaten Rockefeller in the leaderboard.
YOU1000000131_S0000043	Not even Jeff Bezos himself seems likely to achieve that. But there's one thing that Jeff Bezos does have that John Rockefeller never did, despite all his money, and that is access to Dollar Shave Club.
YOU1000000131_S0000044	I mean, look at him, it's clear that this man cares very much about looking and feeling at his very best. But guess what? You too can experience the splendor of Dollar Shave Club's Daily Essentials Starter Set.
YOU1000000131_S0000045	Which, by the way, new members can get for just $5. That set includes shave butter, body wash and One Wipe Charlie's butt wipes to really make you feel special. And if that wasn't enough, you also get their executive razor.
YOU1000000131_S0000046	so really you're getting a heck of a deal. Visit dollarshaveclub.com slash business casual to become a member of a club so prestigious that not even John Rockefeller could get in.
