YOU1000000133_S0000000	The internet has completely changed the way we watch television. Gone are the days when the whole family would gather in the living room to enjoy the exact same program as everyone else.
YOU1000000133_S0000001	Technology has advanced to the point where we've dumped the old immovable boxes in favor of our phones and computers. In today's world, you can watch whatever you want, whenever you want, on demand, straight from the internet.
YOU1000000133_S0000002	We are now in the age of video on demand, and so this week on Behind the Business we'll be taking a look at the company that lies at the heart of this recent revolution, Netflix.
YOU1000000133_S0000004	The year is 1991 and Reed Hastings was getting ready to start his first company. Hastings was a rather unusual tech entrepreneur.
YOU1000000133_S0000005	He came from Minnesota and after graduating from college and serving briefly in the military, he decided to travel to Swaziland with the Peace Corps to teach math.
YOU1000000133_S0000006	After returning to the US and getting a master's in computer science, he and two of his friends started a company in 1991 called Pure Software. The company sold a range of debugging tools for Unix operating systems at a time when there were few good ones on the market.
YOU1000000133_S0000007	and so it rapidly became a big player in the IT world. It doubled its revenue every year for four years in a row, and in 1996 it was sold to Rational Software for 700 million dollars.
YOU1000000133_S0000008	In the span of half a decade Hastings had become a millionaire.
YOU1000000133_S0000009	Life seemed great, but in 1997 he suffered an inconvenience that would eventually become a world changer. Hastings had forgotten to return his video rental of Apollo 13 and as a result was slapped with a $40 late fee.
YOU1000000133_S0000010	He was embarrassed and didn't want to tell his wife, and that got him thinking of a solution. Not just a solution to his own late fee problem, but a solution to everyone's problem. An entirely new system of film rental that would make late fees obsolete.
YOU1000000133_S0000011	Together with a friend of his, on August 29th, 1997 in Scotts Valley, California, Hastings founded a brand new movie rental service called Netflix, with the idea of mailing DVDs to paying customers.
YOU1000000133_S0000012	The creation of Netflix was essentially a bet on the DVD player. Now, the DVD player had been invented in Taiwan in 1994 by Sony, but it wouldn't be until March 1997 that one was first sold in the US.
YOU1000000133_S0000013	Back then, a player cost over a thousand dollars, and when Netflix was formed, less than 1% of Americans actually owned one.
YOU1000000133_S0000014	In a move that seemed insane at the time, Hastings gambled everything on the potential of DVD technology to replace the bulkier, lower-resolution videotape as the nation's format of choice.
YOU1000000133_S0000015	In 1997 it was almost impossible for people to rent DVDs because very few places had any.
YOU1000000133_S0000016	After trying over 200 different mailing packages and testing them out by mailing them to himself, Hastings discovered that he could safely ship a DVD for the small cost of a first-class mailstamp.
YOU1000000133_S0000017	This way Netflix could guarantee that most titles would be in stock, and by enclosing a stamped return mailer, they could make the experience of film rental as convenient as possible.
YOU1000000133_S0000018	This, on April 14th, 1998, with 30 employees and an assortment of 925 titles, Netflix opened for business.
YOU1000000133_S0000019	Their first offer was for a 7-day rental at the price of $4 plus a $2 shipping fee. They also introduced something that is now one of Netflix's proudest hallmarks, smart suggestion algorithms.
YOU1000000133_S0000020	Once a customer had rented enough titles, Netflix could automatically suggest new movies that were likely to interest them. Nowadays, when Google and Facebook know everything about us, it's easy to take such algorithms for granted, but in 1997 they were practically unheard of.
YOU1000000133_S0000021	Netflix started strong, and just 48 hours after opening, they had to upgrade their website's bandwidth due to the excessive traffic they were receiving.
YOU1000000133_S0000022	Soon, Netflix signed promotional deals with Toshiba, Hewlett-Packard and Sony, whereby they offered free rentals to people who bought new DVD players.
YOU1000000133_S0000023	In July 1999, Netflix secured a $30 million capital injection from Group R&O, which allowed them to start a subscription-based service called the Marquee Program.
YOU1000000133_S0000024	For just under $16 per month, customers could rent out as many DVDs as they wanted, as long as they had no more than 4 DVDs at any given time. No late fees, no due dates, it was perfect.
YOU1000000133_S0000025	By that point Netflix was already receiving 10,000 DVD orders every day, but their total revenue was sitting at barely 5 million dollars. Compare this to Blockbuster's four and a half billion dollar revenue and you'll probably see why Netflix decided to try to team up with them.
YOU1000000133_S0000026	Blockbuster was one of the oldest video rental companies and it was by far the largest, with 60,000 employees and 8,000 stores spread across the US.
YOU1000000133_S0000027	As the popularity of Netflix grew, everyone thought Blockbuster would soon enter the market, and with their vast resources, they would have probably crushed their young competitor.
YOU1000000133_S0000028	That's why Netflix decided to act first, and so in the early year 2000 they invited Blockbuster to become a strategic partner and investor.
YOU1000000133_S0000029	Netflix would become the internet arm of the Blockbuster brand, dropping the Netflix name altogether in favor of Blockbuster.com.
YOU1000000133_S0000030	Blockbuster laughed them out of the boardroom. They were certain Netflix would crumble as it had yet to turn a profit three years after its creation. Instead, a few months later, Blockbuster partnered up with Enron Broadband.
YOU1000000133_S0000031	a division of the energy company you probably know today for its notoriously fraudulent accounting practices.
YOU1000000133_S0000033	Of course, at the time nobody knew that, and so investors praised Blockbuster's decision. The situation for Netflix looked grim. They were losing money fast, and by the end of the year they reported a net loss of $57 million.
YOU1000000133_S0000034	Despite doubts coming from all sides, Hastings was convinced that DVD technology would prevail. The only thing that mattered to him was to simply survive until that happened, and 2001 was the year when things finally started going his way.
YOU1000000133_S0000035	The price of DVD players plummeted, with some going around for less than a hundred bucks. 2001 also saw the 9-11 terrorist attacks. Fearful Americans took refuge in their homes, and Netflix subscriptions skyrocketed.
YOU1000000133_S0000036	Despite growing at an unprecedented rate, Netflix still hadn't turned a profit, and so in 2002 they went public to keep the company going. In 2003 they crossed the 1 million subscriber mark and finally had their first profitable year.
YOU1000000133_S0000037	Just as their fortunes started to turn, however, in 2004 Blockbuster finally released their own online DVD mail service. Before long, Walmart also joined the fray, and a three-way battle to undercut one another ensued.
YOU1000000133_S0000038	Blockbuster and Walmart, however, were a bit late to the party. Hastings admitted that if they had started two years earlier, they probably would have won. On an end-of-year conference call, Hastings declared,
YOU1000000133_S0000039	When the CEO of Blockbuster heard that, he promptly had a kitchen sink delivered to the Netflix office, a fairly creative way of declaring war.
YOU1000000133_S0000040	As the competitors undercut one another, Netflix saw its brief profitability evaporate and its stock fell by 75%.
YOU1000000133_S0000041	Despite losing money, they kept on growing, and by 2005 Netflix was shipping 1 million DVDs every day from their assortment of over 35,000 titles. Eventually, this drawn-out battle of attrition took its toll.
YOU1000000133_S0000042	And in 2005, Walmart decided to quit. Blockbuster followed suit, and as the era of brick-and-mortar video rental came to an end, so did their success. In 2008, the same CEO that had rejected Netflix was fired.
YOU1000000133_S0000043	and by 2010 Blockbuster had filed for bankruptcy. Netflix had emerged victorious, and in 2007 it celebrated the delivery of its billionth DVD. Then, in a single announcement, Hastings began the journey of making the very bedrock of his company obsolete.
YOU1000000133_S0000044	This was his endgame, the reason he had been willing to sacrifice prophets for so long and the same reason he had prophetically cited back in the year 2000. Video on demand.
YOU1000000133_S0000046	Netflix first started offering streaming of on-demand videos in 2007, and initially the service was at no additional charge. At first, movie rights were hard to come by, and the videos available to stream on Netflix were, well, pretty awful.
YOU1000000133_S0000047	But in October 2008, they signed a deal with premium cable outlet Starus, which brought in some huge Disney and Sony library releases. The deal cost Netflix only $20 million, a price they soon discovered was an absolute bargain.
YOU1000000133_S0000048	The reason Netflix got such a great price was because they were the only big player in town, and pretty soon they signed deals with Paramount, MGM, and Lionsgate.
YOU1000000133_S0000049	Netflix were also pushing for partnerships with other brands, and before long they were featured on nearly every major entertainment system on the planet. They buddied up with Apple, PlayStation, Xbox, Nintendo Wii, and a bunch of other brands.
YOU1000000133_S0000050	By 2010, nearly 30% of all North American broadband traffic during peak hours came from Netflix. They expanded into Canada in 2010, Latin America and the Caribbean in 2011, and Europe in 2012.
YOU1000000133_S0000051	2011 turned out to be a year of huge surprises for Netflix. In response to the ever-increasing cost of content streaming licenses, Netflix announced the production of their first piece of original content. It would be a political drama called House of Cards.
YOU1000000133_S0000052	featuring Kevin Spacey and directed by David Fincher. Netflix managed to outbid HBO by ordering the first two seasons up front for $100 million. In October of that year, however, Netflix made a much less successful move.
YOU1000000133_S0000053	They introduced a new service called Quickster, which, yes, is spelled with a W. In reality, there was nothing new about Quickster at all, it was basically the spin-off of Netflix's old DVD rental service.
YOU1000000133_S0000054	The branding was sloppy, unimaginative, and just not thought out, but the public's response to Quickster was even worse. Netflix lost 800,000 subscribers in a single month, and three months later their shares had lost two-thirds of their value.
YOU1000000133_S0000055	Unsurprisingly, they shut Quickster down the very next month, bringing the two arms of the business back together. The first piece of Netflix original content was Lilyhammer, which aired on February 6th, 2012.
YOU1000000133_S0000056	It was a relative success, and it paved the way for the bigger shows that were to follow in 2013. First and foremost was House of Cards, which first aired on February 1st and became one of Netflix's most acclaimed titles.
YOU1000000133_S0000057	Airing the entire first season all at once was a bold move by Netflix and it revolutionized the way people watch TV shows. Following the same format came Arrested Development in May and Orange is the New Black in July.
YOU1000000133_S0000058	Netflix continued to use suggestion algorithms to keep people glued to their computers, watching series after series, each available when it's entirely on demand.
YOU1000000133_S0000060	These algorithms have become exponentially smarter in recent years, and they can now spot gaps in the market, giving Netflix a medge in developing new shows.
YOU1000000133_S0000061	At this point Netflix can create original content based solely on what their customers want before they even know they want it.
YOU1000000133_S0000062	That strategy has worked out marvelously for them so far, and in 2013 Netflix received 14 Emmy nominations, 9 of which were for House of Cards.
YOU1000000133_S0000063	They continue to create original content, from TV series to documentaries to movies, though perhaps their faith in Adam Sandler, with whom they are releasing four new movies, is somewhat misplaced.
YOU1000000133_S0000064	By the end of 2016, Netflix will have released 600 hours of new original content for the year and they will have spent a whopping $6 billion on content acquisition. This aggressive expansion is the only option they have.
YOU1000000133_S0000065	with Amazon and Hulu knocking on the door with their own on-demand services and original content. Recently, Netflix integrated its service with Comcast's X1 platform, a deal that could bring them upwards of 4 million new subscribers.
YOU1000000133_S0000066	In such a competitive market, however, a single mistake can be deadly, and there are more than enough companies out there eagerly awaiting Netflix's next stumble. It's still on top at the moment, but the real question is how long can it stay there?
