YOU1000000134_S0000000	Larry Page and Sergey Brin were the kind of guys who kept Bill Gates up at night. Journalist Ken Oletta
YOU1000000134_S0000001	I said, Mr. Gates, what is your nightmare? And I thought he would say Apple or Netscape or Oracle. And he said, I'll tell you what I worry about.
YOU1000000134_S0000002	I worry about some guy in a garage inventing a new technology Microsoft has never thought about.
YOU1000000134_S0000004	Well, in 98, two guys were in a garage and a hand-letted sign and it said Google Worldwide Headquarters.
YOU1000000134_S0000006	In an industry where innovation is just part of the job description, Larry Page and Sergey Brin have become virtual masters of the universe of information gathering.
YOU1000000134_S0000007	What we don't know, we Google.
YOU1000000134_S0000008	629,000 results! Wow! And all this time I thought Googling yourself meant the other thing.
YOU1000000134_S0000009	Not anymore.
YOU1000000134_S0000010	Silicon Valley is littered with startups that have stalled out.
YOU1000000134_S0000011	Why these two computer science geeks succeeded may have a lot to do with the nearly parallel lives they led before creating together one of the world's largest and most powerful companies.
YOU1000000134_S0000012	Brin and Paige respectfully declined to participate in this program.
YOU1000000134_S0000014	Sergei Brin was born in the Soviet Union in 1973. His parents were mathematicians and Jewish, which limited their career opportunities.
YOU1000000134_S0000016	Mark Malseed is the co-author of the Google story.
YOU1000000134_S0000017	So, Sergei's father went to a conference in Warsaw, met a whole bunch of colleagues from the West, saw what life was like outside the Soviet Union, came back, sat the family down and said, we have to leave.
YOU1000000134_S0000019	His parents brought with them a sense of purpose they instilled in their son. It boiled down to a simple message.
YOU1000000134_S0000020	Don't come back with a B. Don't come back with a second place award. Make it first.
YOU1000000134_S0000021	And Sergey internalized this, and it did form a core part of his personality.
YOU1000000134_S0000022	Like Bryn, Larry Page was born in 1973.
YOU1000000134_S0000024	His family lived in Michigan and his father was the first person in his family to get a college degree.
YOU1000000134_S0000025	Both of his parents were in similar fields as Brins.
YOU1000000134_S0000027	They were a second generation computer science, which at that time was very unusual because computer science was really only developing as a field.
YOU1000000134_S0000028	in the 60s and here both of their parents were advanced degrees.
YOU1000000134_S0000029	They see themselves as on a mission and that mission it really does spring from
YOU1000000134_S0000031	In 2009, Page shared that mission with the graduating class at the University of Michigan.
YOU1000000134_S0000032	You know what it's like to wake up in the middle of the night with a vivid dream? And you know how if you don't have a pencil and pad by the bed?
YOU1000000134_S0000033	it will be completely gone by the next morning. I had one of those dreams when I was 23.
YOU1000000134_S0000034	When I suddenly woke up, I was thinking, what if we could download the whole web and just keep the links? And I grabbed a pen and started writing.
YOU1000000134_S0000035	Soon after, I told my advisor, Terry Winograd,
YOU1000000134_S0000036	It would take a couple of weeks for me to download the web. He nodded knowingly, fully aware it would take much longer, but wise enough not to tell me.
YOU1000000134_S0000038	Stanford professor and engineering consultant to Google, Terry Winograd.
YOU1000000134_S0000039	Larry just thinks of ways of doing things that you might not expect. Sergey was a lot like Larry. He also was someone who really wanted to think outside the box, to say, if that sounds like it's impossible, let's try it.
YOU1000000134_S0000040	It was 1995 at Stanford University when the headstrong overachievers first met.
YOU1000000134_S0000042	One of their Stanford professors used to say, well, the difference between the two of them was that Sergey would just burst into my office without asking. Larry would knock and then burst in.
YOU1000000134_S0000044	In the 90s, searching the internet was rudimentary, hit or miss, often returning results that were useless. And the process was very slow.
YOU1000000134_S0000045	So you type in your query. You did something else while you waited for it to get the results. Then you went back and looked at the results and most of them were completely irrelevant.
YOU1000000134_S0000046	Paige and Brynn pushed for something better.
YOU1000000134_S0000048	Sergei's big interest was in taking all the pages on the World Wide Web and trying to make sense of it, trying to find patterns.
YOU1000000134_S0000049	They started to do a record of backlinks, they called them.
YOU1000000134_S0000051	Page noticed that behind every web page there were hundreds or even thousands of other pages that linked to it.
YOU1000000134_S0000053	It was a eureka moment that would change the so-called information age.
YOU1000000134_S0000055	Then they realized that that list of backlinks could be used for ranking.
YOU1000000134_S0000057	so you were better paid.
YOU1000000134_S0000059	If a lot of other websites linked to a web page, that probably meant users thought it was good.
YOU1000000134_S0000061	So the genius was in recognizing that this kind of algorithm could give you the kind of results that mattered the most to searchers.
YOU1000000134_S0000062	Page and Brin had their secret formula.
YOU1000000134_S0000064	Now it needed a name.
YOU1000000134_S0000065	The guys were looking for a great name that was going to capture the grandiose vision that they had and hit upon this giant number.
YOU1000000134_S0000067	One with 100 zeros after it, commonly known as Google. G-O-O-G-O-L.
YOU1000000134_S0000068	They discovered it was owned. They said, you know what, let's put a friendlier spelling on it.
YOU1000000134_S0000070	On September 15, 1997, they registered Google as a website.
YOU1000000134_S0000071	And Page and Brin dropped out of their PhD programs to focus on attracting funding for their young company.
YOU1000000134_S0000072	It wouldn't be easy. Investors like Ram Sharam were skeptical.
YOU1000000134_S0000073	There were five search engines at the time and so I said maybe any one of them might be interested in the technology. The world didn't need a sixth search engine.
YOU1000000134_S0000075	Google just didn't fit into the conventional wisdom of what a website should do, which was to keep users from migrating to another page.
YOU1000000134_S0000076	Google did the unthinkable. It helped users explore the wider web.
YOU1000000134_S0000077	Larry Page and Sergey Brin had a different attitude. They said, we don't want a portal.
YOU1000000134_S0000078	We want to get the search results to them in a split second.
YOU1000000134_S0000080	So one sunny morning, Larry and Sergey were sitting on the porch of a Stanford professor, a friend of theirs.
YOU1000000134_S0000081	And Andy Bechtolsheim, one of the founders of Sun Microsystems, pulls up in his sports car, walks up, gets about a 10-minute demo, says, this is fantastic. This is the next big, big thing.
YOU1000000134_S0000082	and writes a check on the spot for $100,000 made out to Google, Inc.
