YOU1000000135_S0000000	SpaceX and Tesla. You would be hard-pressed to find two companies that are more popular today.
YOU1000000135_S0000001	And yet, in the not-too-distant past, both companies were basically unknown and were in fact simultaneously on the verge of bankruptcy.
YOU1000000135_S0000002	Today we'll learn how Elon Musk did what no other American CEO had ever done before. He created and then rescued two companies at the same time.
YOU1000000135_S0000003	and brought them both to multi-billion dollar valuations.
YOU1000000135_S0000005	This video is brought to you by Audible, and the story presented in it is just one chapter of Elon Musk's awesome biography.
YOU1000000135_S0000006	which you can listen to for free as part of your 30-day free trial if you register with the link in the description.
YOU1000000135_S0000008	In the early 2000s, Elon Musk achieved what any entrepreneur would dream of achieving. He successfully sold his company for over a billion dollars.
YOU1000000135_S0000009	He personally received 165 million and now this is where most people would call it quits, but for Elon this was just the beginning.
YOU1000000135_S0000010	He wanted to change the world for the better, and one of his ideas was to send a greenhouse to Mars.
YOU1000000135_S0000011	in order to boost public interest in space exploration and hopefully increase NASA's budget.
YOU1000000135_S0000012	The idea was outlandishly ambitious, especially because Elon wanted to spend no more than $20 million on it.
YOU1000000135_S0000013	Now, at the time, sending just 500 pounds to orbit could easily cost upwards of 30 million. But Elon had a plan.
YOU1000000135_S0000014	He travelled to Russia, where he tried to buy refurbished intercontinental ballistic missiles.
YOU1000000135_S0000015	But the lowest price the Russians gave him was 8 million dollars a piece, about 50% above his budget for the rocket itself.
YOU1000000135_S0000016	On the way back from Moscow, Elon did some back of the napkin calculations.
YOU1000000135_S0000017	He figured out that the raw materials used in the making of a rocket were only about 3% of the final sales price.
YOU1000000135_S0000018	Instantly, Elon knew what he had to do. If he wanted to send anything to Mars, he'd have to build himself a vertically integrated rocket company.
YOU1000000135_S0000019	To that end, he read several books on rocketry from the Cold War, and in June 2002 he incorporated space exploration technologies, or SpaceX for short.
YOU1000000135_S0000020	He then set about recruiting the right people who could make his vision a reality.
YOU1000000135_S0000021	His ideal candidate was young, single, educated and ready to give up his social life for SpaceX.
YOU1000000135_S0000022	Elon's recruitment strategy was very straightforward.
YOU1000000135_S0000023	He'd basically co-op anyone fitting that profile, from fresh aerospace graduates to the rising stars in Boeing and Lockheed Martin.
YOU1000000135_S0000024	At first people thought Elon was making pranks, but within a year he had assembled some of the brightest engineers in America.
YOU1000000135_S0000025	Together, they would design almost everything for SpaceX, from the engines and rocket bodies to even the smallest details, like the circuitry.
YOU1000000135_S0000026	In many cases, the engineers could build stronger and more lightweight components at just a fraction of the regular price.
YOU1000000135_S0000027	These components would be used to build the Merlin engine, which in turn would power Elon's first rocket, the Falcon 1.
YOU1000000135_S0000028	Development was far from smooth, of course, but nevertheless progress was being made. But then Elon decided to up the ante.
YOU1000000135_S0000029	In early 2004 he participated in the funding round of a new electric car company called Tesla.
YOU1000000135_S0000030	He personally invested a little over 6 million and in return became the chairman of the company's board.
YOU1000000135_S0000031	Right off the bat, Elon began applying his experience from SpaceX at Tesla.
YOU1000000135_S0000032	The company's logo, for example, was created by the same people that made the logo for SpaceX.
YOU1000000135_S0000033	and of course Elon was quick to use the same aggressive hiring strategy he used to assemble the SpaceX team.
YOU1000000135_S0000034	This time, however, instead of poaching employees from Boeing, he was hiring from Apple.
YOU1000000135_S0000035	Before long, the Tesla team was working on their first electric car, the Tesla Roadster. Back at SpaceX, engineers were clocking in 60-hour work weeks
YOU1000000135_S0000036	while Elon was promising very ambitious timelines.
YOU1000000135_S0000037	In fact, his original estimate was to launch the Falcon 1 in November 2003, just 18 months after the company was founded.
YOU1000000135_S0000038	Of course, that estimate got pushed back, and the Falcon 1 wouldn't lift off until March 2006.
YOU1000000135_S0000039	when it spent a total of 41 seconds in the air before crashing down violently. Like for SpaceX, 2006 was a big year for Tesla.
YOU1000000135_S0000040	In July, the Tesla Roadster made its first official appearance and recorded 100 pre-orders in its first day.
YOU1000000135_S0000041	But, like with the Falcon 1, the actual production wasn't going very well. Tesla's CEO at the time was Martin Eberhard.
YOU1000000135_S0000042	and like Elon, he was promising unrealistic timeframes. At first, the idea was to deliver the Roadster in early 2007.
YOU1000000135_S0000043	but an escalating series of production issues pushed the release date farther and farther away.
YOU1000000135_S0000044	In the end, Martin's mismanagement of the Roadster project got him ousted from the very company he had founded, leaving Elon in charge of everything.
YOU1000000135_S0000045	With full responsibility over both companies, the stress was starting to pile up.
YOU1000000135_S0000046	Elon witnessed the second failure of the Falcon 1 rocket, which didn't complete its only 2007 flight.
YOU1000000135_S0000047	At Tesla, Elon struggled fixing the mess left behind by Eberhard, and in fact, the roadster's production would not begin until March 2008.
YOU1000000135_S0000048	But then things got worse. In August Elon launched his third Falcon 1
YOU1000000135_S0000050	which never made it to orbit, and then just one month later his wife publicly announced their divorce.
YOU1000000135_S0000051	Both of Elon's companies were struggling to make a viable product and were running out of money fast.
YOU1000000135_S0000052	In fact, by late October, Tesla had only $9 million left to fund the entire company. Salaries were being delayed and Elon was faced with a choice.
YOU1000000135_S0000053	He had already spent $70 million on Tesla and $100 million on SpaceX.
YOU1000000135_S0000054	With what little he had left, Elon had to choose whether to fund and secure the future of one company, or to risk everything and gamble on saving both.
YOU1000000135_S0000055	Fate gave Elon little time to think. The fourth and potentially final flight of the Falcon 1 was approaching.
YOU1000000135_S0000056	On September 2008, Elon got ready for his last chance to survive. He stood in the SpaceX control center in LA and waited in silence.
YOU1000000135_S0000057	Then, the rocket took off, and the center burst out an ecstatic applause. SpaceX had finally delivered a working product.
YOU1000000135_S0000058	The Falcon 1 became the first privately developed rocket to go into orbit around Earth. But Elon wasn't in the clear just yet.
YOU1000000135_S0000059	A working product would mean nothing if the company behind it went bankrupt.
YOU1000000135_S0000060	In a frantic scramble, Elon had to figure out funding solutions for both his companies before the end of 2008. And the timing couldn't have been worse.
YOU1000000135_S0000061	One of the largest American banks, Lehman Brothers, had collapsed, and the global economy was heading towards disaster.
YOU1000000135_S0000062	In the midst of this, Elon was raising all the personal funds he could to save Tesla. He liquidated his few remaining assets and even got his cousins to pitch in.
YOU1000000135_S0000063	But getting investors on board doesn't happen overnight, and December was creeping in.
YOU1000000135_S0000064	Elon had managed to scrape together $20 million himself, another $20 million from various investors, and $50 million from the German car company Daimler.
YOU1000000135_S0000065	Days before Christmas, it seemed as if only Tesla was going to make it.
YOU1000000135_S0000066	But then, on December 23rd, Elon received a very unexpected call.
YOU1000000135_S0000067	NASA had awarded SpaceX with a $1.6 billion contract to resupply the International Space Station.
YOU1000000135_S0000068	Then, on Christmas Eve, the Tesla deal went through. Elon had successfully saved both companies from bankruptcy.
YOU1000000135_S0000069	In later interviews, he'd recall these final days in December in painful detail.
YOU1000000135_S0000070	But I remember waking up on the Sunday before Christmas in 2008 and thinking, like, damn, this is the closest I've ever gotten.
YOU1000000135_S0000071	And it was looking pretty grim, because at that point, even though the fourth launch of SpaceX had succeeded, we were still running out of money.
YOU1000000135_S0000072	Because we had three failures and only one success. Still not enough.
YOU1000000135_S0000073	And then the financing round for Tesla had not closed. And we had only two days, maybe two, I think. It was like two or three days maybe to close it before Christmas.
YOU1000000135_S0000074	So I was like, man, this could be a really bad end of the year. Maybe both companies will fail.
