YOU1000000137_S0000001	St. Peter's Basilica in the Vatican City in Rome. The cathedral on St. Peter's Square is a magnificent edifice capped with larger-than-life statues of the Apostles.
YOU1000000137_S0000003	It's the most impressive monument of the Renaissance, with colonnades reminiscent of the temples of antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000005	St. Peter's is the largest church in the world. Yet its construction would have been impossible just a few generations before.
YOU1000000137_S0000007	No one had the knowledge of mathematics, physics and structural engineering needed to plan and organize such a vast project.
YOU1000000137_S0000009	Then, in the mid-16th century, artists and scholars stepped onto the stage and managed to do things that had seemed impossible for the previous thousand years.
YOU1000000137_S0000011	Within just four generations, they accrued the knowledge necessary to carry out massive projects such as St. Peter's.
YOU1000000137_S0000013	Europe was transformed under the influence of individuals like Michelangelo Buonarroti, men of extraordinary accomplishment and versatility who found ways to bring seemingly impossible ideas to life.
YOU1000000137_S0000015	Their achievements still resonate today.
YOU1000000137_S0000017	But how did they do it? What was the secret of an age when the world seemed to undergo a paradigm shift? The age of the Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000019	Rome 1547.
YOU1000000137_S0000020	Perhaps one man stood out above all. Michelangelo Bionarotti, project manager, architect and artist on the construction site for St. Peter's.
YOU1000000137_S0000022	Although he was in his early 70s by this time, he was still driven by ambition.
YOU1000000137_S0000024	Michelangelo was a painter, sculptor and architect, a scientist, iconoclast and a genius. What we now refer to as a Renaissance man.
YOU1000000137_S0000026	One of his works would become the icon of an entire era.
YOU1000000137_S0000028	Michelangelo's David is perhaps the best-known sculpture in art history.
YOU1000000137_S0000030	Men like Michelangelo were the managers of an era in which art and culture, knowledge and technology developed at near lightning speed.
YOU1000000137_S0000032	Florence 1501. Michelangelo astonished his contemporaries with works that seemed to border on the miraculous.
YOU1000000137_S0000033	He set out to carve David from a 12-ton block of marble, a feat at which two sculptors before him had failed.
YOU1000000137_S0000035	Michelangelo became obsessed with the undertaking and spent three years working non-stop on the five meter tall statue, the first monumental sculpture of the high Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000037	From a cumbersome block of marble, Michelangelo's hammer and chisel revealed a human figure in the pose of a god.
YOU1000000137_S0000039	The image of mankind changed in the Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000041	Pope Innocent III said at the end of the 12th century that man was rottenness, formed of slime and ashes, a contemptible creature. The medieval belief that the sinful nature of man was visible in his appearance.
YOU1000000137_S0000043	During the Renaissance, we can see how this pessimistic view had become tiresome. The idea arose that man was almost like God. Man was God's creation, endowed with reason, with strength, and created in His image.
YOU1000000137_S0000044	man could almost become a god.
YOU1000000137_S0000046	Some ten years after he completed David, Michelangelo finished his figure of Moses for the tomb of Pope Julius II.
YOU1000000137_S0000048	Larger than life, this Moses is an angry prophet with bulging veins and a fearsome visage, the way gods were depicted in the ancient world.
YOU1000000137_S0000050	Michelangelo may have learned from the masters of antiquity, but he didn't copy them.
YOU1000000137_S0000052	The Renaissance was more than just the rebirth of antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000054	Men like Michelangelo created something new. They took the techniques and art of the ancient Greeks and Romans and developed them further.
YOU1000000137_S0000056	But you won't find a single artwork of the Renaissance that simply copies an ancient one. The crucial thing is that the Renaissance didn't just rediscover the critical spirit of the Greeks, for example. It didn't just grapple with the science and scholarship of antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000057	It developed everything further. It invented completely new things and toppled the ancient giants who had originally been its teachers.
YOU1000000137_S0000059	Botticelli's Primavera, one of the best-known works of Renaissance art.
YOU1000000137_S0000061	Raphael's School of Athens glorified ancient thought.
YOU1000000137_S0000063	And Leonardo da Vinci's Mona Lisa. For more than a thousand years, the skill of realistically capturing the three-dimensional world on a flat canvas had been forgotten.
YOU1000000137_S0000064	the Renaissance rediscovered perspective.
YOU1000000137_S0000066	It was a quantum leap for architecture, which took its inspiration from the symmetry of the great buildings of the ancient world.
YOU1000000137_S0000068	The art of building huge domed structures had fallen into oblivion in the Middle Ages and was rediscovered in the Renaissance. But the Renaissance didn't limit itself to art.
YOU1000000137_S0000070	The invention of double-entry bookkeeping also meant that men of business now knew what funds they had available. The surplus fortunes of the newly wealthy flowed into the pockets of the era's artists.
YOU1000000137_S0000072	It was like an investment program for scholars and artists. Never before had so much been invented or devised in such a short period of time.
YOU1000000137_S0000074	New mechanical machines were created.
YOU1000000137_S0000076	And the human machine was researched in increasing detail. The study of anatomy reached a peak.
YOU1000000137_S0000078	The first pocket-sized timepieces were invented. This also made it possible to track the orbits of planets and the movements of celestial bodies. As the heavens guided seafarers, adventurers discovered new trade routes.
YOU1000000137_S0000079	The known world tripled in size.
YOU1000000137_S0000081	There's probably no place anywhere in the world where so much was discussed in one big conversation involving such a large number of participants, where things were invented in such quick succession.
YOU1000000137_S0000083	Printing triggered a huge discourse that captivated large parts of the population.
YOU1000000137_S0000085	elites, scholars,
YOU1000000137_S0000087	exchanged ideas, and so invented groundbreaking new things.
YOU1000000137_S0000089	But what was the impetus for this exceptional period of history?
YOU1000000137_S0000091	What were the ingredients in this explosive development?
YOU1000000137_S0000093	How could men like Michelangelo suddenly reacquire knowledge and techniques that had been lost for centuries?
YOU1000000137_S0000095	Let's look back to Rome in the first century.
YOU1000000137_S0000097	Back then, the Romans were capable of constructing buildings like St. Peter's, as seen in the Roman Forum, the power center of an empire that ruled the Western world.
YOU1000000137_S0000099	Rome exported its way of life to its father's provinces. It dictated the art, culture and architecture of an entire era.
YOU1000000137_S0000101	At the time, Rome was home to a million people, 20 times more than one of the largest cities of the Renaissance, London.
YOU1000000137_S0000103	But Rome's dominance was built on the oppression of millions of slaves. Entire peoples were subjugated.
YOU1000000137_S0000105	For centuries, the Roman military machine succeeded in holding the empire together.
YOU1000000137_S0000107	But at some point the barbarians gained the upper hand, the Germanic tribes, the Goths and the Vandals.
YOU1000000137_S0000109	In the 5th century, the Western Empire ceased to exist.
YOU1000000137_S0000111	Roma Caputmundi, once the capital of the world and home to a million people, fell into decay and the Dark Ages began.
YOU1000000137_S0000113	Much of the knowledge of antiquity was lost, in all areas, but particularly in engineering, architecture, mathematics and physics.
YOU1000000137_S0000115	The ruins of the ancient world were plundered for building materials.
YOU1000000137_S0000117	Just a few generations after Rome fell, no one was capable of creating anything remotely comparable.
YOU1000000137_S0000119	In the year 330, the Roman emperor Constantine had moved his capital to the Bosporus in what is now Turkey, naming it Constantinople in his own honor.
YOU1000000137_S0000121	After that, the empire split into an eastern and a western half.
YOU1000000137_S0000123	The Eastern Roman Empire, also known as Byzantium, endured until the 15th century. Constantinople was the second Rome, home to more than half a million people who called themselves Romaioi, Romans.
YOU1000000137_S0000125	The Byzantine emperors saw themselves as descendants of Caesar and Augustus, while its patriarch was head of the Orthodox Christians.
YOU1000000137_S0000127	Constantinople also became the repository of ancient wisdom.
YOU1000000137_S0000129	Its scholars were leading figures in every field.
YOU1000000137_S0000131	The Rome of the East was the bulwark of antiquity in the medieval world.
YOU1000000137_S0000133	No one had been able to conquer the city on the Bosporus.
YOU1000000137_S0000135	But one-seventh of its population were merchants from Genoa, Pisa and the Republic of Venice, known as Latins.
YOU1000000137_S0000136	This affluent minority had a reputation for arrogance and belligerence and were unpopular with the Eastern Romans.
YOU1000000137_S0000138	In early 1171, riots broke out in Pera, the Genoese quarter.
YOU1000000137_S0000140	The Emperor Manuel I Komnenos accused the Venetians of causing the trouble. Venetian merchants were imprisoned and their possessions confiscated.
YOU1000000137_S0000142	Venice tried to defend its people to no avail. It was the start of a conflict that was to last for decades and ultimately end in disaster for Constantinople.
YOU1000000137_S0000144	The conflict culminated in what history calls the Fourth Crusade.
YOU1000000137_S0000145	This wasn't a crusade against people of a different faith, but a Catholic war against Orthodox Christians.
YOU1000000137_S0000147	The Crusaders laid siege to Constantinople and, on the night of the 12th of April 1204, broke through its defences.
YOU1000000137_S0000149	For three days they plundered the city, abusing, raping and killing many of its residents.
YOU1000000137_S0000151	The collapse of Byzantium, its defeat by the West during the Fourth Crusade, and its subjugation by the Ottoman Empire all played a major role in the development of the Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000153	Many scholars fled to Italy, taking manuscripts with them and trying to instill new values and ideas into a culture they still saw as barbaric.
YOU1000000137_S0000154	It gave an unprecedented boost to innovation.
YOU1000000137_S0000156	The libraries of Constantinople were replete with treasures of immeasurable worth. The collective knowledge of antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000158	As hundreds of scholars and artists fled the advance of the Ottoman Turks, they took valuable books with them.
YOU1000000137_S0000160	The scholar Manuer Chrysoloros was one of them. When the Chancellor of Florence offered him a chair at the university there, he also sent him a wish list of ancient works.
YOU1000000137_S0000162	This exodus of scholars from Byzantium reintroduced ancient techniques to the West. Marble sculptures took on a realism, movement and vitality unknown in the Middle Ages. Ancient frescoes inspired painters.
YOU1000000137_S0000164	Long forgotten engineering techniques triggered a wave of technical innovations.
YOU1000000137_S0000166	Ancient ideas about the movement of the heavenly bodies were taught once more.
YOU1000000137_S0000168	Science, especially mathematics and physics, experienced an unexpected revival after centuries of oblivion.
YOU1000000137_S0000170	The Europeans learned from several civilizations. They learned from the Greeks and Romans, the Arabs, the Byzantines, and also from the Indians. The Arabic numeral system we use today actually came from India.
YOU1000000137_S0000174	But they didn't just copy. They developed something new with what they had learned and disseminated these ideas through printing.
YOU1000000137_S0000176	there was an incredible flourishing of discussion and debate.
YOU1000000137_S0000178	Florence in 1410, a city state with a population of 50,000, the size of London, and bursting with self-confidence.
YOU1000000137_S0000180	The Italian city was like the Silicon Valley of the Renaissance, a fount of knowledge and a meeting place for artists and scholars.
YOU1000000137_S0000182	The ambitious plans for the Cathedral of Maria del Fiore were drawn up around 1300.
YOU1000000137_S0000183	It was to be the largest church in Christendom, bigger and more beautiful than the cathedrals of Pisa, Siena and Milan.
YOU1000000137_S0000185	153 meters long, Florence Cathedral remains the fourth largest church in the world. But back then, it was number one.
YOU1000000137_S0000187	By the time its 45-meter diameter dome was completed, it set a world record.
YOU1000000137_S0000188	Giorgio Vasari, an artist and architect, began work on the 4,000 square meter fresco in its interior, which was to rival Michelangelo's Last Judgment.
YOU1000000137_S0000190	But Vasari's figures are lost in the height of the dome. Visitors below can barely see them.
YOU1000000137_S0000192	In 1418, more than a hundred years after its construction began, the cathedral dome had not been built.
YOU1000000137_S0000194	No one in the Middle Ages had the knowledge to solve the structural and technical problems. Filippo Brunelleschi took on the task.
YOU1000000137_S0000196	Brunelleschi was an architect and sculptor, as well as an engineer and an inventor.
YOU1000000137_S0000198	Inspired by the ancient domes of the Pantheon and the Hagia Sophia, he had clear ideas about how to realize the ambitious project.
YOU1000000137_S0000200	He developed special cranes for the dome's construction, new inventions that would revolutionize building methods.
YOU1000000137_S0000202	Brunelleschi's machines were a novelty of his era and were widely admired.
YOU1000000137_S0000204	The cable that lifted the blocks of stone was 7 centimeters thick, 180 meters long, and weighed half a ton.
YOU1000000137_S0000206	Years later, the builder would receive the exclusive rights to build a ship with a crane on it, the first patent in industrial history. Filippo Brunelleschi rediscovered perspective, a technique largely forgotten since antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000208	It was a geometrical system that made it possible to depict three-dimensional views realistically.
YOU1000000137_S0000209	Using it, he managed to put the building plans down on paper and render them visually comprehensible.
YOU1000000137_S0000211	It was the dawn of modern architecture.
YOU1000000137_S0000213	Perspective drawing also inspired painters and their works took on a new realism.
YOU1000000137_S0000215	Artists took viewers on a journey to new worlds, and Renaissance paintings became more realistic than ever before.
YOU1000000137_S0000217	The rediscovery of perspective drawing was a powerful engine of progress.
YOU1000000137_S0000219	The fashionable architects in Italy's competing city-states, particularly in Venice, Milan, Florence and Pisa, became some of the top earners of the Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000221	No longer nameless as they had been in the Middle Ages, they were celebrated and pampered elites.
YOU1000000137_S0000223	Venetian noblemen spent fortunes on palaces in the Neo style.
YOU1000000137_S0000225	Swiss architect Antonio Contino designed and built the Bridge of Sighs, one of the most photographed motifs in the world.
YOU1000000137_S0000227	This new style of building became popular outside Italy.
YOU1000000137_S0000228	The city hall in Zurich is a masterpiece of the late Renaissance. A hundred years earlier, the sculptor and builder Anton Eisenmann had built one of the most picturesque examples of Italian Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000229	The Lucerne Town Hall in Switzerland.
YOU1000000137_S0000231	The new style, inspired by the buildings of the ancient world, was characterized by symmetry and a clear system for the arrangement of columns, arches and domes.
YOU1000000137_S0000233	Architecture, gardens and sculptures were designed as complete artistic ensembles. The aim was to please the eye and please the people, not praise God.
YOU1000000137_S0000235	Medieval art was basically religious art.
YOU1000000137_S0000237	That's in part evidenced by the fact that we only know the names of a handful of the artists.
YOU1000000137_S0000239	Although it was customary to sign individual works, we often speak of the master of such-and-such, whose name we don't even know. In the Renaissance, we see the creators of works being named.
YOU1000000137_S0000241	Art became free from religious motifs and turned towards everyday life.
YOU1000000137_S0000243	It also described that everyday life more accurately. Think of perspective painting, for example. Art tried to reflect everyday life in great detail. Extremely self-confident artists stepped up.
YOU1000000137_S0000244	and made their demands, confronting the powerful who in turn then courted them.
YOU1000000137_S0000246	Michelangelo, for example, who would even dictate certain things to the Pope.
YOU1000000137_S0000248	In 1347, the Black Death broke out in Europe.
YOU1000000137_S0000250	Bubonic plague killed almost half the English population within just seven months, and at least a third of the population of Europe in the next four years.
YOU1000000137_S0000252	Millions perished.
YOU1000000137_S0000254	It was the most horrific epidemic in European history, and it changed everything, ultimately even people themselves.
YOU1000000137_S0000256	It might sound cynical, but the plague didn't just have a negative effect on the culture of the Renaissance and the arts.
YOU1000000137_S0000258	The wealth of the dead was concentrated in the hands of the survivors.
YOU1000000137_S0000260	And those who survived saw life with completely different eyes.
YOU1000000137_S0000262	Some must have said, let's enjoy our days and spend them in the best way possible.
YOU1000000137_S0000264	Maybe they wanted to surround themselves with beautiful art.
YOU1000000137_S0000266	Others would have wanted to square their accounts with God and do something for the well-being of their souls, like Cosimo di Medici, who built an entire church.
YOU1000000137_S0000268	The plague had a fundamental influence on people's attitude to life.
YOU1000000137_S0000270	The imperative of the Renaissance was, live this life and enjoy it.
YOU1000000137_S0000271	Renaissance art was a complete departure from the art of the Middle Ages. Nude bodies everywhere, beautiful people enmeshed in idyllic landscapes, open eroticism.
YOU1000000137_S0000273	In Michelangelo's Last Judgment, the heavenly host is shown nude in great anatomical detail. It was a revolution.
YOU1000000137_S0000275	The plague ravaged Florence. Only a fifth of the city's population survived the Black Death.
YOU1000000137_S0000277	It also changed how wealth was distributed and led to the rise of a new elite, tycoons who became unimaginably rich.
YOU1000000137_S0000279	Families like the Medici were merchants and bankers, people who had been held in contempt by the feudal society of the Middle Ages. Now, they were the ones in charge.
YOU1000000137_S0000281	Let's go back to the year 1425 and the sculptor Donatello.
YOU1000000137_S0000283	His patron Cosimo Medici was the first great sponsor of the arts.
YOU1000000137_S0000284	Medici was a wealthy banker and a shrewd strategist who employed almost mafia-like methods.
YOU1000000137_S0000286	He was one of the richest men of his day and his money fueled the development of art and architecture in Florence.
YOU1000000137_S0000288	It provided the spark that ignited the Italian Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000290	But his success would never have been possible without a seemingly minor invention that revolutionized banking.
YOU1000000137_S0000292	Double-entry bookkeeping was a simple financial instrument that involved keeping a credit account showing income and a debit account with outgoing payments.
YOU1000000137_S0000293	The first complete double-entry bookkeeping system can be traced back to 1340, in ledgers from Genoa showing government income and expenditure.
YOU1000000137_S0000295	Double-entry bookkeeping showed account holders how much capital they had on hand, allowing them greater overview and control of their finances.
YOU1000000137_S0000297	The Medicis were global players. They issued loans and signed secure credit notes for travelers that could be cashed in many countries, the precursor to today's travelers' checks.
YOU1000000137_S0000302	On taxes, donations to the needy, on buildings and on art.
YOU1000000137_S0000304	A host of writers, scholars, artists and architects were dependent on his money. And they repaid him in beauty.
YOU1000000137_S0000306	The Medici Palace is a glorious stage of Renaissance art. It's hard to believe that Cosimo instructed the architect not to make it too magnificent, as he didn't want to rouse the envy of the other patrician families.
YOU1000000137_S0000308	The Medicis also invested in their spiritual well-being. They donated money for a new church, the Basilica di San Lorenzo.
YOU1000000137_S0000310	Cosimo de' Medici supported artists' careers and spawned something that had not existed before, the celebrity.
YOU1000000137_S0000312	This celebrity arose in a sort of intellectual hothouse, in a market full of competition, where humanists, intellectuals, creatives and artists of all kinds were supported, and often very well paid, by patrons.
YOU1000000137_S0000314	These patrons, in turn, hoped these artists would bring their courts greater fame and status.
YOU1000000137_S0000316	For painters and sculptors, hyperbole soon became just as important as skill.
YOU1000000137_S0000318	In this very competitive arena, they acquired fame and status. And we still know their names today.
YOU1000000137_S0000320	But that also means the unrecognized artist, the suffering genius, was a particularly frequent phenomenon.
YOU1000000137_S0000322	Donatello was one of the first great celebrity artists of the Renaissance.
YOU1000000137_S0000324	He was almost 60 when he came to Cosimo de' Medici with designs for his statue of David, the boy who defeated Goliath.
YOU1000000137_S0000326	This, his most significant work, was also a brave one, because Donatello's David was naked.
YOU1000000137_S0000328	Just a few generations earlier, ancient statues were destroyed for showing nudity.
YOU1000000137_S0000330	Both Medici and Donatello were certainly aware of how revolutionary it was.
YOU1000000137_S0000331	Donatello's David was the first life-sized sculpture of a nude since antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000333	Unlike other cultures, the Renaissance didn't worry about depicting naked or semi-naked bodies. That was very significant for the development of medicine.
YOU1000000137_S0000335	You can't study anatomy if you can't depict naked bodies.
YOU1000000137_S0000337	that was crucial to a different way of looking at people.
YOU1000000137_S0000339	A person wasn't just animated by the spirits and guided by the stars.
YOU1000000137_S0000341	He was a mechanically functioning machine, an organism.
YOU1000000137_S0000343	What was also unusual was his interpretation.
YOU1000000137_S0000345	Donatello's David is not a muscular adult, but a youth with a rather feminine appearance.
YOU1000000137_S0000347	And he is fascinatingly lifelike. But where did Donatello get his knowledge of the human body?
YOU1000000137_S0000349	With the enthusiasm of the early Renaissance for all things classical, interest in anatomy was growing as well.
YOU1000000137_S0000351	Almost all the artists, sculptors and painters of the Renaissance would have studied human anatomy, if only from books and drawings.
YOU1000000137_S0000353	there was a flourishing trade in fresh corpses. It was illegal in many places and punishment for this crime was often draconian, but curiosity often triumphed over fear.
YOU1000000137_S0000355	Di Natale quite possibly dissected corpses too, as did Albrecht Drer, Michelangelo and Leonardo da Vinci one or two generations later.
YOU1000000137_S0000357	But even in Donatello's time, in the early Renaissance, artists were very familiar with the structure of the human body, which allowed them to create new, very lifelike depictions of people.
YOU1000000137_S0000359	Men like Donatello were either artistically talented scholars or scholarly artists.
YOU1000000137_S0000361	As fate would have it, Donatello's interpretation of the Old Testament hero didn't achieve the same popularity as another sculpture of the Renaissance, one that was also created in Florence.
YOU1000000137_S0000363	At five meters tall, Michelangelo's David is a monumental statue.
YOU1000000137_S0000365	Half a century after Donatello, it symbolized the self-confidence of the new Renaissance man.
YOU1000000137_S0000369	The explosive thing about the Renaissance was that people became aware of their abilities and strengths in a new way.
YOU1000000137_S0000371	They unleashed an incredible energy in their thinking and actions, in business and technology.
YOU1000000137_S0000373	There was an outpouring of self-confidence.
YOU1000000137_S0000375	In the Middle Ages, nearly everyone was illiterate. The few who could read and write were from wealthier families or men and women of the church.
YOU1000000137_S0000377	The people who made or owned books looked after them like treasures.
YOU1000000137_S0000379	A copyist might only produce 10 to 15 volumes in an entire lifetime, which made the books incredibly valuable.
YOU1000000137_S0000381	But that was about to change.
YOU1000000137_S0000383	To obtain a lovely codex such as a Bible, for example, you would have to slaughter an entire flock of sheep. And that was expensive.
YOU1000000137_S0000385	But suddenly books could be had for little money, and reading became democratic.
YOU1000000137_S0000387	Knowledge became accessible to larger numbers of people.
YOU1000000137_S0000389	More and more people were able to participate in scholarly discussions about new ideas.
YOU1000000137_S0000391	That's the only way we can explain how Europe became the continent of innovation, more so than any other.
YOU1000000137_S0000393	The scribes of the church hadn't just copied works, they had also changed them and falsified sources, claiming their interpretation as the Word of God.
YOU1000000137_S0000395	That gave them great power.
YOU1000000137_S0000397	But the Renaissance broke their monopoly on knowledge, one of the most important bastions of the Church.
YOU1000000137_S0000399	An awareness of sources and the truth grew, not least because these sources were now accessible. People started analyzing them using classical techniques, techniques used in antiquity.
YOU1000000137_S0000401	The traditional myths propagated by the church simply weren't accepted anymore.
YOU1000000137_S0000403	Mainz 1450. Printer Johannes Gutenberg's invention may have been the most significant one in a thousand years. And yet we don't know what he looked like.
YOU1000000137_S0000405	His achievement was to combine existing methods of reproduction and printing into a single system.
YOU1000000137_S0000407	The handheld cast was the key to his printing press.
YOU1000000137_S0000409	It allowed letters to be cast individually more quickly and with greater precision.
YOU1000000137_S0000411	This marked the invention of modern printing.
YOU1000000137_S0000413	It was also the dawn of mass communication.
YOU1000000137_S0000415	Information became more widely available, opening the door to new opinions and perspectives.
YOU1000000137_S0000417	Information also became valued in new ways, as the printed word took precedence over oral traditions.
YOU1000000137_S0000419	Printing was of truly enormous significance, and Gutenberg is the person who did the most important thing in a thousand years of world history. Reading became increasingly widespread.
YOU1000000137_S0000420	The great scientific innovations and the great religious revolution, the Reformation, wouldn't have been possible without printing.
YOU1000000137_S0000422	The first 60 years after the invention of printing saw the publication of 400 different vernacular editions of the Bible.
YOU1000000137_S0000424	At the same time, the number of lay people who could read and write grew.
YOU1000000137_S0000426	More and more people now had direct and immediate access to biblical texts, to the Word of God.
YOU1000000137_S0000429	The people of the Renaissance felt close to God. They felt they were becoming God-like themselves. They wouldn't have said that in the Middle Ages. It would have been considered blasphemous. People referred to the Bible and called themselves God's creations.
YOU1000000137_S0000430	God made us in his image. We're almost gods in miniature. God came closer to people in the Renaissance than he ever was in the Middle Ages.
YOU1000000137_S0000432	But it wasn't books that made up the bulk of the printing shop's business. It was flysheets and pamphlets.
YOU1000000137_S0000434	They were affordable and cost a labourer two or three hours' pay.
YOU1000000137_S0000436	Now even ordinary people could print a pamphlet and disseminate their opinions, verses, and drawings.
YOU1000000137_S0000438	Three subjects dominated, sensations and miracles, religious instruction, and political and military propaganda.
YOU1000000137_S0000440	Illustrated flysheets also carried the first caricatures.
YOU1000000137_S0000442	They could be an invitation, an opinion, or a warning.
YOU1000000137_S0000444	Just like today's social media networks, they served as a vehicle for the mass dissemination of opinion.
YOU1000000137_S0000446	The Renaissance had fly sheets. It had literature that was printed and spread very quickly. It could be printed in Nuremberg tomorrow and in two days' time would be in Zurich."
YOU1000000137_S0000448	Information disseminated more quickly and was much harder to control, too.
YOU1000000137_S0000450	The censorship of the church that dictated what was right didn't work anymore once the flysheets began circulating.
YOU1000000137_S0000452	You can only understand the huge boom in free thinking in the Renaissance if you look at the media, and the flysheets in particular.
YOU1000000137_S0000454	Mass communication helped create that new type of individual, the celebrity.
YOU1000000137_S0000456	Giorgio Vasari, who had painted the frescoes in the Florence Cathedral dome, was also a biographer of the most dazzling personalities of his time, the artists.
YOU1000000137_S0000458	Vasari also produced portraits of Raphael and Michelangelo, but he was particularly taken with Leonardo da Vinci. Leonardo was unconventional and wasn't afraid to acknowledge his homosexuality.
YOU1000000137_S0000460	He was remarkably creative and talented, but also rather vain.
