YOU1000000147_S0000037	The animals are so well-esteemed that they live like kings. They're massaged daily, played classical music, and even fed beer to induce their appetite.
YOU1000000147_S0000038	Kobe beef is renowned for its superior flavor, tenderness and high amount of intermuscular fat, which contributes to its melt-in-the-mouth qualities.
YOU1000000147_S0000039	All Wagyu beef is rated on a marbling scale of 1-12 based on this distribution of fat, and Kobe beef only qualifies if it scores between 10-12.
YOU1000000147_S0000040	The luxury beef market has even been tainted by controversy after numerous establishments tried to pass off regular Wagyu beef as Kobe.
YOU1000000147_S0000041	With Kobe fraud rampant in the US, all cuts must now be assigned a 10-digit ID number so that it can be traced back to the account it came from.
YOU1000000147_S0000042	Restaurateurs must also carry a license of authenticity that can be shown on demand.
YOU1000000147_S0000043	So if you're a beef aficionado, it's worth checking before shelling out up to $300 for a single pound of meat.
YOU1000000147_S0000044	Blonde Aqua Tain
YOU1000000147_S0000046	steak.
YOU1000000147_S0000047	For those rich enough to take a been-there-done-that approach to Kobe beef, perhaps blonde to aquataine steak is more your forte.
YOU1000000147_S0000048	This rare beef is considered the most expensive steak in the world, and you can expect to pay about $3,200 for just one cut.
YOU1000000147_S0000049	The meat comes from prized free-range Blanc d'Aquitaine cattle and is produced by Parisian butcher Alexandre Paulmard on his family farm in northeastern France.
YOU1000000147_S0000050	The extortionate price tag is thanks to the technique Pomar developed in the 1990s to treat the meat.
YOU1000000147_S0000051	The cattle are hand-reared and free to roam the forests and grasslands of the French countryside, and only four are killed weekly.
YOU1000000147_S0000052	Each cow is then slaughtered humanely to make the process as stress-free as possible and to keep acidity levels at a minimum.
YOU1000000147_S0000053	The meat is then stored in a room and pumped with a constant stream of air at speeds of almost 75 miles per hour.
YOU1000000147_S0000054	and temperatures of negative 45 degrees Fahrenheit, where it remains in this state of forced hibernation for 15 years.
YOU1000000147_S0000055	To see if it's really worth it, you'll have to visit Pullman's store in Paris. Very few restaurants are entrusted with the beef and Pullman pays each establishment a personal visit before they're even allowed to serve it.
YOU1000000147_S0000056	Lob-knot potatoes.
YOU1000000147_S0000057	The potato is one of the most humble foods around, but not when it comes to the sought-after labanat variety, aka the world's most expensive potato.
YOU1000000147_S0000058	These spuds are so well-regarded that they're even known as the caviar of the potato world.
YOU1000000147_S0000059	Why, you ask? Firstly, they're almost exclusively grown on the tiny island of Noirmoutier off the coast of Western France, and only about 20 tons are produced yearly.
YOU1000000147_S0000060	Preparing them for sale is also an arduous process because they're too delicate to be machine harvested.
YOU1000000147_S0000061	so each potato must be carefully hand-picked instead. With all the added effort it takes to get a hold of them, you might be wondering why labanat potatoes are worth eating to begin with.
YOU1000000147_S0000062	Fans of the souped-up spuds say the sea air and sea water, which acts as a fertilizer for the soil, gives the potatoes a hint of sea salt and even a suggestion of lemon.
YOU1000000147_S0000063	If you fancy Labanauts for tea, you should probably know that they sell for about $300 per pound.
YOU1000000147_S0000064	White truffles.
YOU1000000147_S0000065	If there's one thing capable of elevating a dish to new layers of prestige, it's truffles. These fragrant fungi are some of the world's rarest delicacies.
YOU1000000147_S0000066	and even the Romans couldn't get enough, attributing them with therapeutic and aphrodisiac properties.
YOU1000000147_S0000067	White truffles, or the diamond of the kitchen, are by far the best. The knobbly white mushrooms can only be harvested between October through December.
YOU1000000147_S0000068	in the forest of Piedmont in Northern Italy, where they grow inches below the earth with the roots of hardwood trees, which means finding them isn't easy.
YOU1000000147_S0000069	Specially trained dogs or pigs, known as trefoculteurs, must scour the forest floor in search of hidden gems below the earth.
YOU1000000147_S0000070	Scientists have tried and failed to domesticate white truffles, meaning you also won't be stumbling upon any in your local supermarket anytime soon.
YOU1000000147_S0000071	These factors all contribute to the fervor surrounding truffles and the value their complex flavor can bring to risotto, pasta, and even foie gras. Just one pound of white truffles costs around $2,000.
YOU1000000147_S0000072	And in 2009, a record-breaking single 1.6 pound specimen was even auctioned for an eye-watering $150,000.
YOU1000000147_S0000073	Kopi Luwak Coffee
YOU1000000147_S0000074	Many people enjoy an after-dinner beverage, and if you're entertaining guests with particularly deep pockets, perhaps only Kopi Luwak coffee will suffice.
YOU1000000147_S0000075	Legend has it this highly valued coffee was first discovered in Indonesia under Dutch colonial rule.
YOU1000000147_S0000076	Native farmers and plantation workers were forbidden from harvesting coffee for their own use and were left to scrounge around for it.
YOU1000000147_S0000077	That's when they made an unusual discovery. Civet cats would eat coffee cherries and poop out the seeds, or coffee beans, without digesting them.
YOU1000000147_S0000078	After brewing coffee from the discarded beans, they realized it tasted great too, mostly because the civets picked only the ripest cherries.
YOU1000000147_S0000079	The tradition continued and nowadays vendors of authentic Kopi Luwak coffee can command anywhere between $250 to 1,200 per kilogram.
YOU1000000147_S0000080	There are some controversies surrounding the unconventional beverage though. Primarily, civet cats are nocturnal and don't have big appetites.
YOU1000000147_S0000081	which means more than 80% of Kopi Luwak coffee sold in the US has never actually passed through one.
YOU1000000147_S0000082	Attempts to industrialize the process also means many civet cats are caged and force-fed the berries round the clock, which results in crappy coffee made by very crappy people.
YOU1000000147_S0000083	Densuke Black Watermelon.
YOU1000000147_S0000084	After a meal as rich as the one I've just laid out, a fresh fruit salad is about as much dessert as you could manage.
YOU1000000147_S0000085	This won't be any old fruit though, duh. First up, the densuki black watermelon.
YOU1000000147_S0000086	These rare melons are exclusively grown on the northern island of Hokkaido in Japan in annual quantities of about 10,000 units.
YOU1000000147_S0000087	Besides their intriguingly dark outer appearance, they're said to have crisper flesh, more juice, and an enhanced sweetness compared to their overseas relatives.
YOU1000000147_S0000088	There's a lucrative market for decorative fruit in Japan, so it's not uncommon for densukis to be purchased as expensive gifts.
YOU1000000147_S0000089	Depending on the size, they usually go for upwards of $250, but in 2008, one fine specimen even sold for $6,100.
YOU1000000147_S0000090	Yubari King Melon
YOU1000000147_S0000091	Even the Densuke is a bargain compared to Japan's most highly-priced melon, the Yubari King.
YOU1000000147_S0000092	which is basically a cross between two cantaloupes.
YOU1000000147_S0000093	This esteemed fruit is also exclusively grown on Hokkaido Island and is a major status symbol for anyone with enough
YOU1000000147_S0000095	spare dough to add one to their collection.
YOU1000000147_S0000096	In spring 2016, supermarket owner Takamura Kunishi hit the headlines after he pocketed a pair of Yubari Kings for the eye-popping price of $27,240.
YOU1000000147_S0000097	making them the most expensive melons ever sold. But what does one of these premium fruits taste of? A gold bullion? Apparently, they just have an ultra-concentrated sweetness.
YOU1000000147_S0000098	Kunishi said he offered such a fee for the melons to pay back the hard work of the Yubari farmers.
YOU1000000147_S0000099	but even a less coveted buyer can still expect to pay thousands at auction. Japan's luxury fruit market isn't just exclusive to melons.
YOU1000000147_S0000100	And in 2019, Takamaru Kanishi raised eyebrows again after paying $11,318 for a bunch of ruby Roman grapes.
YOU1000000147_S0000101	which worked out at around $370 per grape.
YOU1000000147_S0000102	This rare variety is lauded for its juiciness, high sugar content, and low acidity. Oh, and did I mention they're about the size of ping pong balls thanks to years of selective breeding?
YOU1000000147_S0000103	When they first hit the market in 2008, 700 gram Ruby Roman Bunches sold for around $910, and their prices only skyrocketed since.
YOU1000000147_S0000104	Donkey cheese
YOU1000000147_S0000105	A cheese course is the perfect way to complete a meal, but for a banquet like this one, plain old cheddar just won't cut it.
YOU1000000147_S0000106	Believe it or not, there's such a thing as donkey cheese, otherwise known as pule, and it'll cost you a pretty penny.
YOU1000000147_S0000107	This bizarre creation is only produced by farmer Slobodan Simic on his rural farm in Serbia with the help of some 300 donkeys from the Zasavica Nature Reserve.
YOU1000000147_S0000108	It's esteemed for its supposed healthy benefits, with claims that it's high in protein, calcium and omega-3 fatty acids.
YOU1000000147_S0000109	Getting milk from the dockies isn't easy because only about 20 animals produce it at one time.
YOU1000000147_S0000110	and it takes several gallons of milk to make one pound of cheese.
YOU1000000147_S0000111	This is because their milk doesn't contain enough casein, the characteristic that thickens it into curd, to make the cheese the traditional way.
YOU1000000147_S0000112	Thankfully, Simic has a secret method to make the cheese, but it comes at a price.
YOU1000000147_S0000113	Each kilo sells for about $1,110. That's a lot to pay for literal ass cheese.
YOU1000000147_S0000114	don't you think? Which of these premium ingredients would you most like to try? Let me know in the comments and thanks for watching.
