YOU1000000155_S0000000	Real estate investing rules of thumb, the 2% rule, the 50% rule, and the 70% rule.
YOU1000000155_S0000001	There are some rules of thumb that can help investors quickly screen through deals to make a good educated guess on whether or not to pursue them.
YOU1000000155_S0000002	Now this is important. Notice that I didn't say there are some rules of thumb that can help investors make purchase decisions.
YOU1000000155_S0000003	because rules of thumb are not meant to be hard and fast rules. They simply help an investor get a quick and dirty opinion on some valuable metrics.
YOU1000000155_S0000004	always do a proper analysis. But regardless, these rules of thumb can come in really handy in saving you from analyzing every single deal that you come across.
YOU1000000155_S0000005	My name is Brandon Turner and in this video I've outlined several of the most common real estate math rules of thumb.
YOU1000000155_S0000006	so you can begin practicing them in your own analysis of properties.
YOU1000000155_S0000008	First, the 2% rule, also known as the 1% rule or the 2% test.
YOU1000000155_S0000009	Perhaps one of the most common rules of thumb used by rental property investors is known as the 2% rule.
YOU1000000155_S0000010	But not because it's a rule, so I say 2% test. I like that better.
YOU1000000155_S0000011	Essentially, this rule of thumb looks at the monthly rent divided by the value of the property in a percentage form.
YOU1000000155_S0000012	For those who just got confused, let's make this super simple. If a property rents for $2,000 a month,
YOU1000000155_S0000013	and the value is $200,000, then 2,000 divided by 200,000 equals 1%.
YOU1000000155_S0000014	In this example, the property does not pass the 2% test, but it does meet the 1% test. Exactly.
YOU1000000155_S0000015	Or, what if a property that rents for $1,500 a month and it costs $180,000 to buy? Well, $1,500 divided by $180,000 is .8%.
YOU1000000155_S0000016	That's definitely short of the 1% rule or 1% test. Now, what if that property rents for $1,500 a month, but it's worth $120,000?
YOU1000000155_S0000017	Well, 1500 divided by 120,000 equals 1.25%. Alright, so you get how the math works now, right? But what does it mean?
YOU1000000155_S0000018	Well, essentially, the 1% or 2% test gives us a quick and dirty view on whether or not the property will produce positive cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000019	And of course, just a rule of thumb, it isn't always precise, but generally speaking, the higher the percentage, the better the cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000020	This also greatly depends on location, price, and how much the expenses truly are on the property.
YOU1000000155_S0000021	But the rule of thumb can help an investor make some decisions on whether or not to pursue a certain property.
YOU1000000155_S0000022	For example, I know that most properties that fall short of 1% will likely never produce a positive cash flow for me.
YOU1000000155_S0000023	If it's between 1 and 2% it probably will, and if it's above 2% which is really hard to find today, then I'm almost positive that it will.
YOU1000000155_S0000024	So, if my real estate agent tells me that they have a perfect rental house for me to buy, and I see that the purchase price is $125,000,
YOU1000000155_S0000025	and I find that it will rent for $1,000 a month, I can make a very quick decision and I know that, most likely, that deal ain't gonna ever provide cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000026	because it falls short of the 1% rule because 1000 divided by 125,000 equals 0.8%.
YOU1000000155_S0000027	In a case like this, I probably wouldn't even spend any more time looking at the deal if I was only interested in the cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000028	So that's the value of the 2% rule test thing. While the 2% rule and the 1% rule or test we just mentioned
YOU1000000155_S0000029	They can help you get with a go, no-go decision on looking further into a rental property.
YOU1000000155_S0000030	it doesn't really tell us how much cash flow we might expect. For that, investors often rely on the 50% rule of thumb.
YOU1000000155_S0000031	The 50% rule states that on average and over time, half of the income in a property is spent on operating expenses.
YOU1000000155_S0000032	Now, what are operating expenses? Well, good question. Operating expenses are all of the expenses involved with running a rental property.
YOU1000000155_S0000033	except the loan payment. So it includes taxes, insurance, utilities, repairs, vacancy, and other metrics.
YOU1000000155_S0000034	that leave the landlord's checking account every single month or every year, depends on how you want to look at it.
YOU1000000155_S0000035	The 50% rule can help an investor quickly estimate the cash flow of a rental property because it combines all of those expenses, except for the loan, into one easy number.
YOU1000000155_S0000037	So, let's work through this. Imagine a property rents for $2,000 a month. The 50% rule says half of this, a thousand, will be spent on expenses.
YOU1000000155_S0000038	This means we're left with a thousand bucks, but now we need to make the mortgage payment on this, right? Unless you paid cash for the property, but let's say you didn't.
YOU1000000155_S0000039	So with that thousand dollars we have left, let's say the mortgage is $600. So how much do you have left? 400 bucks.
YOU1000000155_S0000040	because 2000 times 50% equals 1000, 1000 minus 600 for operating expenses is $400 in cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000041	That remaining number is what you can estimate over time on average you might get in monthly cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000042	Of course, that 50% estimate on operating expenses can really vary wildly depending on the property.
YOU1000000155_S0000043	In some areas, taxes and insurance might be incredibly high, but in other areas it might be much lower. Some properties require that the landlord pay all utilities.
YOU1000000155_S0000044	where other properties allow the tenant to pay their own. And while inherent weaknesses do exist.
YOU1000000155_S0000045	The 50% rule does have value. I mean, when you're looking at a property that rents for $1,200 a month,
YOU1000000155_S0000047	and you know the mortgage payment would be around a thousand, you can pretty much guarantee that property will not produce a positive cash flow.
YOU1000000155_S0000048	Because 200 bucks a month is not a lot of room for all those expenses. Because 1200 times 50% equals 600.
YOU1000000155_S0000049	600 minus a thousand is negative 400. Now, the 50% rule helps keep real estate investors in check,
YOU1000000155_S0000050	And to remind us that there are a lot of expenses that over time add up. Yeah, I mean a new roof is only needed every 20 years.
YOU1000000155_S0000051	But if you divide a $10,000 roof into 240 months, that roof is actually costing you $42 a month, every single month.
YOU1000000155_S0000052	These operating expenses add up over time, and as most investors have seen, they tend to settle around 50% given a long enough time frame.
YOU1000000155_S0000053	Okay on to the final rule of thumb today the 70% rule
YOU1000000155_S0000054	The last couple rules of thumb that we talked about were designed to help rental property owners, but what about the house flippers, the wholesalers? I don't want to leave you guys out.
YOU1000000155_S0000055	So for those who are flipping houses, the 70% rule can be helpful in determining just how much to pay for a property.
YOU1000000155_S0000056	The 70% rule states that the most you should pay for a potential flip is 70% of the after repair value, like what it would sell for when it was all fixed up.
YOU1000000155_S0000057	minus the repair costs. So example, if a home would sell for 300 grand all fixed up and the property needed 50 grand worth of work to get there,
YOU1000000155_S0000058	Then, 300,000 times 70% is 210,000. Subtract out that $50,000 and you're left with 160K.
YOU1000000155_S0000059	According to the 70% rule, the most someone should pay for that property would be $160K. But of course, there are problems with the 70% rule.
YOU1000000155_S0000060	This rule of thumb assumes that 30% of the ARV, the after repair value, is going to be spent on holding costs, on clothing costs, on the buying side, the selling side.
YOU1000000155_S0000061	commissions, taxes, attorney fees, title company fees and more, and the flippers profit and any other charges that come up during the deal. Now this works well in some markets,
YOU1000000155_S0000062	but it has some severe limitations.
YOU1000000155_S0000063	For example, the 70% rule doesn't really work that well for a property with a really low ARV, after repair value.
YOU1000000155_S0000064	such as $50,000. As mentioned earlier, the 30% deducted from the ARV includes the holding costs and the closing costs, as well as the profit
YOU1000000155_S0000065	the investor or the flipper wants to make. However, like 30% of 50 grand is like $15,000. So following the 70% rule,
YOU1000000155_S0000066	All of the fees, cost, and profit would only be $15,000.
YOU1000000155_S0000067	If the fees and holding costs were to total like 10 grand, that would leave just $5,000 in profit for the house flipper.
YOU1000000155_S0000068	And I don't know any house flipper who's going to take on the risk of flipping a house for just five grand.
YOU1000000155_S0000069	So, following the 70% rule, a flipper or wholesaler would pay far too much for the property in this example.
YOU1000000155_S0000070	And investor flipping houses at this level might require far less than 70%, maybe a 50% or even lower.
YOU1000000155_S0000071	Now, a similar problem exists with the 70% rule for more expensive properties.
YOU1000000155_S0000072	The 70% rule would dictate that a home with an ARV of 700 grand that needs 50 grand to work
YOU1000000155_S0000073	should produce a maximum offer of $440,000.
YOU1000000155_S0000074	But, in most markets, finding a $700,000 property for $440,000 is simply not feasible.
YOU1000000155_S0000075	A person who sticks exclusively to that 70% rule are likely never going to find a good enough deal to ever flip a single property in that market.
YOU1000000155_S0000076	In this case, 80% or even 85% might be good enough.
YOU1000000155_S0000077	Furthermore, some investors may spend more or less on fees and costs because of their particular life situation or location.
YOU1000000155_S0000078	For example, in some states, purchasing a home may require three grand in closing costs, while in other states it might be $6,000.
YOU1000000155_S0000079	Some investors may have a real estate license, which saves them tens of thousands of dollars in commissions.
YOU1000000155_S0000080	Whereas, other investors, well, they may need to pay commissions when they actually sell the property. So, how should the 70% rule be valued?
YOU1000000155_S0000081	Well, carefully. It's a quick and dirty way to guesstimate the approximate amount you should pay for a property.
YOU1000000155_S0000082	But, as with all rules of thumb, no concrete decisions should be made unless you've run a real estate analysis on the property.
YOU1000000155_S0000083	And of course, if you want to do that, check out the BiggerPockets suite of calculators. You can get them at biggerpockets.com forward slash calc, C-A-L-C.
YOU1000000155_S0000084	Check it out. Alright, that's all I got. If you like this video, make sure to give a thumbs up and subscribe to our channel. It'd be great. We'll see you around the site, around the community.
YOU1000000155_S0000085	around our Instagram or Facebook or wherever you like to connect with us at. For BiggerPockets.com, my name is Brandon Turner, signing off.
