YOU1000000160_S0000000	The console wars are entering a whole new era in 2020 as we move on to the next generation of gaming and a massive tech giant enters the picture.
YOU1000000160_S0000001	But as a gamer, what new console do you choose? Or do you pick them all?
YOU1000000160_S0000002	Well, we made the choice even easier for you today, as we pit the PS5 up against the Xbox 2 and the Google Stadia in the ultimate battle of console domination.
YOU1000000160_S0000003	This isn't just about brand loyalty as we break down gaming choices, features, graphics, and online interaction to determine the ultimate winner.
YOU1000000160_S0000005	Graphics Comparisons 4K graphics are the new standard in gaming, and this is the bare minimum that will be supplied by all three consoles.
YOU1000000160_S0000006	The one caveat? Internet speed. Playing a detail-rich game like Assassin's Creed Origins could look very different at one home using Stadia compared to another.
YOU1000000160_S0000007	The Google Stadia uses variable graphic performance based solely on internet speed.
YOU1000000160_S0000008	So if your parents are binge-watching Netflix while your little sister jams out to Spotify, you could easily find yourself playing a game at 720p with stereo sound instead of being maxed out at 4K graphics with HDR video and 5.1 surround sound.
YOU1000000160_S0000009	The PS5 and Xbox Two will rely on discs and downloads to provide a consistent quality for a lot of the games.
YOU1000000160_S0000010	Besides the 4K quality, each of the three consoles also aim to provide 60 frames per second as a standard for a majority of the game.
YOU1000000160_S0000011	In simple terms, character movements are going to look incredibly smooth, things like car races are going to be fluid, and all those first-person shooters will be even better than you could imagine.
YOU1000000160_S0000012	Another way these consoles are all improving on the graphical presentation? With ray tracing.
YOU1000000160_S0000013	The lighting technique includes extremely vivid graphics, and will make everything from reflections to shadows look even more realistic than they already are.
YOU1000000160_S0000014	All in all, each console is pretty much on par with each other in the graphics department, with the PS5 and Xbox 2 taking a slight edge because of Stadia's reliance on proper internet speeds.
YOU1000000160_S0000015	The Controllers What are good graphics without a good controller to enjoy those games with? The PS5 and Xbox Two both have a history of controllers their gamers are used to.
YOU1000000160_S0000016	While you can expect more of the same from Xbox with their Pro Controller, Sony is making vast improvements for their next entry in the DualShock controller.
YOU1000000160_S0000017	One of the biggest features is a major upgrade in the rumble technology and the adaptive nature of the analog stacks.
YOU1000000160_S0000018	No longer will the controller just play out a random rumble or buzz while you play.
YOU1000000160_S0000019	everything reacts to the surroundings you're in. If you're an undercover agent who must climb their way through a snowy mountainside, you'll feel the struggle of each footstep as you move the analog stick around.
YOU1000000160_S0000020	Driving a vehicle on a beach instead of the road? You'll feel the difference as you travel through sand as opposed to the paved road.
YOU1000000160_S0000021	On top of that, the trigger buttons on top of the newest DualShock controller are more sensitive than ever.
YOU1000000160_S0000022	Blasting your way through levels with a laser gun will feel very different than playing as Batman and throwing a Batarang, and the pressure you place on the trigger will indicate the speed and force rather than just button mashing.
YOU1000000160_S0000023	Google Stadia isn't trying to reinvent the wheel with their controller either. Knowing what works, the Stadia controller features dual analog sticks, the typical input buttons, and multiple triggers on top.
YOU1000000160_S0000024	If the DualShock controller works without any major problems or glitches, then the PS5 edges out the competition for the innovative nature of their design.
YOU1000000160_S0000025	Cloud Game Services And speaking of cloud-based gaming, Google Stadia is not the only one providing this streaming service.
YOU1000000160_S0000026	Besides their typical game releases and digital downloads, both Sony and Microsoft have their own subscription-based streaming game services.
YOU1000000160_S0000027	The Xbox Game Pass is priced at $10 a month and features over 100 games with a rotating title of options including console classics.
YOU1000000160_S0000028	The xCloud service Microsoft runs on looks to expand the game pass to all types of iOS and Android devices in the near future.
YOU1000000160_S0000029	The PlayStation Now service has an affordable option if players are willing to pay for a whole year up front.
YOU1000000160_S0000030	While the base price starts at $9.99 per month, a whole year costs around $60, which equals out to $5 a month.
YOU1000000160_S0000031	The PS5 will be one of the best ways to enjoy the service, with a huge library of past games from the PS2, PS3, and PS4 all rolled into one.
YOU1000000160_S0000032	The cloud-based service also includes PC gaming through the PS Now app. The pricing discounts give the PlayStation Cloud streaming a huge plus.
YOU1000000160_S0000033	But the Xbox Game Pass does have some exclusive rights to Minecraft, so there's that. It's a little hard to compare Stadia's options until the service fully rolls out, but there will be a free plan.
YOU1000000160_S0000034	allowing gamers to hop on any Google device and play. The Pro plan will include a number of free monthly gaming options as well. Solid state hard drives.
YOU1000000160_S0000035	The insides of both the Xbox 2 and PS5 will show a major improvement with solid-state hard drives.
YOU1000000160_S0000036	The massive improvement was years in the making, and the more affordable hard drives will be a game changer in many ways.
YOU1000000160_S0000037	Load times will be virtually non-existent, and the struggles of saving hard drive space will be gone as well. With a solid-state drive, gamers don't need to download the whole game to play.
YOU1000000160_S0000038	Not interested in the single-player campaign? Just download the multiplayer element of the game and be on your merry way!
YOU1000000160_S0000039	Not only will you be able to save hard drive space, but the anticipation of playing a game will not take hours and hours.
YOU1000000160_S0000040	On the Google side of things, even though the Stadia platform will be available through the Chromecast Ultra and Chromebooks, there are no downloads needed. Everything will be cloud-based.
YOU1000000160_S0000041	saving some hard drive space and reducing loading times as Google's high-speed servers provide all the loading and space you need for a whole library of games.
