YOU1000000166_S0000057	I'll instead be referring to the Yoda species as the Tridactyls.
YOU1000000166_S0000058	because their extremities have three digits, right? But bear in mind that's really just a fan-made designation for all the members of the Yoda species that we're currently aware of, which are just three.
YOU1000000166_S0000059	Honestly, you got original Yoda, you got Yaddle from the Phantom Menace who just appears for a couple seconds, and Baby Yoda, whatever his name ends up being, from the Mandalorian.
YOU1000000166_S0000060	So with that bit of housekeeping out of the way and with the very short list of actual known members of the Yoda species, what do we know about tridactyls?
YOU1000000166_S0000061	We know that Yoda lived to the ripe old age of 900 in Return of the Jedi, which everyone else is surprised about, but he isn't, seeming to indicate that it's not really that big of a deal for him.
YOU1000000166_S0000062	Baby Yoda, who's just stuck with that name for this episode, I guess, is 50, but functionally he's about a 10 month old.
YOU1000000166_S0000063	if my kid is any indication. He's nonverbal, but he is capable of walking and getting into trouble. So we know-
YOU1000000166_S0000064	as a tridactyl you get 900 years in the galaxy on the high end but at least the
YOU1000000166_S0000066	The first 50 of them are spent as a baby, which I guess leaves like a hundred to make it through high school.
YOU1000000166_S0000067	Another 200 years of living in your parents' basement, before finally getting your own apartment at the tender age of 300.
YOU1000000166_S0000068	Now, because we're working in outer space and in a fictional franchise, it's worth double-checking. When they say that Baby Yoda is 50 years old in The Mandalorian,
YOU1000000166_S0000069	Does that translate to years as we understand them here on Earth? And it appears like it does. According to Wikipedia, the Republic standardized its time based on Coruscant.
YOU1000000166_S0000070	which, conveniently, rotates its sun exactly once every 365 Coruscantian days, which are broken down themselves into 24-hour increments.
YOU1000000166_S0000071	And then, minutes that are incredibly close to our own minutes. So when Yoda says that he's 900 years old, it's pretty close to what we think 900 years is.
YOU1000000166_S0000072	And the Mandalorian has every reason to be surprised that his 50-year-old Mark was still a baby.
YOU1000000166_S0000073	So, knowing that, it's time to talk about the biology. Having such a long development period is more than just an interesting evolutionary quirk,
YOU1000000166_S0000074	It actually tells us a lot about how tridactyls may have evolved over time. Mostly because it parallels a lot of our own human evolution.
YOU1000000166_S0000075	You see, most animals evolved to shorten the amount of time between birth and reproductive maturity so that they can go on and grow their population as fast as possible.
YOU1000000166_S0000076	But that's not the only successful evolutionary strategy. You may have noticed that us humans have incredibly long and particularly vulnerable childhoods.
YOU1000000166_S0000077	When a baby giraffe is born, it can stand almost... almost... almost... right away. Oh, they're so cute! Humans, on the other hand, not so much.
YOU1000000166_S0000078	It is taking months, if not a year, for a baby human to actually get up on its feet. So why do humans, the smartest animals on the planet,
YOU1000000166_S0000079	come out so useless.
YOU1000000166_S0000080	Well, turns out that the whole issue comes down to our brains. You see, our brainy heads and the fact that they're so fat have changed our entire course of human evolution.
YOU1000000166_S0000081	Our ancestors, who many believe emerged from sub-Saharan Africa, were among the first species of animals to stop walking around on four legs
YOU1000000166_S0000082	and start walking up on two. Our brains were big enough that we were able to logic out the idea that it took less energy to walk on two legs.
YOU1000000166_S0000083	and it minimized our bald skin's exposure to the extremely hot ground temperatures in those African deserts.
YOU1000000166_S0000084	As newly bipedal people, our evolution started favoring other members of our species who could also walk upright. Good for us, natural selection at its finest.
YOU1000000166_S0000085	But there's always a price to pay for innovation. You see, as we evolve to be more and more capable of walking
YOU1000000166_S0000086	and running around on two legs, our bodies evolve to facilitate that and compensate for our changed center of gravity, primarily doing this by narrowing our hips.
YOU1000000166_S0000087	This, in turn, helped us to walk upright like champs, but now all of a sudden we had a problem. That big fat head of ours was literally too big to be born.
YOU1000000166_S0000088	Sure, we had ourselves a big brain, but now there was nowhere for it to go because our hips were too narrow to accommodate birthing ahead that huge.
YOU1000000166_S0000089	So, human evolution had to change again. As the theory goes, we started having babies earlier in their gestational period.
YOU1000000166_S0000090	earlier, at a time when the baby was still tiny and smushy and helpless, which would be pretty darn bad for our survival except for one thing.
YOU1000000166_S0000091	The heads were still small enough to squeeze up on out of there. Still a very painful process, but now at least it was doable.
YOU1000000166_S0000092	And then once the baby was on the other end, there would be what's known as the fourth trimester.
YOU1000000166_S0000093	An extra trimester of development that happens outside in the real world, where we as parents would have to take care of that helpless newborn,
YOU1000000166_S0000094	Because technically, it still should have been developing in the womb. It just needed to be, you know, evicted from its home before it was too big to leave its door.
YOU1000000166_S0000095	Now, let's take a look at our friendly Yoda. What features do we see? Well, he's bipedal, he's small, with a disproportionately huge head for his highly evolved brain,
YOU1000000166_S0000096	He's got a short, highly efficient body with diminutive, narrow features, including his hips. Even looking at the basic character model,
YOU1000000166_S0000097	you can see how in order to procreate, the tridactyls would have to have themselves radically different proportions.
YOU1000000166_S0000098	You can also see how having a big brain is a huge evolutionary advantage. Humans are so far at the top of the food chain that we protect other members of the food chain.
YOU1000000166_S0000099	Tridactyls in the Star Wars universe are the wisest and most powerful force users in the galaxy.
YOU1000000166_S0000100	But the downside is that they, like us, are essentially born too early. Helpless for months, if not years, or until at least their dad makes them pay rent.
YOU1000000166_S0000101	and their mom stops doing their laundry. This theory continues to hold water if we look at infancy for humans versus infancy for tridactyls. In their first two years,
YOU1000000166_S0000102	Human baby brains grow to 75% of their full adult size. We don't know if this is the same for tridactyls,
YOU1000000166_S0000103	But we do know that the proportions of human babies parallel the proportions of baby Yoda. Enormous head, adorably tiny body.
YOU1000000166_S0000104	Besides making babies hilariously top-heavy, these proportions also serve a function. In infancy,
YOU1000000166_S0000105	Human brains command up to 87% of the total energy that the body uses at rest.
YOU1000000166_S0000106	Meaning that even while sleeping, the body is diverting a massive amount of energy to growing the brain.
YOU1000000166_S0000107	Because of this, the rest of the baby's growth lags behind the head, where the brain is. This, according to the expensive tissue hypothesis.
YOU1000000166_S0000108	We can see that Baby Yoda is an extreme version of this principle with a wildly huge and merchandisable head
YOU1000000166_S0000109	and a teeny tiny body, making me think that Baby Yoda is an extremely evolved version of what the human race could look like someday.
YOU1000000166_S0000111	The process of evolutionarily elongating the development period is called Niat-D.
YOU1000000166_S0000112	And after humans benefited from it, surviving when our relatives didn't, well, evolution didn't stop its roll.
YOU1000000166_S0000113	Humans are actually still experiencing longer development periods now than we even did 10,000 years ago.
YOU1000000166_S0000114	The shape of our faces and heads are continually becoming less like our Neanderthal cousins by becoming flatter, less hairy, less oblong.
YOU1000000166_S0000115	Again, we share a lot of these same features with Yoda, who's small, flat-faced with an enormous head. But if human evolution continues to make our childhoods longer and longer,
YOU1000000166_S0000116	The question of course becomes, where does it stop? Well, it stops at Yoda.
YOU1000000166_S0000117	The problem with a long childhood is that a lot can happen when you're tiny and helpless.
YOU1000000166_S0000118	Eventually, there's an evolutionary tipping point where childhood becomes so long that it actually leaves the species too vulnerable to survive into adulthood.
YOU1000000166_S0000119	Tridactyls could very well be the extreme end point of a species like ours.
YOU1000000166_S0000120	As the Mandalorian clearly shows, baby tridactyls, even 50-year-old baby tridactyls, aren't capable of taking care of themselves.
YOU1000000166_S0000121	Sure, they have impressive force powers, but very little control over them.
YOU1000000166_S0000123	Human children similarly are pretty darn helpless, and it means that we have to do things like baby-proof the house, and make up all kinds of safety rules for kids.
YOU1000000166_S0000124	Imagine having to worry about that sort of stuff for 50, or even 100 years. It becomes extremely hard for the species to get their offspring to a place of self-sufficiency.
YOU1000000166_S0000125	And that's just the tip of the iceberg. Natural disasters, plagues, drone attacks from the Empire.
YOU1000000166_S0000126	All of those things are gonna be pretty darn hard to avoid, but they become a lot easier to bounce back from if suddenly your species can repopulate quickly.
YOU1000000166_S0000127	But if all of a sudden you're spending a hundred years or more to reproduce a single generation?
YOU1000000166_S0000128	I mean, you're just begging for the next Death Star to give you a little zap, which brings us to Yoda!
YOU1000000166_S0000129	We know so little about his history, but what we're able to theorize is pretty darn incredible. He's practically the last of his species,
YOU1000000166_S0000130	because of the evolutionary double-edged sword that he's dealing with. On one hand, he's one of the most highly evolved beings in the galaxy.
YOU1000000166_S0000131	But he's so evolved that his species can no longer survive. They're completely obscure.
YOU1000000166_S0000132	It's incredibly tragic, and no, we don't have any of the details about how the tridactyls were wiped out, but that elongated childhood.
YOU1000000166_S0000133	that extended neoteny to the extremes of 50 plus years of childhood, that is certainly a massive contributor
YOU1000000166_S0000134	as to why. So incredibly, Star Wars, the series often derided as being space fantasy
YOU1000000166_S0000135	and not science fiction, turns out to be scientifically plausible yet again, so, gotta hand it to you, Lucas, I'm pretty stunned.
YOU1000000166_S0000136	No, I've tried to help you out with this and the whole midichlorians powering the force thing, but I gotta admit, still have some quibbles to level at you about the Jedi's recruitment practices.
YOU1000000166_S0000137	That one will be coming up pretty soon. We have some bones to pick on that front, okay friend? In the meantime, if you didn't see the real-life equivalent of midichlorians,
YOU1000000166_S0000138	and how they're actually powering the real life force in your day to day life, click the video that you see on screen right now.
