YOU1000000170_S0000001	I worked at this place, CWI.
YOU1000000170_S0000002	And for my then current project, which was the Amoeba operating system, which I was working under Sapo Mellander.
YOU1000000170_S0000003	One of our projects was to write application level utilities
YOU1000000170_S0000004	for this new amoeba operating system.
YOU1000000170_S0000005	and so there was an operating system kernel and it was very good at talking to the network
YOU1000000170_S0000006	and it was very good at managing processes, but there wasn't much user-level software.
YOU1000000170_S0000007	There was barely a shell, I think there was a ported, very old Unix shell, something like the original Unix version 6 shell.
YOU1000000170_S0000008	But because the file system model on Amoeba was so very different,
YOU1000000170_S0000009	we couldn't take an existing suite of Unix utilities.
YOU1000000170_S0000010	And so we wanted it to be self-hosting.
YOU1000000170_S0000012	And in order to do that, we realized we needed a large amount of user level sort of applications, utilities, tools.
YOU1000000170_S0000013	whatever you call it, from an editor to a mail program, to a login utility and a backup tool.
YOU1000000170_S0000014	And one of the things I realized as we had a small team of people sort of working on those things,
YOU1000000170_S0000015	that it was very slow going writing all that stuff in C and it wasn't particularly interesting or sort of novel.
YOU1000000170_S0000016	or difficult and often we also didn't really care how fast the code ran.
YOU1000000170_S0000017	All the reasons why you would write a piece of software in C didn't really apply.
YOU1000000170_S0000018	The only reason left was that C was the only language for which we had a compiler.
YOU1000000170_S0000019	There was this ABC language that I had in the back of my mind that would be a much better language to write.
YOU1000000170_S0000020	a whole bunch of utility application tools for Amoeba.
YOU1000000170_S0000021	Except that ABC was so high and abstract that it really
YOU1000000170_S0000023	It wasn't a good language to talk to servers and file systems and processes.
YOU1000000170_S0000024	The whole operating system was abstracted away from ABC.
YOU1000000170_S0000025	It was almost something like... I don't know, in an alternate universe ABC could have become the language of spreadsheets.
YOU1000000170_S0000026	It was very good for talking about a user's data.
YOU1000000170_S0000027	and doing all sorts of clever stuff with that data.
YOU1000000170_S0000028	It did that using very general all-purpose data structures like lists and dictionaries.
YOU1000000170_S0000029	And of course it had very nice code structuring devices.
YOU1000000170_S0000030	like a small number of simple statements that could be combined in any way you wanted to create other constructs.
YOU1000000170_S0000031	the usual function and procedure abstractions.
YOU1000000170_S0000032	It was not at all an object-oriented language, although the implementation had some objects shining through.
YOU1000000170_S0000033	Anyway, ABCS...
YOU1000000170_S0000035	as it existed still, wasn't usable.
YOU1000000170_S0000036	But since I had worked on the ABC project, I knew exactly how it was built.
YOU1000000170_S0000037	And I had this idea in my head that...
YOU1000000170_S0000039	Given how much time we had available for our project, I could actually build a whole new language, design and implement it from scratch.
YOU1000000170_S0000040	given what I learned about both the design and the implementation of ABC and start using it to implement our suite of tools.
YOU1000000170_S0000041	and still be ahead of the game compared to a situation where we would just have sort of
YOU1000000170_S0000043	clunked on writing the things we wanted to write in C.
YOU1000000170_S0000044	for three months.
YOU1000000170_S0000046	I did my day job and at night and whenever I got a chance I kept working on Python.
YOU1000000170_S0000047	I believe that within three months I was to the point where I could tell people, look, here, this is what I built.
YOU1000000170_S0000048	and it had an interactive interpreter loop.
YOU1000000170_S0000049	So the first demos were all, let's assign an expression to a variable and print it back.
YOU1000000170_S0000051	And let's define a small function and call it and let's put some let's put some things in an array and iterate over the array
YOU1000000170_S0000053	and all those things worked.
YOU1000000170_S0000055	And
YOU1000000170_S0000057	Somehow, and I don't exactly know how fast this happened, but
YOU1000000170_S0000059	Certainly my two office mates were almost instantly taken with it and started helping out.
YOU1000000170_S0000061	And they and a few others within the institute were very excited about this thing that I built.
YOU1000000170_S0000063	And started sort of
YOU1000000170_S0000065	We didn't use it on Amoeba, because it wasn't mature enough to write the Amoeba utilities we wanted.
YOU1000000170_S0000066	But it was already instantly useful enough to run on our UNIX system.
YOU1000000170_S0000067	people within CWI, even outside my own department, started using it.
YOU1000000170_S0000068	and recognizing that it was fun and productive to use and they used it for small scripts.
YOU1000000170_S0000069	and people started contributing things like.
YOU1000000170_S0000071	bug fixes. Somehow things went very quickly during that first year.
YOU1000000170_S0000072	By the end of 1990, a year after I started, we developed a plan to do an open-source release of this language.
YOU1000000170_S0000074	And this was before the word open source had even been coined.
YOU1000000170_S0000075	So we didn't call it that but we did have some models we had like
YOU1000000170_S0000077	X11, the Windows system at the time.
YOU1000000170_S0000078	had a distribution that was one of the sort of open source examples.
YOU1000000170_S0000079	With two colleagues, I worked on building a distribution.
YOU1000000170_S0000080	Actually, it turned out to be very simple.
YOU1000000170_S0000081	to get management to sign off on this release.
YOU1000000170_S0000083	That was an incredibly lucky stroke.
YOU1000000170_S0000084	I just sort of...
YOU1000000170_S0000086	I asked my manager's manager, what shall we do about this?
YOU1000000170_S0000087	And he said, oh, you got to talk to this and this person in the administrative branch of the institute.
YOU1000000170_S0000088	And I talked to this woman, and she was in charge of all legal affairs, I believe.
YOU1000000170_S0000089	And I said, well, I have written this source code and I would like to release that and I have sort of...
YOU1000000170_S0000090	made up a license that's like identical to the MIT license. I could say MIT releases software under exactly this license.
YOU1000000170_S0000091	and we just put the formal name of our institute in there instead of the regions of the institute.
YOU1000000170_S0000092	She asked me some questions like...
YOU1000000170_S0000094	Did someone pay for this to be developed? And my answer was no. I started this all in my own time.
YOU1000000170_S0000095	And it was for this research project that sort of
YOU1000000170_S0000097	My manager is fine with it.
YOU1000000170_S0000099	And so she said, sure, go ahead. And we did it.
YOU1000000170_S0000101	And that's so that in February 91, we did the first Python release.
YOU1000000170_S0000103	And it felt like, at the time, like an incredible milestone. We needed to post it to Usenet.
YOU1000000170_S0000104	there was this Usenet news group that would receive source code for random free projects.
YOU1000000170_S0000105	I got immediately started getting useful positive feedback from well initially just from random people
YOU1000000170_S0000106	who picked up free software from Usenet.
YOU1000000170_S0000107	We quickly sort of got into a routine of doing new Python releases.
YOU1000000170_S0000108	and every time
YOU1000000170_S0000110	I mean there were the obvious improvements to the language and the library and bug fixes, a very important category of things that were often contributed.
YOU1000000170_S0000111	were ports or porting fixes where people had different architectures, different compilers
YOU1000000170_S0000112	The Unix world was much less homogeneous at the time. There were lots of small Unix vendors that had their own compilers or their own hardware.
YOU1000000170_S0000113	all sorts of things. So the big things that happened
YOU1000000170_S0000114	during say the first half of the 90s was a community of Python users and developers self-organized.
YOU1000000170_S0000115	Then came the invitation to come to the United States for a couple months.
YOU1000000170_S0000117	from NIST, the National Institute for Standards and Technology. So I spent two months there.
