YOU1000000176_S0000001	Cells are the smallest living units of an organism.
YOU1000000176_S0000003	All cells have three things in common, no matter what type of cell they are.
YOU1000000176_S0000005	All cells have a cell membrane which separates the inside of the cell from its environment.
YOU1000000176_S0000007	cytoplasm, which is a jelly-like fluid, and DNA, which is the cell's genetic material.
YOU1000000176_S0000009	There are two broad categories of cells.
YOU1000000176_S0000011	The first category is eukaryotic cells. They have organelles which include the nucleus and other special parts.
YOU1000000176_S0000013	Eukaryotic cells are more advanced, complex cells, such as those found in plants and animals.
YOU1000000176_S0000015	The second category is prokaryotic cells.
YOU1000000176_S0000016	They don't have a nucleus or membrane-enclosed organelles.
YOU1000000176_S0000017	They do have genetic material, but it's not contained within a nucleus.
YOU1000000176_S0000018	Prokaryotic cells are always one-celled or unicellular organisms, such as bacteria.
YOU1000000176_S0000020	So, what are organelles?
YOU1000000176_S0000021	Organelle means little organ.
YOU1000000176_S0000023	Organelles are the specialized parts of a cell that have unique jobs to perform.
YOU1000000176_S0000025	Let's start with the nucleus, the control center of the cell.
YOU1000000176_S0000027	The nucleus contains DNA, or genetic material.
YOU1000000176_S0000028	DNA dictates what the cell is going to do and how it's going to do it.
YOU1000000176_S0000029	Chromatin is the tangled, spread-out form of DNA found inside the nuclear membrane.
YOU1000000176_S0000031	When a cell is ready to divide, DNA condenses into structures known as chromosomes.
YOU1000000176_S0000033	The nucleus also contains a nucleolus.
YOU1000000176_S0000035	which is a structure where ribosomes are made.
YOU1000000176_S0000037	After ribosomes leave the nucleus, they will have the important job of synthesizing or making proteins.
YOU1000000176_S0000039	Outside the nucleus, the ribosomes and the rest of the organelles float around in cytoplasm, which is the jelly-like substance.
YOU1000000176_S0000041	Ribosomes may wander freely within the cytoplasm.
YOU1000000176_S0000043	or attach to the endoplasmic reticulum, sometimes abbreviated as ER.
YOU1000000176_S0000044	There are two types of ER. Rough ER has ribosomes attached to it.
YOU1000000176_S0000045	And Smooth ER doesn't have ribosomes attached to it.
YOU1000000176_S0000047	The endoplasmic reticulum is a membrane-enclosed passageway for transporting materials, such as the proteins synthesized by ribosomes.
YOU1000000176_S0000049	Proteins and other materials emerge from the endoplasmic reticulum in small vesicles.
YOU1000000176_S0000051	where the Golgi apparatus, sometimes called the Golgi body, receives them.
YOU1000000176_S0000053	As proteins move through the Golgi body, they're customized into forms that the cell can use.
YOU1000000176_S0000055	The Golgi body does this by folding the proteins into usable shapes.
YOU1000000176_S0000056	or adding other materials onto them, such as lipids.
YOU1000000176_S0000058	or carbohydrates.
YOU1000000176_S0000060	Vacuoles are sac-like structures that store different materials.
YOU1000000176_S0000061	Here in this plant cell, the central vacuole stores water.
YOU1000000176_S0000063	Going back to the animal cell, you will see an organelle called a lysosome.
YOU1000000176_S0000064	Lysosomes are the garbage collectors that take in damaged or worn-out cell parts.
YOU1000000176_S0000065	They are filled with enzymes that break down this cellular debris.
YOU1000000176_S0000067	The mitochondrion is an organelle that is the powerhouse for both animal and plant cells.
YOU1000000176_S0000069	During a process called cellular respiration, the mitochondria make ATP molecules that provide the energy for all of the cell's activities.
YOU1000000176_S0000071	Cells that need more energy have more mitochondria.
YOU1000000176_S0000073	Meanwhile, the cell maintains its shape through a cytoskeleton.
YOU1000000176_S0000075	The cytoskeleton includes the thread-like microfilaments, which are made of protein.
YOU1000000176_S0000077	and microtubules, which are thin, hollow tubes.
YOU1000000176_S0000079	Some organisms, such as plants, that are photoautotrophic
YOU1000000176_S0000081	meaning they capture sunlight for energy.
YOU1000000176_S0000083	have cells with an organelle called a chloroplast.
YOU1000000176_S0000085	The chloroplast is where photosynthesis happens.
YOU1000000176_S0000087	It's green because it has a green pigment called chlorophyll.
YOU1000000176_S0000089	Plant cells also have a cell wall outside of their cell membranes that shape, support, and protect the plant cell.
YOU1000000176_S0000091	Animal cells never have a cell wall.
YOU1000000176_S0000093	There are many other unique structures that only some cells have.
YOU1000000176_S0000095	Here are just a few. In humans, for example, the respiratory tract is lined with cells that have cilia.
YOU1000000176_S0000096	These are microscopic hair-like projections that can move in waves.
YOU1000000176_S0000097	This feature helps trap inhaled particles in the air and expels them when you cough.
YOU1000000176_S0000099	Another unique feature in some cells is flagella. Some bacteria have flagella.
YOU1000000176_S0000100	A flagellum is like a little tail that can help a cell move or propel itself.
YOU1000000176_S0000102	The only human cell that has a flagellum is a sperm cell.
YOU1000000176_S0000104	In summary, remember...
YOU1000000176_S0000105	Eukaryotic cells are plant and animal cells with a nucleus and membrane-enclosed organelles.
YOU1000000176_S0000107	while prokaryotic cells are unicellular organisms without these things.
YOU1000000176_S0000109	All cells have a cell membrane, cytoplasm, and genetic material.
YOU1000000176_S0000111	And even though only plant cells have chloroplasts, both plant and animal cells have mitochondria.
