YOU1000000188_S0000001	One of the oldest art forms, painting has been around ever since our ancient ancestors first started producing charcoal creations on cave walls.
YOU1000000188_S0000002	While countless generations of artists have left their mark over the millennia, only some artworks have succeeded in transcending time and culture to be revered around the globe.
YOU1000000188_S0000003	Here's a look at the most famous paintings of all time found in museums around the world.
YOU1000000188_S0000005	Number 12. American Gothic. Now hanging up in the Art Institute of Chicago,
YOU1000000188_S0000006	American Gothic is one of the most famous paintings of 20th century rural Americana.
YOU1000000188_S0000007	Grant Wood's defining masterpiece was painted in 1930 and depicts a farmer and his daughter standing in front of what is now known as the American Gothic House.
YOU1000000188_S0000008	Initially, locals and art critics took the somber tones and characters' puritanical clothes as a critique of rural life.
YOU1000000188_S0000009	The onset of the Great Depression, however, saw the painting become associated with the resoluteness and indomitable spirit of the American pioneers.
YOU1000000188_S0000011	Number 11. The Persistence of Memory. One of the greatest and most distinctive works of surrealist art of all time,
YOU1000000188_S0000012	Salvador Dali's The Persistence of Memory really does stand out from the crowd.
YOU1000000188_S0000013	In the 1931 painting, we can see melting pocket watches draped across a bleak landscape.
YOU1000000188_S0000014	The strange scene is widely thought to have been inspired by Albert Einstein's theory of relativity.
YOU1000000188_S0000015	Dali's fantastic creation can be enjoyed at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
YOU1000000188_S0000017	Number 10. The Kiss. Painted between 1907 and 1908 during the height of Gustav Klimt's Golden Period,
YOU1000000188_S0000018	The kiss veritably shimmers and shines before your eyes as gold, silver, and platinum radiate forth from the canvas.
YOU1000000188_S0000019	Influenced by both the arts and crafts and Art Nouveau movements, the painting depicts two gold-clad lovers entwined in an intimate embrace.
YOU1000000188_S0000020	Just one of the many highlights of the Belvedere in Vienna's extensive collection, The Kiss is Klimt's most popular and enthralling work.
YOU1000000188_S0000022	Number 9. Nighthawks. Another of the Art Institute of Chicago's most famous artworks is Nighthawks,
YOU1000000188_S0000023	which was painted by Edward Hopper in 1942. In the oil painting, we can see four people in a diner late at night.
YOU1000000188_S0000024	Light shines out of the brightly lit interior, illuminating the darkness outside through the large glass window.
YOU1000000188_S0000025	While many take it to depict loneliness and isolation, Hopper himself said it alluded more to potential predators in the night.
YOU1000000188_S0000026	One of American art's most popular and parodied paintings, Nighthawks is the most renowned and recognizable of Hopper's artworks.
YOU1000000188_S0000028	Number 8. The Great Wave Off Kanagawa. The most famous painting to come out of Japan, The Great Wave Off Kanagawa was produced by Hokusai,
YOU1000000188_S0000029	using a woodblock print technique sometime between 1829 and 1833.
YOU1000000188_S0000030	The stunning scene, with its vivid blues, sees an enormous wave threatening to engulf three fishing boats.
YOU1000000188_S0000031	As it was developed as part of the artist's 36 Views of Mount Fuji series, the iconic volcano can be spotted in the background.
YOU1000000188_S0000032	Due to the fact that numerous prints were made, original impressions of the Great Wave off Kanagawa can be found in the British Museum and the Metropolitan Museum of Art, among others.
YOU1000000188_S0000034	Number 7. Water Lilies. Consisting of some 250 different paintings,
YOU1000000188_S0000035	Claude Monet's Water Lily series was painted at his home in Giverny between 1896 and 1926.
YOU1000000188_S0000036	The main subject of the paintings is the water lily pond in the back of his garden.
YOU1000000188_S0000037	with various other flowers, a wooden bridge, and a majestic Weeping Willow also featuring.
YOU1000000188_S0000038	One of the great French Impressionists, Claude Monet's paintings are instantly recognizable and are on display in museums around the world.
YOU1000000188_S0000040	Number 6. Nightwatch. Arguably the most famous artwork of the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam,
YOU1000000188_S0000041	The Night Watch is one of the most magnificent paintings to ever emerge from the Dutch Golden Age. Painted in 1642 by Rembrandt van Rijn,
YOU1000000188_S0000042	The enormous canvas portrays a group of civic guards as they head off to practice their shooting.
YOU1000000188_S0000043	For much of its existence, the painting was coated with a dark varnish, which gave the incorrect impression that it depicted a night scene.
YOU1000000188_S0000044	leading to the name Nightwatch. The painting is famed for its dramatic use of light that makes it seem as if the life-size figures are actually moving before us.
YOU1000000188_S0000046	Number 5. The Scream. The Scream is a series of expressionist paintings and prints by Norwegian artist Edvard Munch.
YOU1000000188_S0000047	showing an agonized figure against a bloody red sky. The landscape is the background of Oslofjord, viewed from a hill in Oslo.
YOU1000000188_S0000048	Edvard Munch created several versions of the Scream in various media. The first version was painted in 1893
YOU1000000188_S0000049	and is on display in the National Gallery of Norway. It was stolen in 1994 in a high-profile art theft.
YOU1000000188_S0000050	and recovered several months later. In 2004, another version of the screen was stolen from the Munch Museum, only to be recovered in 2006.
YOU1000000188_S0000052	Number 4. Girl with a Pearl Earring. Although it is often compared with the Mona Lisa,
YOU1000000188_S0000053	Johannes Vermeer's Girl with a Pearl Earring is, in fact, a tronie, not a portrait.
YOU1000000188_S0000054	Thought to have been painted around 1665 by the Dutch master, the captivating artwork depicts an imagined, rather than real girl,
YOU1000000188_S0000055	wearing a blue turban and a sizable, glimmering pearl earring. Tracy Chevalier wrote a historic novel fictionalizing the circumstances of the painting's creation.
YOU1000000188_S0000056	The novel inspired a 2003 film with Scarlett Johansson as Johannes Vermeer's assistant wearing the pearl earring.
YOU1000000188_S0000058	Number 3. The Last Supper. Painted in the 1490s on a refectory wall in a monastery in Milan,
YOU1000000188_S0000059	The Last Supper is one of the most recognizable artworks on Earth.
YOU1000000188_S0000060	While the years have not been kind to the original, the convent still sees people come from all over the world to catch a glimpse of the fabulous fresco.
YOU1000000188_S0000061	The marvelous mural depicts the scene where Jesus Christ tells the 12 apostles sitting to either side of him that one of them will betray him.
YOU1000000188_S0000062	Some writers propose that the person in the painting seated to the left of Jesus is Mary Magdalene rather than John the Apostle.
YOU1000000188_S0000063	This popular theory plays a central role in Dan Brown's novel, The Da Vinci Code.
YOU1000000188_S0000065	Number 2. Starry Night. Vincent van Gogh's defining work, Starry Night, describes the view he could see out of his asylum window
YOU1000000188_S0000066	in Saint-Rmy-de-Provence after he had a breakdown and cut off part of his own ear in 1888.
YOU1000000188_S0000067	The iconic scene shows a swirling night sky punctuated with stars overlooking a still-sleeping village.
YOU1000000188_S0000068	The Dutch post-impressionist painter's stunning creation is now exhibited at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
YOU1000000188_S0000069	and is one of the most valued works in their extensive collection.
YOU1000000188_S0000071	Number 1. Mona Lisa. Widely considered to be the most famous painting in the world,
YOU1000000188_S0000072	The Mona Lisa has delighted onlookers ever since it was painted in the early 1500s by Leonardo da Vinci.
YOU1000000188_S0000073	The painting is named for Lisa del Giocondo, a member of a wealthy family in Florence.
YOU1000000188_S0000074	In 1911, the Mona Lisa was stolen by Louvre employee Vincenzo Perugia, an Italian patriot who believed the Mona Lisa should be returned to Italy.
YOU1000000188_S0000075	After having kept the painting in his apartment for two years, Perugia was finally caught when he attempted to sell it to the Uffizi Gallery in Florence.
YOU1000000188_S0000076	Today, the Mona Lisa hangs again in the Louvre in Paris, where 6 million people see the painting each year.
